(23, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/25/its-hard-to-find-good-advice/', '2014-09-25 00:00:00', 'ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Hard for Start-Up Owners to Find Good Advice', '', '<strong>The New York Times - ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Hard for Start-Up Owners to Find Good Advice</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/25/its-hard-to-find-good-advice/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/25/its-hard-to-find-good-advice/</a> <br/> A lot of people want to tell me how to run <a href="https://posse.com/" target="_blank" >Posse</a>. <br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned a big difference exists between people who enjoy giving advice and those who really care about me and the business. ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s also a big difference between people who think they know how to build a company like ours and those who have actually done it.<br/> I can think of four people who have helped me at Posse and without whom we would have failed. But the new phase we are entering requires a new group of advisers. Here is some of what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m looking for:<br/> <strong>Previous success in similar fields.</strong> Some of the people I enlisted to my early advisory board sounded impressive. TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d held high-level positions at big corporate companies. When we suffered some early start-up bumps, though, they were unprepared. Their knowledge of how a start-up should grow was based on watching Ã¢â‚¬Å“The Social Network.Ã¢â‚¬Â? When we didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t hit it big straight out the gate, they became concerned. I learned to look for people who had built a similar company from the ground up.<br/> <strong>Focus on the granular.</strong> Many people who want to give me advice start with a discussion about the potential size of the exit and how quickly weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be able to get there. This always creates distractions such as attending to the setting up of complicated corporate structures to minimize future tax or setting up big sales deals ahead of building a product. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve found that the best advisers are the ones who drill me on what we have to achieve in the next three months. TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re interested in the granular metrics of the business, how we can improve them and how we can create replicable processes.<br/> Good start-ups are rarely short of willing advisers. Maybe these people are looking for involvement in something that looks like fun; maybe they seek a slice of a big exit. But IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve developed a keen radar for time wasters. I spend as much time as possible getting to know someone before inviting them to become involved. I do thorough reference checks and never give away shares in the company without a vesting period.<br/> When I do find someone whoÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s right, I recognize that the relationship has value. Such people are usually in high demand; theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re giving up other opportunities to take a risk and help me. Time is their most valuable asset, so I make sure IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m prepared for meetings and I check in regularly to make sure that theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re happy with our progress and that they enjoy being involved.', 'What to look for when hiring advisers', 'Previous success in similar fields. Focus on the granular. ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 12, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(24, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 80, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/09/25/the-unexpected-impact-of-changing-my-body-language/', '2014-09-25 00:00:00', 'The unexpected impact of changing my body language', '', '<strong>Posse - The unexpected impact of changing my body language</strong><br/> <a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/09/25/the-unexpected-impact-of-changing-my-body-language/" target="_blank" >http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/09/25/the-unexpected-impact-of-changing-my-body-language/</a> <br/> MIT Media Lab recently released a study of business pitches and sales calls.Ã‚Â  Without hearing any of the content of the meetings, only by reading the presentersÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ interactions, they predicted the outcome of the pitches with 87% accuracy.Ã‚Â  <br/> If the MIT study could predict the success or failure of a pitch with such accuracy then what were they looking for?Ã‚Â  How could I mimic powerful confident body language?Ã‚Â  I found a few simple tricks and the results were astonishing.Ã‚Â  HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what I did:<br/> <strong>Power posing.</strong> <br/> Psychologists have written volumes about the physiological impact of spreading yourself out in a powerful posture.Ã‚Â  In <a href="http://www.ted.com/talks/amy_cuddy_your_body_language_shapes_who_you_are?language=en" target="_blank">Amy CuddyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s brilliant TED talk</a>, she shows that holding our body in expansive high power poses Ã¢â‚¬â€? hands above head in a V shape, shoulders back Ã¢â‚¬â€? for two minutes increases our testosterone by 20% (thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the hormone linked to power and self-esteem) and decreases the stress hormone cortisol by 25%.Ã‚Â  <br/> <strong>Give a strong handshake</strong> <br/> Every meeting starts with a handshake. Ã‚Â I didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t give much thought to the process, but I notice when something is off.Ã‚Â  Sometimes the other person grips too hard, or softly like a fish; sometimes they extend their hand palm facing down, forcing me to take the submissive position.<br/> Recently I did a corporate performance course at NIDA where we practised shaking each otherÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s hands and introducing ourselves by our full name.Ã‚Â  At first I found it awkward to say both my first and last name at the same time as shaking hands, but as I practised I became more comfortable looking into the personÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s eyes and introducing myself.Ã‚Â  It was a powerful exercise.<br/> <strong>Sit at the head of the table</strong> <br/> When I arrive at a pitch meeting, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m usually seated in a boardroom by the receptionist before the investors arrive, so I can decide where I sit at the table.Ã‚Â  I used to sit along the side facing the window, until one day a bunch of investors all commented on where I sat.Ã‚Â  They said they could tell a great deal about entrepreneurs by where they choose to sit in the room.<br/> <strong>Smile and make eye contact at the end of a meeting</strong> <br/> At the end of each meeting I make a conscious effort to make a strong exit.Ã‚Â  I smile, make eye contact, shake hands warmly, and thank them. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve discussed with other entrepreneurs how to leave pitch meetings, and some suggest I should aim to leave the meeting making the other person feel that I donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t care whether I hear back from them or not.Ã‚Â  ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not my style; IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learnt that being authentic is my top priority.Ã‚Â  I have to be myself<br/> Amy CuddyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s research verifies the degree to which physical change generates hormonal change, which in time changes the way we are.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â  I closed the last funding round quickly and have since had much greater success at closing bigger partnership opportunities. Changing my body language changed my behaviour and my behaviour changedÃ‚Â  my confidence and self-perception.Ã‚Â  And that transformed the outcome.', 'How to mimic confident body language', 'Power posing. Give a strong handshake. Sit at the head of the table. Smile and make eye contact at the end of a meeting.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 13, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(25, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/15/the-problem-with-going-into-business-with-a-friend/', '2014-09-15 00:00:00', 'The Problem With Going Into Business With a Friend', '', '<strong>The New York Times - The Problem With Going Into Business With a Friend </strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/15/the-problem-with-going-into-business-with-a-friend/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/15/the-problem-with-going-into-business-with-a-friend/</a> <br/> Within my group of friends are three couples who started technology companies together. Two divorced within the first four years but still run successful businesses as a team Ã¢â‚¬â€? not without some pain, I imagine.<br/> The other couple grew stronger. Melanie Perkins and Cliff Obrecht have been running companies together for the last seven years. Two years ago they founded an online graphic design company, <a href="https://www.canva.com/" title="The company''s website." target="blank">Canva</a>, that is going through a growth explosion, with more than 750,000 users in the first year. They appear to have the perfect partnership Ã¢â‚¬â€? they complement each otherÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s strengths and drive the business forward in tandem.<br/> In an effort to understand why Mel and Cliff have thrived as partners, while so many others, myself included, have struggled, I asked them to share their secrets. HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s MelÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s advice:<br/> <strong>Keep the dream alive.</strong> Mel says she and Cliff have always been clear about what their vision is for the business. Every day they talk about what Canva will look like in five to 10 years. Ã¢â‚¬Å“When you know what you both want to build,Ã¢â‚¬Â? she said, Ã¢â‚¬Å“it makes every little decision easier. TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re all steps toward a shared dream.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br/> <strong>Have unstructured conversations.</strong> Ã¢â‚¬Å“We do lots of walking where weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re free to have crazy conversations and brainstorm ideas,Ã¢â‚¬Â? she said, adding that in business, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easy to have rigid boardroom-type discussions in which everyone is afraid to speak openly for fear of side-tracking the meeting.<br/> <strong>DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t keep battle scars.</strong> Once a decision is made, it becomes a team decision. There is always discussion, but what matters is working toward the shared vision. Ã¢â‚¬Å“We always focus on the best outcome for the business,Ã¢â‚¬Â? she said. Ã¢â‚¬Å“Once something is agreed, the process behind the decision isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t mentioned again.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br/> <strong>Build trust over time.</strong> Mel describes how, during the first few years of working together, they were both involved in everything. Over time, as the company has grown, theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve developed trust and chosen to focus on different areas. Ã¢â‚¬Å“WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re in business together because we believe in each otherÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s skills,Ã¢â‚¬Â? she said. Ã¢â‚¬Å“ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s great that we each get to play to our strengths, because it means we can cover a lot of ground.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br/> <strong>Have the same expectations of each other.</strong> Ã¢â‚¬Å“Both of us have an extremely high work ethic,Ã¢â‚¬Â? Mel said. Ã¢â‚¬Å“WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re focused on the business 24/7, and a common expectation of ourselves and each other provides the foundation that makes everything else possible.', 'The secrets to a healthy partnership with a friend', 'Keep the dream alive. Have unstructured conversations. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t keep battle scars. Build trust over time. Have the same expectations of each other. ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 21, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(26, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 79, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/19/why-i-do-all-of-my-recruiting-through-linkedin/', '2014-08-19 00:00:00', 'Why I Do All My Recruiting Through LinkedIn', '', '<strong>The New York Times - Why I Do All My Recruiting Through LinkedIn</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/19/why-i-do-all-of-my-recruiting-through-linkedin/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/19/why-i-do-all-of-my-recruiting-through-linkedin/</a> <br/> Recruiting the right team member is always difficult. I start off knowing that I need someone to perform a task, and imagine what qualities that person might possess. How, in a sea of people, can I find my ideal candidate?<br/> Earlier this year I signed up to <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/16/business/smallbusiness/online-recruiting-efforts-gain-ground.html" target="_blank" >LinkedInÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Recruiter service</a>. For $2,200 per quarter, I can run detailed searches on exactly the type of candidates IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m looking for and then approach them en masse. I can search by location, previous and current job titles, previous employers, which universities they attended and how long theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve been in their current jobs.<br/> As a small-business owner, I recognize that building the right team is crucial. We only have room for A-plus players, who will always be in good positions and may require quite a bit of convincing to leave. LinkedIn gives us access to the passive job hunter market that used to be available only through expensive recruiters, and it helps us seek out top quality candidates from within other companies.<br/> There is one catch. If IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m trying to poach the best people from our competitors, I can be sure that theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re trying to steal my best people, too. Once we turned down an acquisition offer from a competitor only to have the company approach all of our staff members individually on LinkedIn.<br/> This is almost impossible to prevent, but IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve come up with a couple of strategies that may help. First, if your business is small, I see little benefit in setting up a LinkedIn page for it. Doing so just enables competitors to find and attack all your staff members at once.<br/> Second, you can try to discourage your staffers from using the platform Ã¢â‚¬â€œ although this is nearly impossible. When we relocated team members from Sydney to New York, a recruiter suggested that I ask our engineers not to change their location on LinkedIn because it would highlight them as fresh meat for the hungry New York recruiters.', 'How Linkedin can help with your recruitment', 'LinkedIn gives us access to the passive job hunter market that used to be available only through expensive recruiters, and it helps us seek out top quality candidates from within other companies.  ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 10, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(27, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 78, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/07/letting-someone-go-with-dignity/', '2014-08-07 00:00:00', 'Letting Someone Go With Dignity', '', '<strong>The New York Times - Letting Someone Go With Dignity</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/07/letting-someone-go-with-dignity/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/07/letting-someone-go-with-dignity/</a> <br/> Obviously, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s no fun to get fired. But itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s also no fun to be the one doing the firing.<br/> I have heard it said that the stress of terminating someoneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s employment can reduce your lifespan. I certainly know that IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve awakened in a sweat the night before I have to have Ã¢â‚¬Å“the conversationÃ¢â‚¬Â? with someone. Or worse, I have put off the conversation and let the frustration and anticipation build for months.<br/> Letting someone go is never an easy process, but here is some of what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned.<br/> <strong>Let them save face.</strong> <br/> Whenever I sit down with people, I make it as obvious as I can whatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about to come. I ask them how they think their role is working out. I never make it about their personal contribution; itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s always about the role and how it fits into the organization. I lead them toward seeing that, in a small company like ours, their role isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t quite what we need. <br/> You may think itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s dishonest not to be upfront and tell them exactly why they havenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t worked out. But by the time we reach this point, we will already have had several conversations about whatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not working and how they can improve. This conversation is about making a tough moment easier and helping ensure they have the confidence to move on with their life.<br/> <strong>DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t procrastinate. </strong> <br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve discovered that when I think someone wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work out, they wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t. I can recognize when IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made a recruitment mistake within the first three months, and IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll let them go within a week of the realization. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve found that the longer I leave it, the more they bond with the team and the worse the impact. It gives the person and the company the opportunity to move on.<br/> <strong>Stick to any agreements. When in doubt, be generous.</strong> <br/> All of our employment agreements have probationary periods of three months. If the person is let go in that time, we pay one weekÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s notice. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s important that there be no doubt about what the person should be paid. If thereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s ever a question, I err on the generous side. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not good to look stingy, and IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned that itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s important to do whatever I can to make the person leaving as happy as possible.<br/> <strong>Be clear about what happens next and help them as much as you can.</strong> <br/> At the end of our conversation, I lay out the next steps. TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll usually agree to go back to the office and hand over anything important to another team member, and we agree on how to explain the departure. <br/> We then talk about their plan to find another job. I ask if theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d like introductions to my contacts, and I offer to write them a glowing (but honest) reference. <br/> <strong>Announce it to the team together and let them say goodbye.</strong> <br/> We go back to the office and call the team together for the announcement. We almost always paint it as the employeeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s decision. I just stand there while the person explains. I thank them for their contributions, and we all go out for a drink. The drinks are usually a bit awkward, but itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s important to let the remaining team members grieve.', 'The process of letting someone go', 'Let them save face. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t procrastinate. Stick to any agreements. When in doubt, be generous. Be clear about what happens next and help them as much as you can. Announce it to the team together and let them say goodbye.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 11, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(28, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/how-im-trying-to-manage-my-online-brand/', '2014-07-16 00:00:00', 'How IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m Trying to Manage My Online Brand', '', '<strong>The New York Times - How IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m Trying to Manage My Online Brand</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/how-im-trying-to-manage-my-online-brand/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/how-im-trying-to-manage-my-online-brand/</a> <br/> I met recently with a large Silicon Valley venture fund. My company is not raising money at the moment, but the fund had heard about <a href="https://posse.com/" target="_blank" >Posse</a> and reached out to me online. Since I was in town anyway, I decided to meet with the fundÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s investors and build a relationship. <br/> Two senior executives from the other side of the world knew my lifeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s story and didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t mind reciting it. I felt naked.<br/> Knowing that such web searches before meetings would become more common, I decided to take control of my online brand. HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve done.<br/> <strong>1. Think about why.</strong> <br/> If your only concern is that people will conduct searches on you before meetings, you may just need to create a LinkedIn profile so they will find something that you want them to see.<br/> For me, though, the purpose of building an online brand was bigger. I wanted to raise the profile of my company in order to win clients, attract users and raise capital.<br/> <strong>2. Define your brand.</strong> <br/> As entrepreneurs we create brand values for our companies but often not for ourselves. By writing down my values, I defined my personal brand and made it easier to make sure that my values are projected across everything I do online. This included the way my own blog is written, the types of other publications I write for and what I post in social media. As with a company brand, I try to ensure that the message is consistent.<br/> <strong>3. Understand that social networks are the new calling cards.</strong> <br/> If you are on social media, people are going to check out your profiles. LinkedIn, Facebook, Twitter and Instagram will come up first, often in that order.<br/> <strong>4. Pay attention to what comes up first in Google.</strong> <br/> One reason to write a blog with your name in the URL is that itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s likely to pop up first on any Google search. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s also helpful to have a name that isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t common. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m lucky with my first name, which has a less common spelling, and my blog ranks high if you search Ã¢â‚¬Å“Rebekah Campbell.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br/> If there were bad things written about me online (there arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t), I would try to create new listings that would rank highly in Google and push the old links to the second page of search results. If you search your own name and nothing comes up, or if an early link displays something youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d prefer to keep under wraps, consider creating a LinkedIn page. It always surprises me when I see politicians who have problem headings on page one of their Google results donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t have a LinkedIn profile.', 'How to take control of your online brand', 'Think about why. Define your brand. Understand that social networks are the new calling cards. Pay attention to what comes up first in Google.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 10, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(29, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/02/how-i-learned-to-build-and-appreciate-a-good-board/', '2014-07-02 00:00:00', 'How I Learned to Build and Appreciate a Good Board', '', '<strong>The New York Times - How I Learned to Build and Appreciate a Good Board</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/02/how-i-learned-to-build-and-appreciate-a-good-board/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/02/how-i-learned-to-build-and-appreciate-a-good-board/</a> <br/> When I started <a href="https://posse.com/" target="_blank" >Posse</a>, I knew nothing about company boards or their value. The family lawyer who helped establish our companies suggested that I create a board before I raised our first investment round and that I try to find some high profile people to join it. His objective was to make the team slide in my presentation deck look as impressive as possible. Off I went to enlist some big name folks to join my not-yet-established company.<br/> Putting the right group together is challenging. Three years in, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m on my third lineup, after experiencing the best and worst of what boards can do. Here are five things IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned the hard way.<br/> <strong>Make sure your directors have the right experience</strong>.<br/> Many people imagine that a board should consist of gray-haired gentlemen with high profiles in the business community along with friends who will invest in the business. My original board sounded impressive, but many were impressive in the wrong industries. They had no experience with the challenges a start-up like ours might face. So I received bad advice which led us to hire the wrong team and spend too much too quickly. <br/> <strong>Make sure you invite people you like and trust.</strong> <br/> Directors have a power. They decide who leads the company, what deals to do and when to exit, so you must all share the same vision. You must know they will do the right thing, that they will stick around and support you when you hit tough times. <br/> I spent a lot of time with each of our existing directors before I asked them to join. I knew I could trust them to act in the best interests of the company and to stick it out. <br/> <strong>Keep the numbers small.</strong> <br/> We have four directors on our current board, including me, and one regular observer who acts like a director but doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t vote. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a tight group: Everyone knows the othersÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ strengths; everyone is committed to making Posse a hit. For me, the benefit of having a small board is that I can spend time with each person regularly. ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s no delay when we need to make an important decision. Everyone is in touch with whatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s happening and can contribute.<br/> <strong>Set expectations up front.</strong> <br/> ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easy to procrastinate when finalizing deals with advisers and directors. Everyone is there to be helpful, and at the start, it doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t seem worth negotiating to pay them a share of nothing. The problems kick in after a few months when things start going well and you realize that you and they have different expectations about payment. <br/> You must determine what you expect of directors. How will they help with fund-raising, strategy, introductions and the like? If appropriate, you might want to agree on how much time they will commit Ã¢â‚¬â€? although when you have the right people on board itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s likely theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll bug you with ideas and suggestions for how they can help. Although these conversations can be awkward at the beginning, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve found that the directors who are best at negotiating their own deals are the ones who are most helpful when I am negotiating deals for Posse.<br/> <strong>Be transparent and organized. </strong> <br/> Your board should be the one group of people with whom you can be completely transparent. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s their job to help you work through challenges; they must understand those challenges if theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re going to add value. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve also found that board meetings are much more effective when IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve put time into considering the agenda and have written a presentation to talk through.<br/> The names on our board are impressive but thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not why theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re there. A top-notch board of great people with relevant experience and a shared vision has made my founderÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s journey easier and more fun.', 'How to build the right group of board', 'Make sure your directors have the right experience. Make sure you invite people you like and trust. Keep the numbers small. Set expectations up front. Be transparent and organized. ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 12, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(30, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/05/what-im-looking-for-in-a-new-partner/', '2014-06-05 00:00:00', 'What IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m Looking for in a New Partner', '', '<strong>The New York Times - What IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m Looking for in a New Partner</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/05/what-im-looking-for-in-a-new-partner/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/05/what-im-looking-for-in-a-new-partner/</a> <br/> Merging with an existing company means there will be a second founder. As I consider entering another business partnership, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m setting up processes to ensure I donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t make the wrong decision. HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s what went wrong for me the first time Ã¢â‚¬â€? and what I am looking for this time.<br/> <strong>Cultural fit.</strong> <br/> In my music business, my co-founder and I discussed our shared vision of building an international company but had different ideas about the level of work involved. I worked around the clock; he liked to surf in the morning and had a personal work-life balance rule that precluded staying in the office after 5 p.m.<br/> ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s frustrating to work harder than a partner who shares equally in the success of the business. This time, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll make sure that my co-founder and I have the same expectations for what we want to achieve and how weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll get there.<br/> <strong>Similar aptitudes and complementary skills.</strong> <br/> Two heads are better than one Ã¢â‚¬â€œ but only if the co-founder is smart and views problems from a different perspective. My previous co-founder used to refer every decision to me; that way, he never had to say no to anyone. It was always Ã¢â‚¬Å“RebekahÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s decisionÃ¢â‚¬Â? not to give employees what they wanted. Along with being annoying, this didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work because no one challenged me.<br/> I also think it would help to have a co-founder with complementary skills. For example, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m a strong external marketer and sales person. It would be ideal to find a partner who is better at operations and finances.<br/> <strong>Similar approach to resolving problems.</strong> <br/> One reasons start-ups fail is because the founders fall out. They often start out as friends, and itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s great when things go well. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s when times get tough, which they almost always do, that partners squabble. They blame each other. One isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t as smart, makes a wrong call or doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t put in the work. This kills confidence with both the investors and the team, and it can even kill the business. Founder divorce has to be one of the most painful and draining experiences you can go through.<br/> This time, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll make sure IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m comfortable that my co-founder and I will be able to work through problems proactively. There will be times when we disagree, but we will have a process in place to resolve these situations.<br/> Finding the right business partner is like finding the right life partner. You want to make sure you really know the person and how you work together before you make it legal.', 'Finding the right busines partner', 'Cultural fit. Similar aptitudes and complementary skills. Similar approach to resolving problems.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 12, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(31, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 79, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/how-i-learned-to-recruit-an-a-team/', '2014-05-29 00:00:00', 'How I Learned to Recruit an A-Plus Team', '', '<strong>The New York Times - How I Learned to Recruit an A-Plus Team</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/how-i-learned-to-recruit-an-a-team/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/how-i-learned-to-recruit-an-a-team/</a> <br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve always struggled to hire the right people. Often, candidates who respond well during the interview process turn out to be disappointing after they start. Within two weeks, I know IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made a mistake.<br/> When I started <a href="https://posse.com/" target="_blank" >Posse</a>, I hired a team of 12 in the first year and appointed five directors. I remember looking around the table at our Christmas lunch a year later and realizing that every single person that IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d hired in those first 12 months had left, including four of the directors. So, I had a problem: Either I was terrible at picking people, or I wasnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢tÃ‚Â  managing them successfully after they started.<br/> My new board started to ask questions. I attended a couple of management courses and hired a leadership coach. I learned several things I could do to improve our recruitment process and how I worked with new employees in their first few weeks. I also learned that even the best managers claim at best an 80 percent success rate. No matter how good I become, at least one in five new hires are not going to work out. <br/> Recently weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve been scaling up again, and IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve hired a bunch of new people. All of the concepts I learned during my training have helped, and our group is strong, but until a few weeks ago, I felt uneasy. Had I nailed it this time? An ambitious start-up like ours will only succeed with anÃ‚Â A-plus team. Steve Jobs famously said, Ã¢â‚¬Å“A small team of A-plus players can run circles around a giant team of B and C players.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve spent a lot of time analyzing the situation, trying to determine the factors that distinguish an A-plus employee from a B-plus employee. Mr. Jobs spoke about trusting your gut Ã¢â‚¬â€œ how you feel when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re with the person. This may be great advice if you have his gut, but it doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work for me. I tend to like everyone, and that makes it tougher.<br/> We have some excellent players on our team. I look around my office as I write this blog, and it occurs to me that they all share three traits: drive, cultural fit and raw intelligence. These will be the things I look for as I continue to build my team.<br/> <strong>Drive: </strong>What is their personal ambition and drive, and are they happy with their achievements at Posse? What do they want? The best employees arrive at the office full of ideas to share: They have been thinking about Posse at night and canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t wait to put their ideas into action. By contrast, B players just put in the hours. They smile but drop comments indicating that they are looking forward to Friday, or that Monday is not their favorite day of the week. Personally, I love Monday mornings Ã¢â‚¬â€œ I have a full week to make stuff happen before we have to stop for the weekend.<br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve found that one good way of assessing a prospective employeeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s drive is to review their careers. One of the people I hired recently had done a lot of volunteer work in politics. It was obvious that this was her passion. She interviewed well, and I hired her. But after she started, all she talked about was politics. Posse was just a job to earn money; she could never be A-plus. An A-plus player is likely to have passions outside work, but not passions theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d rather be doing than being on the team at Posse.<br/> <strong>Cultural fit: </strong>A thriving team of A-plus players feels amazing, everyone bursting with ideas and enthusiasm. The energy is electric. But it takes only one negative person Ã¢â‚¬â€? someone who doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe in or care about the vision Ã¢â‚¬â€? to bring down everyone else. It goes back to what Mr. Jobs said about trusting your gut. How does the person make you feel? The problem is, I find it hard to know how I feel about someone until IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve spent quite a lot of time with them. I fall in love with everyone quickly but then fall out of love just as fast.<br/> Recently, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve narrowed the field of candidates to two or three people that I like and then invited them to meet the rest of the team. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve done this five times in the last year, and twice the team rejected all of the candidates. Once, I overrode the team Ã¢â‚¬â€? I was sure he was the right person, and we really needed to fill the position.<br/> Within a month, I knew I had made a mistake. In team brainstorming sessions, where everyone would throw out crazy ideas, heÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d sit in the corner and criticize. I know that teams need all types to work effectively, but negativity is a killer. Some people told me privately that they didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t feel comfortable sharing ideas in a group format any more; they were afraid heÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d criticize them.<br/> <strong>Raw intelligence or talent: </strong>In the past, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve considered experience and connections when hiring. In fact, these are not relevant to a small ambitious business like ours; experience is often a bad thing. On several occasions, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve hired people from big-name companies, and they arrived at Posse expecting that things would work in a similar fashion.<br/> Now, I can identify talent and intelligence during the interview process. One of the best people who recently joined our team was employed at a consulting company with which we were working. I had seen the quality of her work over a couple of months and knew she was a superstar. The other two great hires weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made have been previous colleagues of existing team members. If I donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know the person, then I ask lots of questions during the interview process in which the candidate must think in order to come up with a creative answer. I also ask pure logic questions just to get a sense of how they process information and generate solutions.<br/> In the past, I have not had a lot of success picking the best talent, but I have learned to recognize stars and hold onto them once theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re in. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve also learned to let go of mistakes quickly. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m happy to report that our current team is pumping, which is good. We have major plans ahead.', 'Things to look for when building a team', 'Drive. Cultural fit. Raw intelligence or talent', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 9, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(32, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 42, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/the-first-meeting-was-fabulous-why-isnt-my-phone-ringing/', '2014-05-06 00:00:00', 'The First Meeting Was Fabulous. Why IsnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t My Phone Ringing?', '', '<strong>The New York Times - The First Meeting Was Fabulous. Why IsnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t My Phone Ringing?</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/the-first-meeting-was-fabulous-why-isnt-my-phone-ringing/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/the-first-meeting-was-fabulous-why-isnt-my-phone-ringing/</a> <br/> I believe IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m a good salesperson. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m good at getting meetings with the right people and getting them excited, but I suffer from recurring attacks of what I call First Meeting Syndrome. My first meeting is red hot, but I struggle to get a follow-up; time passes and the deal goes cold. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m a great door-opener, but IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m not so good at closing the deal.<br/> Over the past year, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve wondered: What am I doing wrong? How come IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m so good at initial meetings but so lousy at following through? I asked mentors for advice, and I tracked folks who are killer salespeople in order to learn what their magic was at meetings.<br/> Here are a few of the things I learned:<br/> <strong>Get the other company to do the talking.</strong> <br/> I used to spend a lot of time preparing for meetings. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d research the company, come up with a range of suggestions and try to impress them with my presentation. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d talk for 80 percent of the meeting.<br/> One mentor suggested that I make my first meeting all about them. Rather than arriving with a fully developed proposal, spend most of the time asking about their strategy. Then describe what Posse does and try to generate partnership ideas together.<br/> <strong>ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s all about the person.</strong> <br/> When I planned my presentation, I thought it through as though I were pitching to Visa, Coke or the like, and structured it according to my expectations of what Coke wanted to achieve. But in reality, there is no such thing as pitching to a company; I can only pitch to one or two people who happen to work for that company. I have to sell to <em>them</em>.<br/> <strong>Deal with the most senior person.</strong> <br/> Senior executives are generally more prepared to take a risk while their juniors tend to worry about making mistakes.<br/> <strong>Leave a written presentation.</strong> <br/> It is easier to visualize a product when thereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a tangible booklet to flip though. I also learned that after the meetings people would pass the presentation around to colleagues. And many of the people I meet with are in their 50s or older and may be more comfortable with paper presentations.<br/> <strong>Create time pressure. </strong> <br/> Daily deal sites like Groupon and Living Social were successful initially because of the scarcity principle, the concept that consumers want now what they fear may not be available tomorrow. The same is true if you are trying to sell some kind of deal or partnership. People are unlikely to say yes today if they think can say yes next week.<br/> <strong>Be persistent. </strong> <br/> After a meeting, I used to send a follow-up email, but many of the people I meet with are too busy to respond to nonurgent emails from start-ups; they hit delete and consign my missive to the bit bucket. Now, I go straight to the phone. I feel uncomfortable making the call, but when I reach people, theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re always pleasant.<br/> As the founder of a tiny start-up, I learned that I needed all of these tricks to close my media partnership deal. I worked on the most senior person in the organization, asked executives about their strategy, let them come up with the ideas, showed how the project would make them look innovative and reduced the level of risk by guaranteeing that I would make sure it succeeded.', 'Tips in closing deals', 'Get the other company to do the talking. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s all about the person. Deal with the most senior person. Leave a written presentation. Create time pressure. Be persistent. ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 11, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(33, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/finding-the-right-early-customers-for-a-start-up/', '2014-04-29 00:00:00', 'Finding the Right Early Customers for a Start-Up', '', '<strong>The New York Times - Finding the Right Early Customers for a Start-Up</strong><br/> <a href="http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/finding-the-right-early-customers-for-a-start-up/" target="_blank" >http://boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/finding-the-right-early-customers-for-a-start-up/</a> <br>Before starting my technology company, <a href="https://posse.com/" target="_blank" >Posse</a>, I built a music management company in Australia. With each new artist, we would start from scratch with no profile, no fan base and no money to spend on marketing. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d work out how to develop a brand and how to reach the right community of early adopters.<br/> Most bands give up before they reach 10,000 fans. After a while, I learned that if I developed a fan base of 10,000 and the music appealed to a wide market, the next several hundred thousand fans were relatively easy to come by. <br/> Here are a few tricks I learned building fan bases for bands that I also used to build a community for Posse: <br/> <strong>DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t underestimate the value of passionate fans.</strong> <br/> The best way to experience a new band is in a small venue crammed with screaming fans. These taste makers become the first to discover a new talent, and they will later say, Ã¢â‚¬Å“I saw them at X with 200 other people, and now theyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re playing stadiums.Ã¢â‚¬Â? <br/> PosseÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s strategy for building that initial base involves a student adviser program. We advertise on free student job boards all over the world, seeking advisers to intern from home. They commit to completing two activities a week during a four-week program, and in exchange we provide them with a letter for their rÃƒÂ©sumÃƒÂ©.<br/> The activities include running user-experience tests, writing up product feedback and suggestions, recruiting friends to join Posse, promoting Posse to retailers in their area with stickers for the store windows, and writing blog posts about the best places in their town. We run the program every four weeks and aim to sign up 150 advisers.<br/> <strong>Leverage other peopleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s fan bases.</strong> <br/> In music, the easiest way to build a fan base is by landing a support slot with a major artist. When the band performs as an opening act, thousands of music lovers get to see them.<br/> At Posse, we feature high-profile people on our blog in the hope that we will attract their followers. We publish two or three blog posts every day from celebrities, highlighting their lists of favorite spots to eat, drink and shop in their hometowns. <br/> Our community manager Chris writes up the blogs and encourages our featured celebrities to share them on Facebook and Twitter, which they usually do, often to hundreds of thousands of followers. He also reaches out to each of the featured stores, and they all post and tweet the link. Everyone is looking for content to post on social media, and the blog posts generate a huge amount of traffic for Posse.<br/> <strong>Make sure the product has natural momentum.</strong> <br/> When I started Posse, I thought our initial version of the product was great Ã¢â‚¬â€? but it didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t gain momentum. People didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t share it with friends, and users would drop off right after signing up. I remembered my discovery from music management: If people donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t love the product, and it doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t grow organically, no amount of marketing will save it. I have spent two years improving Posse, and itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s now reached a monthly growth rate in new users of 15 percent, without marketing. WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re almost at the point where IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be confident enough to start spending marketing money.<br/> ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a graveyard for businesses that fail to commit the time and effort to build a community of fans. Many spend a fortune on marketing too early Ã¢â‚¬â€œ before the product has gained natural momentum and before there are committed customers. No one wants to watch a band in an empty room. Finding the right first 10,000 fans takes careful thought, hard work and patience.', 'Tricks for building fan bases', 'DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t underestimate the value of passionate fans. Leverage other peopleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s fan bases. Make sure the product has natural momentum.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 11, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(34, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/04/29/what-two-years-of-pitching-for-investment-has-taught-me/', '2014-04-29 00:00:00', 'What two years of pitching for investment has taught me', '', '<strong>Posse - What two years of pitching for investment has taught me</strong><br/> <a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/04/29/what-two-years-of-pitching-for-investment-has-taught-me/" target="_blank" >http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/04/29/what-two-years-of-pitching-for-investment-has-taught-me/</a> <br/> This last fortnight I had been out on the fundraising trail, for weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d just opened our third and biggest round yet.Ã‚Â  I had met with a new class of investors and could not afford the same level of knockbacks.Ã‚Â  I had to improve my strike rate.<br/> So I visited a consultancy group.Ã‚Â  They forced me to re-write my deck from scratch and re-think my style.Ã‚Â  Yet, as I made their suggested changes, I discovered that I still had much to learn.Ã‚Â  If I hoped to raise that capital, I had to improve.<br/> Here are a few of my changes:<br/> <strong>Put all the facts upfront.</strong> <br/> I used to open my presentation with an engaging story to captivate my listener.Ã‚Â  Then IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d take the investor on a journey through our product, aided by a stack of pretty screen shots, and then hit them at the end with our impressive growth statistics and team, aiming to finish on a high.Ã‚Â  <br/> This had to change.Ã‚Â  Now, I open with the hard-hitting stuff.Ã‚Â  Key investors, team members and growth statistics are on the first slide, for my task is to establish our credibility in the first sixty seconds.Ã‚Â  I spend less time telling my audience about the product and how it works, more time showing it working by demonstrating actual applications.<br/> <strong>Cover everything in the presentation.</strong> <br/> Two years ago, I focused on entertaining stuff like how I bought the domain name or came up with the idea.Ã‚Â  I seldom addressed tough issues in my presentation, but received them later in questions such as:Ã‚Â  Ã¢â‚¬ËœHow much have you spent so far?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢ Ã¢â‚¬ËœWhat have you spent that on?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢ Ã¢â‚¬ËœWho owns what shares in the company?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢ and, Ã¢â‚¬ËœWhen will you break even?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢<br/> I do now.Ã‚Â  My pitch deck features slides that address every tricky question, and I go through each one in detail.Ã‚Â  IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve worked at making the presentation more serious, transparent and, I think, effective.<br/> <strong>Momentum, momentum, momentum</strong> <br/> The only way to close an investment round is with momentum.Ã‚Â  In my early pitches, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d slightly inflate our numbers and talk about deals that were incomplete in order to sound more impressive.Ã‚Â  <br/> This approach has a damaging effect.Ã‚Â  Once a deal starts rolling, investors want to know how many users we have this week, and the next, and the next.Ã‚Â  They donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t care how many we started with Ã¢â‚¬â€œ what matters is momentum.<br/> <strong>Personal style</strong> <br/> I have always been comfortable with my natural style.Ã‚Â  Recently, however, I have made some slight adjustments in order to come across as more serious.Ã‚Â  <br/> I have made slight changes to what I wear, my vocal tone, the amount of eye contact I make, and my body language.Ã‚Â  IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve noticed that subtle body language adjustments can greatly change my level of confidence and change the way I interact with listeners through my delivery.Ã‚Â  I read a recent study by MIT Labs, by the end of the study, they could identify whether the presenter would make a successful sale without listening to the dialogue at all.Ã‚Â  The predictions, made by watching the presenterÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s body language, were 85% accurate.', 'The changes you have to make when pitching for funding', 'Put all the facts upfront. Cover everything in the presentation. Momentum. Personal style.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 12, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0);
