(35, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/01/14/the-end-of-stress/', '2014-01-14 00:00:00', 'The end of stress', '', '<strong>Posse - The end of stress</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/01/14/the-end-of-stress/" target= "_blank" >http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2014/01/14/the-end-of-stress/</a> <br>Can we access the key causes of stress?&nbsp; Instead of managing them, would it be possible to remove them from life altogether? &nbsp;Obviously, I&rsquo;m not a doctor or psychologist.&nbsp; But as I sit at the kitchen table of my parent&rsquo;s house on holiday, these are my thoughts.<br><strong>Control:</strong> <br>A lot of my stress comes from feeling out of control. Chris is stressed because he can&rsquo;t control his co-worker and her vindictive behaviour. &nbsp;He lies awake fretting about what she&rsquo;s going to do next.<br>Control is one area where we entrepreneurs have it much better. &nbsp;Sure, it&rsquo;s stressful when we have to rely on other people, but there&rsquo;s usually something we can do about it. &nbsp;The next day we can scope out new investors or cut costs. &nbsp;We&rsquo;re never at the mercy of someone else. &nbsp;Chris feels as if he&rsquo;s out of control but he&rsquo;s a talented, hard working guy; he could always quit and find another job. &nbsp;To remove &lsquo;control&rsquo; as a stress factor I must remember that I&rsquo;m ultimately in control.&nbsp;<br><strong>Expectation:</strong> <br>Another major cause of stress comes from worrying that things won&rsquo;t work out the way I&rsquo;d hoped. &nbsp;Much of the pain that I experience, lying in bed waiting on an investor to email, comes from a future I&rsquo;ve created in my head &ndash; a future where our investment round closes smoothly &ndash; a future that may not exist. &nbsp;This feeling is similar to grief. &nbsp;When I suffered the loss of someone very close to me, much of the pain was for the loss of a future I&rsquo;d imagined. &nbsp;I think it&rsquo;s healthy to hope for an investment round to close or for a product to take off, to plan and work towards those goals. &nbsp;But I also think it&rsquo;s important to remember that the future hasn&rsquo;t arrived.&nbsp; The only thing that&rsquo;s for sure is now.<br><strong>Perception:</strong> <br>Last year, I wrote <a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/06/18/on-jealousy/" target="_blank" title="On jealousy">a post about professional jealously</a>. &nbsp;I was flooded with emails and Facebook messages, so obviously it struck a chord with many people. &nbsp;I find it difficult to avoid comparing myself to other people or worry about what others think of me. &nbsp;I know this is pointless but it&rsquo;s very hard to stop. &nbsp;&nbsp;When I compare myself to others, it always leaves me thinking that something&rsquo;s wrong with me, which knocks my self-confidence. &nbsp;And it&rsquo;s crazy to worry about what others think of me because no one actually cares much about what I&rsquo;m doing. &nbsp;Everyone has their own stuff going on. &nbsp;The world is big and I am small.<br><strong>Self esteem: &nbsp;</strong> <br>Often, people who seem the most confident externally (like entrepreneurs) are, behind it all, the least. &nbsp;They just act confident to compensate for that voice inside their head that tells them they&rsquo;re not good enough. &nbsp;Self-esteem and self-confidence &ndash; that&rsquo;s a whole other issue.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ll write about that later. &nbsp;I do believe that, through cultivating a deep sense of self-belief, I could kill stress entirely.<br>Stress is an invisible energy drain; it wears us down. &nbsp;It doesn&rsquo;t matter if you&rsquo;re a struggling startup entrepreneur like me or you have a corporate job like Chris.&nbsp; We all suffer. &nbsp;With so much opportunity out there in the world, I want all the energy I can have. &nbsp;This year, rather than work on ways to manage stress, I&rsquo;m going to address its root causes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Then I&rsquo;ll be able to relax my stress-reducing routines and have a bit more fun as well.', 'End the root causes of stress', 'Control. Expectation. Perception. Self esteem.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 12, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(36, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/11/12/can-startups-create-a-culture-that-competes-with-google/', '2013-11-12 00:00:00', 'Can startups create a culture that competes with Google?', '', '<strong>Posse - Can startups create a culture that competes with Google?</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/11/12/can-startups-create-a-culture-that-competes-with-google/" target= "_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/11/12/can-startups-create-a-culture-that-competes-with-google/</a> <br>I came back in August, ultimately successful at raising both money and our profile in the US.&nbsp; I felt more positive than ever about our chances, and was excited to return, working directly with our team again.&nbsp; When I arrived at the office I found a tired, miserable group.&nbsp; People were coming in late, leaving early and productivity was low.&nbsp; My next challenge was to rebuild our company culture.&nbsp; Here are five things I did to shake things up.<br><strong>1. Productivity &amp; Community. &nbsp;</strong> <br>The first issue I had to address was low team morale and lack of productivity.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve found that one of the best ways to lift morale immediately when you&rsquo;re in a slump is &ndash; communicate with everyone every day. &nbsp; This enables you to reinforce the company&rsquo;s objectives, ensure that everyone&rsquo;s ideas and concerns are heard, and create transparency. <br><strong>2. Location.</strong> <br>I worked in the garage office for six weeks and hated it.&nbsp;I started looking for new premises as soon as I returned to Australia, and with a bit of effort found an awesome spot on Oxford St, in the heart of Sydney&rsquo;s trendy shopping and cafe district. It&rsquo;s a delight to arrive at work in the morning, and I often find myself working late into the evening with several members of the team.&nbsp; People want to stay behind and work because it&rsquo;s an awesome place to be.<br><strong>3. Offsite events.</strong> <br>Every 3 &ndash; 6 months we hold a company offsite, renting a house in the country and spending a couple of days discussing our progress and planning for the future.&nbsp; A few weeks ago, we went to the Blue Mountains and were there when the fires broke out!&nbsp; We spent two days reviewing our company values and user personas, brainstorming user stories, featuring ideas for the product, and prioritising the next few months of marketing and development.&nbsp; We had a great time together and returned to work excited about the future.<br><strong>4. Progress. &nbsp;</strong> <br>No matter how great your culture may be, a smart team only remains motivated if they feel they&rsquo;re making progress.&nbsp; Nothing is more disheartening than slogging it out on site, then marketing a product that people don&rsquo;t use.&nbsp; <br><strong>5. Celebrating wins.</strong> <br>Every start-up has a mile-long list of desired achievements.&nbsp; Every time we finish something, I&rsquo;ve mentally moved on to other things that haven&rsquo;t yet been completed.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s hard to stop and celebrate victories, but it&rsquo;s incredibly important for team morale.&nbsp; <br>The dictionary definition of company culture is:&nbsp; &lsquo;The behaviour of humans who are part of an organization and the meanings that the people attach to their actions.&rsquo; I think culture determines how excited team members are to come into work in the morning.&nbsp; <br>Culture can&rsquo;t be dictated.&nbsp; For instance, I&rsquo;ve learned that mandating work hours doesn&rsquo;t lift productivity but inviting everyone to a team breakfast does. Startups can&rsquo;t afford the time or money to build culture in the same way as Google.&nbsp; We have to be creative, using what attracts people to work at a startup in the first place.&nbsp; People join startups because they want to make an impact, for their ideas to be heard.&nbsp; They want to be a part of building something they believe in, to sense rapid progress and be part of a tight team that has fun and respects each other.&nbsp; None of this costs much money &ndash; just a bit of effort and creative thinking.', 'Building a company culture', 'Productivity & Community. Location. Offsite events. Progress. Celebrating wins.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 13, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(37, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 79, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/09/24/what-ive-learnt-about-outsourcing-so-far/', '2013-09-24 00:00:00', 'What IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learnt about outsourcing so far', '', '<strong>Posse - What I&rsquo;ve learnt about outsourcing so far</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/09/24/what-ive-learnt-about-outsourcing-so-far/" target= "_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/09/24/what-ive-learnt-about-outsourcing-so-far/</a> <br>Startups with limited resources may be tempted into outsourcing to cheaper places.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;ve heard horror stories of entrepreneurs who spent a fortune building an idea in India only to discover a rat&rsquo;s nest of badly written code that doesn&rsquo;t scale.&nbsp; Then there are great successes who utilise an outsourced team to access huge resources at low cost and grow quickly.<br>Outsourcing, it seems, is one area where everyone holds a different opinion.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve tried almost every different outsourcing model &ndash; some were successful, some disastrous &ndash; and we&rsquo;re about to build a significant second team in Manila.&nbsp; Here are some of my stories and what I&rsquo;ve learned along the way.<br><strong>1. Outsourcing the development of a minimum viable product. </strong> <br>When I started Posse, I wanted to get a site up as soon as possible to see if the model worked.&nbsp; I had no technical expertise and didn&rsquo;t know how long it would take or how much it should cost.&nbsp; I didn&rsquo;t have enough expertise to hire my own developer so I outsourced to a dev shop in Sydney who then outsourced much of the work to their team in India.&nbsp; <br>But the approach was flawed and I wouldn&rsquo;t recommend it.&nbsp; Having a team of part-time developers in Sydney meant that no one was focused on the project.&nbsp; A startup struggling to devise a new model needs focus and commitment.&nbsp; I wanted smart people who&rsquo;d wake in the middle of the night with brilliant ideas for the site design and implementation.&nbsp; But for them, we were a one- or two-day per week project.&nbsp; No-one cared that much, the design was poorly conceived and riddled with bugs.&nbsp; The code was sloppy; it wouldn&rsquo;t scale, and was abandoned when we put our own team in place.&nbsp; It had to be.<br><strong>2. Partial outsourcing of development. </strong> <br>As soon as I closed our first funding round, I hired a CTO to run the development of our product right here.&nbsp; To develop as much as possible on the available budget he decided to hire two other developers in-house and outsource the rest to a different team in India.&nbsp; <br>This approach worked slightly better as our Sydney team was more focused on the product design.&nbsp; We started running regular user tests and developed agile processes, and the Indian team were quicker and more responsive in our direct dealings with them.<br>Again there were drawbacks.&nbsp; The Sydney team spent a lot of time writing specs for the team in India.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s impossible for a technical spec to cover every decision that the implementer has to make.&nbsp; For every major definition in the spec there were a hundred micro decisions left to the Indian developer.&nbsp; We&rsquo;d never met them; they didn&rsquo;t speak good English, or understand the business problem we were trying to solve.&nbsp; So, they often came up with wrong decisions.&nbsp; <br><strong>3. Outsourced sales and database management.</strong> <br>One of the biggest lessons I learned from the music site was that we needed a scalable sales process. &nbsp; I looked for a way to streamline the client on-boarding process so it could be done by anyone from anywhere at low cost.&nbsp; Now, when you recommend a shop on Posse, a call centre in Manila contacts the store owner, lets them know you&rsquo;ve recommended them and asks if they&rsquo;d like to list on the site.&nbsp;<br>The process works incredibly well for us.&nbsp; <br><strong>4. Building our own team in Manila</strong> <br>Now that we&rsquo;re growing, we&rsquo;ve decided to launch our own team in Manila.&nbsp; I went over there last week to scope out the scene and investigate different approaches.&nbsp; I learned about Manila&rsquo;s thriving startup scene and was shown two of the largest startup incubators, packed with enthusiastic entrepreneurs and engineers building their own products.<br>Through trialling different methods of outsourcing and learning from others who&rsquo;ve done it well, I value the time and effort put into getting it right.', 'Some lessons learned from outsourcing', 'Outsourcing the development of a minimum viable product. Partial outsourcing of development. Outsourced sales and database management. Building our own team in Manila.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 18, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(38, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/08/22/why-you-should-raise-money-yourself-and-not-hire-a-corporate-advisor/', '2013-08-22 00:00:00', 'Why you should raise money yourself and not hire a corporate advisor', '', '<strong>Posse - Why you should raise money yourself and not hire a corporate advisor</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/08/22/why-you-should-raise-money-yourself-and-not-hire-a-corporate-advisor/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/08/22/why-you-should-raise-money-yourself-and-not-hire-a-corporate-advisor/</a> <br>Hang around a few startup events and it&rsquo;s likely you&rsquo;ll bump into someone who&rsquo;s interested in becoming your &lsquo;corporate advisor&rsquo;.&nbsp; Most likely, this person will be male, aged 40 &ndash; 50, dressed in a suit and &ndash; impressive.&nbsp; He&rsquo;ll know everyone at the conference.&nbsp; He&rsquo;ll suggest you have coffee, talk about how busy he is and name-drop a bunch of well-known people he&rsquo;s &lsquo;consulting&rsquo; to.&nbsp; He&rsquo;ll flatter you; say how amazing your idea is, and tell you he can introduce you to a collection of impressive sounding people, all for a modest fee and some equity.<br>Don&rsquo;t do it!&nbsp; The deals these guys offer may be bad for the entrepreneur and investors don&rsquo;t like them.&nbsp; And you miss out on all the benefits of fundraising.&nbsp; Yes, it&rsquo;s painful but the fundraising process is the best education you can have for the next stage.<br>In many ways, fundraising sucks.&nbsp; It takes up a huge amount of time that you&rsquo;d rather spend building your business, and it&rsquo;s hard to take knockback after knockback.&nbsp; But where there&rsquo;s pain there&rsquo;s often gain, and with fundraising there&rsquo;s a huge upside.<br><strong>- Very smart people will challenge your idea and make suggestions.&nbsp;</strong> In the course of fundraising, I&rsquo;ve met some of the smartest people out there, with direct experience of building businesses similar to Posse.&nbsp; These challenging conversations about my product day after day helped shape my strategy.&nbsp; Many of our best ideas started as suggestions from prospective investors or concepts sculpted by their questions.<br>- <strong>You&rsquo;ll build a network of people who will help you later.</strong>&nbsp; I often catch up with people I pitched to but who didn&rsquo;t invest and ask for connections to other businesses or media partners.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve pitched to more than 1000 people so I amassed a pretty large and powerful network.<br>-<strong> You&rsquo;ll refine your pitch.</strong>&nbsp; By repeating the same pitch over and over, I soon sensed what people found exciting about our product strategy.&nbsp; I polished my pitch until it shone, which helps when I talk to media or sell to customers.<br><strong>- You&rsquo;ll be careful with money.&nbsp;</strong> I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;ve heard stories of companies who raised tens of millions from a VC and spent it all in a year before falling over.&nbsp; When you go out and meet people one on one, and they write you a personal cheque to invest in your business, I think you take spending much more seriously.&nbsp; <br>In my experience, working with a corporate advisor often doesn&rsquo;t work out; you end up frustrated, wasting time, money and equity.&nbsp; And you miss out on terrific groundwork for your business.', 'The upsides of fundraising on your own', 'Very smart people will challenge your idea and make suggestions. A network of people who will help you later. YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll refine your pitch. YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be careful with money.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 21, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(39, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 90, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/30/sole-founder-vs-co-founders/', '2013-07-30 00:00:00', 'Sole founder vs. co-founders', '', '<strong>Posse - Sole founder vs. co-founders</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/30/sole-founder-vs-co-founders/" target= "_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/30/sole-founder-vs-co-founders/</a> <br>I&rsquo;ve spoken to many friends and advisors, some with co-founders and others who&rsquo;ve done it themselves, to assess the benefits and risks of solo vs. co-founder relationships.&nbsp; There&rsquo;s no right answer: both setups work for different people at different stages of their businesses.&nbsp; As I reflect on my own decision, here are what I think are the top four reasons to work with a partner or go it alone.<br><strong>Why to be a sole founder</strong> <br><strong>1. You set the culture.</strong>&nbsp; There&rsquo;s nothing more frustrating than being in partnership with someone who isn&rsquo;t nearly as driven or hard working as you are. This not only feels unfair but it also affects the culture of your company: the rest of the team follows the leaders, and if one of the leaders is lazy then it&rsquo;s hard to create an ambitious and hardworking culture.<br><strong>2. It&rsquo;s easier to make decisions quickly.</strong>&nbsp; No one is right all the time, but if you made the leap to start a business then you obviously are confident enough in your own ability to back yourself.&nbsp; Different people have different visions and different priorities.&nbsp; Start-ups have to move quickly to gain momentum on a tight time frame.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s good to deliberate but it&rsquo;s important to make decisions quickly.&nbsp; <br><strong>3. You can&rsquo;t fall out with yourself.</strong>&nbsp; One of the top reasons startups fail is the founders fall out.&nbsp; They often start out as friends and it&rsquo;s great when things are going well.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s when times get tough partners squabble. It kills confidence with the investors, the team and very often kills the business. &nbsp; <br><strong>4. Sole founders learn more.</strong>&nbsp; You are responsible for everything, not just the bits that you like or are good at.&nbsp; You need to understand financial modelling, team building, product design, sales, marketing, community, HR and operations.&nbsp; When there&rsquo;s a problem, there&rsquo;s no one else to turn to.&nbsp; You need to solve it.&nbsp; Although this has been difficult and tedious at times, when I reflect, I&rsquo;m glad that I&rsquo;ve done it.&nbsp;<br><strong>Why to have a co-founder:</strong> <br><strong>1. You&rsquo;ll make better decisions and are more likely to reach the right outcome faster.</strong>&nbsp; Two heads are better than one.&nbsp; As long as your co-founder is smart and approaches problems from a perspective that differs from your own, through a process of debate, you&rsquo;ll arrive at better decisions.&nbsp; <br><strong>2. It&rsquo;s easier to lead a team.&nbsp; </strong>One key role of a founder is to work with, listen to the team, articulate strategy, and keep everyone motivated.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s hard to do this when you&rsquo;re not in the same physical location.&nbsp; Multiple founders mean that someone can lead investment discussions, someone can run marketing and PR and someone can be with the team at the same time.&nbsp; A strong founding team allows everyone to focus on their strengths, and you can get a lot more done.<br><strong>3. It&rsquo;s more fun.&nbsp;</strong> If you&rsquo;re thinking of starting a company by yourself, don&rsquo;t underestimate how lonely and dark it will be when times are tough.&nbsp; I would have loved to have a partner to balance out the hard times and to celebrate with when things went well.&nbsp; <br><strong>4. Co-founders are more fundable.</strong>&nbsp; In the early stages of a business, investors back the team more than the idea.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s no secret that professional investors, particularly VCs, don&rsquo;t like backing first time sole founders.&nbsp; They know how tough the road is and think that multiple founders will pick each other up when one loses motivation, they&rsquo;ll make better decisions and achieve more, all of which increases their chances at success.', 'Benefits of solo vs. co-founder relationships', 'Sole founder - You set the culture. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easier to make decisions quickly. You canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t fall out with yourself. Sole founders learn more. Co-founder - YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll make better decisions and are more likely to reach the right outcome faster. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easier to lead a team. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s more fun. Co-founders are more fundable.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 21, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(40, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/03/what-entrepreneurs-can-learn-from-extreme-sports-athletes/', '2013-07-03 00:00:00', 'What entrepreneurs can learn from extreme sports athletes', '', '<strong>Posse - What entrepreneurs can learn from extreme sports athletes</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/03/what-entrepreneurs-can-learn-from-extreme-sports-athletes/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/07/03/what-entrepreneurs-can-learn-from-extreme-sports-athletes/</a> <br>For athletes, challenging situations can mean life or death.&nbsp; They may not have the luxury of failing, learning and starting again.&nbsp; As they spoke at MaiTai and On Cue, I listened for thought patterns that helped them succeed in treacherous, time pressured situations.&nbsp; How could I learn to become a better entrepreneur?<br><strong>These four stood out.</strong> <br><strong>1. Stamina</strong>:&nbsp; Entrepreneurs experience hard times too.&nbsp; Just like the kite surfers: conditions are hard and sometimes I don&rsquo;t feel like walking into another pitch meeting.&nbsp; Hearing <a href="http://www.susimai.com" target="_blank">Susi Mai</a> a world famous kite-surfer talk about how as an athlete she struggles with the same thing and still gets out there in the wind and the cold every day even when she&rsquo;s exhausted made me realise that all who put themselves out there go through this.&nbsp; The ones who succeed are the ones who slug it out.<br><strong>2. Focus on right now:</strong> William Trubridge holds the record for the deepest unassisted dive.&nbsp; He only focuses on &lsquo;right now&rsquo;, not on the much more dangerous ascent ahead.&nbsp; <br>It&rsquo;s important to keep the future in mind but, like free diving, I&rsquo;ve found the process of building Posse so challenging, with so many things to think about, that one of the hardest things is focus.&nbsp; Yet without it, everything else could fall over<br><strong>3. Developing flexibility: </strong>On the way down, one of William&rsquo;s biggest challenges is maintaining flexibility in his body, or the deep-water pressure can shatter his bones.&nbsp; I thought about where I&rsquo;ve been rigid in my thinking about how our product and team should work and what the priorities are.&nbsp; The team often push back on my structure, so I&rsquo;ll take a leaf out of William&rsquo;s book and become more flexible<br><strong>4. Commitment to a challenge:</strong> <a href="http://www.jesserichman.com" target="blank">Jessie Richman</a> was named &lsquo;Kiteboarder of the Year&rsquo; in 2012.&nbsp; He spoke about what goes through his head when he&rsquo;s taking off on a huge jump.&nbsp; And when he has accidents, what he thought led to those accidents.&nbsp; A key word that kept coming up in his response was &lsquo;commitment&rsquo;.<br>It&rsquo;s the same for startups.&nbsp; In my previous music company, I always had a question in the back of my mind: do I believe in this artist?&nbsp; Am I sure this is going to happen?&nbsp; All these projects failed.&nbsp; Success came when my belief didn&rsquo;t waiver, even for a second.&nbsp; <br>As entrepreneurs, we put ourselves on the line every day: it&rsquo;s a high-pressure occupation.&nbsp; Will I learn fast enough and have the discipline to win the entrepreneur equivalent of a gold medal?&nbsp; I can&rsquo;t be sure; no one can.&nbsp; Listening to these athletes speak about their approach to challenges was inspiring.', 'Lessons from extreme sports athletes', 'Stamina. Focus on right now. Developing flexibility. Commitment to a challenge.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 27, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(41, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/24/how-we-analyzed-competitors-to-design-our-product/', '2013-04-24 00:00:00', 'How we analyzed competitors to design our product', '', '<strong>Posse - How we analyzed competitors to design our product</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/24/how-we-analyzed-competitors-to-design-our-product/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/24/how-we-analyzed-competitors-to-design-our-product/</a><br>Now that we&rsquo;ve officially launched in the US, it&rsquo;s natural that we&rsquo;ll be compared to competitors.&nbsp; In my blog today, I wanted to reflect on the process we used to design our product and how we took inspiration and ideas from others, like Foursquare and Yelp.<br><strong>1. Define the problem and the audience</strong> <br>We started with a hunch that some people preferred recommendations from friends to reviews from strangers on Yelp or TripAdvisor.&nbsp; <br>We continued the interview cycle until we identified four audience definers: gender, age, behaviors, and &lsquo;preferences&rsquo;.&nbsp; By this I mean, what they sought in recommendations from friends and why they enjoyed giving recommendations to friends.&nbsp; This may appear cold and calculating: breaking down users into audience segments, then designing features and artwork to appeal to those users.&nbsp; It certainly helped us understand who would want to use our product and why they&rsquo;d use it instead of the competition.<br><strong>2. Who has previously tried to solve the problem?&nbsp; Why did they succeed or fail?</strong> <br>For this exercise, we mapped out every platform, past or present that had tried to solve social search.&nbsp; Yelp and Trip Advisor obtained lots of reviews and great data but failed to get a high enough proportion of their users writing reviews to show what your friends think of places.&nbsp;&nbsp; Both sites seemed littered with irate customers writing negative reviews.&nbsp; These upset the merchants, and many users we interviewed were skeptical about who was writing the reviews.&nbsp; <br>The only platform we could find that had managed to crack the problem of persuading lots of socially connected people to give it content was Foursquare.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m not saying that Foursquare, Yelp, Trip Advisor and many other local discovery platforms aren&rsquo;t great products that are loved lots of users.&nbsp; Foursquare in particular was revolutionary in the way they use game mechanics and design to make participation in their platform fun: Posse and many others since have taken inspiration from these ideas to develop other products.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m just saying, this is a process we went through: analyzing the competition to design what will hopefully be a better product for a certain part of the market that doesn&rsquo;t seem to be well-served by the existing players.<br><strong>3. Designing the principles behind our solution</strong> <br>Once we&rsquo;d defined our problem, our audience, and analyzed the competition, we created a list of principles.&nbsp; These principles underpinned the product for which the platform we designed would work.&nbsp; They included statements like: &lsquo;Our audience make recommendations to signal social status&rsquo;; &lsquo;Our audience like to collect and display their favorite things (Pinterest / Wanelo)&rsquo;; &lsquo; &lsquo;Our product category is so competitive that our product must be delightful and fun so people want to share it with friends&rsquo;; &lsquo;Our audience doesn&rsquo;t want to earn currency for making recommendations but love recognition with authentic unexpected gifts from their favorite retailers&rsquo;.&nbsp; <br><strong>4. Designing the product</strong> <br>With these principles in place, we set about designing the actual product.&nbsp; It all came together surprisingly quickly.&nbsp; The whole team took part in daily product design and we brought in lots of outside help for fresh perspectives on ideas.<br>This whole process of defining the problem and audience, analyzing the competition, designing our product principles and then the product took around four months and involved more than 200 outside interviews before the first line of code was written.', 'Ideas and process used to design a product', 'Define the problem and the audience. Who has previously tried to solve the problem?  Why did they succeed or fail? Designing the principles behind our solution. Designing the product.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 22, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(42, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/09/why-its-important-for-startups-to-celebrate-little-victories/', '2013-04-09 00:00:00', 'Why itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s important for startups to celebrate little victories', '', '<strong>Posse - Why it&rsquo;s important for startups to celebrate little victories</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/09/why-its-important-for-startups-to-celebrate-little-victories/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/04/09/why-its-important-for-startups-to-celebrate-little-victories/</a><br>If, like me, you run or work in a startup, you may (should!) read lots of business books and attend conferences, honing your leadership skills. And they all urge us to &lsquo;celebrate small victories&rsquo; with our teams. &nbsp; It&rsquo;s a great principle, but reality can get in the way: it&rsquo;s hard for startups to set aside time and money to celebrate wins. &nbsp;When you&rsquo;re burdened with a list of unmet goals, it&rsquo;s easy to overlook what you have achieved.<br>In the chaotic, pressure-cooker of a startup, where time and money are critical, here are five reasons for celebrating small wins.<br><strong>1. It reminds people that goal setting works.</strong> <br>I want everything to happen all at once, but accept that this isn&rsquo;t achievable. &nbsp;Our team make steady progress because every quarter we agree on a plan and set of goals. &nbsp;The goals are challenging but achievable, and when we hit them it feels great! &nbsp;Celebration underscores the success of our process.&nbsp; It motivates everyone to set and reach for the next goal.<br><strong>2. It unifies everyone around a positive outcome.</strong> <br>In a small startup team, each person is often responsible for their own department. &nbsp;On our team we have one Community Manager, one Business Development, two retail engineers, two mobile engineers, two web engineers and so on. &nbsp;We set company-wide goals but everyone contributes differently. &nbsp;Celebrating company-wide success rather than just individual achievements unifies everyone around the goal and reinforces that we&rsquo;re working on something bigger than ourselves.<br><strong>3. There&rsquo;s an opportunity to look at the big picture.</strong> <br>Celebrating provides a great moment to reflect on the big picture.&nbsp; What are we planning to achieve? &nbsp;Stopping to reflect as we reach each milestone in the journey enables the team to reflect on what&rsquo;s working, what&rsquo;s not and where we should focus our resources next.<br><strong>4. Everyone wants to be on a winning team.</strong> <br>Success is the best way to boost team morale. &nbsp;It can&rsquo;t be faked but when it&rsquo;s achieved, you should make the most of it by celebrating! &nbsp;Our engineers slogged away for months when people weren&rsquo;t using the website, and the community manager struggled to engage our audience. &nbsp;Now that we&rsquo;ve turned a corner and lots of people are using the platform, I&rsquo;ve found that the team&rsquo;s enthusiasm, creativity and productivity have exploded.<br><strong>5. It makes everyone feel appreciated.&nbsp;</strong> <br>Startup teams work much harder than regular people &ndash; well, ours does. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s vital that founders demonstrate how much they appreciate and value their team&rsquo;s contribution, and celebrating is a great way to do this.<br>I find the challenge of leading a team &ndash; keeping everyone motivated and focused in the right direction incredibly difficult. I&rsquo;ve tried everything I know to build a great culture: bringing inspirational shareholders to speak, running regular offsite events, and hosting regular team lunches are a few. &nbsp;All these help, but there&rsquo;s only one way to make a smart team happy in the long-term and that&rsquo;s progress. &nbsp;Regularly celebrating wins guarantees that progress is felt as much as possible.', '5 Reasons for celebrating small wins', 'It reminds people that goal setting works. It unifies everyone around a positive outcome. ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s an opportunity to look at the big picture. Everyone wants to be on a winning team. It makes everyone feel appreciated. ', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 25, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(43, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 38, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/03/15/launch-a-startup-like-a-rock-band-at-sxsw/', '2013-03-15 00:00:00', 'Launch a startup like a rock band at SXSW', '', '<strong>Posse - Launch a startup like a rock band at SXSW</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/03/15/launch-a-startup-like-a-rock-band-at-sxsw/" target= "_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/03/15/launch-a-startup-like-a-rock-band-at-sxsw/</a><br>This year I&rsquo;m back at SXSW, launching our internet company and App.&nbsp; I applied many of the tactics I learned in music, and we had amazing success at securing media coverage and traction.&nbsp; Here are six tricks I learned in music that I used to launch Posse at SXSW this week on a budget.<br><strong>1. Get influential people talking about you before the festival.</strong> <br>In music, we focused on being heard by high profile producers: these guys are great talkers and they aren&rsquo;t pitched every day.&nbsp; For the Posse launch, we worked out which US tech influencers love SXSW and asked them to share their five favourite places to eat, drink and shop in Austin.&nbsp; We secured big names like Elspeth Rountree (NBC &amp; Fox), Maya Baratz (ABC News) and David Tisch (Boxgroup) asking them to contribute &ndash; and turned it into a &lsquo;Tech Elite&rsquo;s Guide to Austin&rsquo;.<br>We posted blogs featuring the list of a different influencer daily in the two weeks leading up to Austin, all of which were retweeted by the featured people themselves, their businesses, media and the retailers they recommended.&nbsp; <br><strong>2. Timing is everything. &nbsp;</strong> <br>Bands save releasing records until right before SXSW.&nbsp; When something awesome happens (like you release an App or secure a round of funding) don&rsquo;t write a press release straight away.&nbsp; We saved our App Launch and funding announcement so we could land a major press story right on the eve of SXSW.&nbsp; <br><strong>3. Guerrilla marketing works &ndash; but you have to be clever. &nbsp;</strong> <br>Every pole in downtown Austin is covered by 9am each morning.&nbsp; Big companies spend thousands designing and printing fancy-looking posters and then hire people to cover the poles.&nbsp; The most effective posters are simple, and if you&rsquo;re on a low budget like us, you must find a way to stand out.&nbsp; <br><strong>4. Hustle all day and all night!</strong> <br>If you come to SXSW launching anything, you have to be prepared to hustle from 7am to midnight every day. We were at all the parties we could make &ndash; if you&rsquo;re influential and you&rsquo;ve been at SXSW, there&rsquo;s a good chance we spoke to you and tried to get you to download our app.&nbsp; Opportunities were everywhere &ndash; on the first day when everyone was waiting to register, we combed through the queue meeting everyone and offering cupcakes to anyone who signed up on the spot.<br><strong>5. Get a street team</strong> <br>You can only cover so much ground by yourself.&nbsp; To maximise your impact it&rsquo;s important to try to get as many people as possible representing you at the festival.&nbsp; We chose a team of enthusiastic marketing students who did an excellent job signing up users, distributing maps and helping run our tradeshow stand.<br><strong>6. Tie yourself to other people&rsquo;s events</strong> <br>The key trick of SXSW for a band is to get on the bill at an event where everyone is going to be.&nbsp; If you try to put on your own show, you have the near-impossible job of promoting the show to a large group of people you don&rsquo;t know and who already have a plan of events they want to go to.', 'Six tricks to launch a startup in a conference', 'Get influential people talking about you before the festival. Timing is everything. Guerrilla marketing works Ã¢â‚¬â€œ but you have to be clever. Hustle all day and all night! Get a street team. Tie yourself to other peopleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s events.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 23, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(44, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 79, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/02/13/hiring-for-a-start-up-what-ive-learned-so-far/', '2013-02-13 00:00:00', 'Hiring for a start-up Ã¢â‚¬â€œ what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned so far', '', '<strong>Posse &ndash; Hiring for a start-up &ndash; what I&rsquo;ve learned so far</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/02/13/hiring-for-a-start-up-what-ive-learned-so-far/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2013/02/13/hiring-for-a-start-up-what-ive-learned-so-far/</a><br>The rate at which people we hire work out is still only about 80%.&nbsp; My mentors run major companies; they have hired hundreds of people.&nbsp; When I ask about their success rate, most come up with a figure between 80 &ndash; 90%.&nbsp; Maybe I&rsquo;m not doing so badly.&nbsp; Here&rsquo;s some of what I&rsquo;ve learned:<br>1. The most important thing to look for in a start-up team member is the ability to <strong>MAKE THINGS HAPPEN</strong>.&nbsp; In a corporate or less intense environment, it&rsquo;s okay to set a bunch of targets and then come up with a list of reasons why something wasn&rsquo;t possible. In a start-up there are two meaningful outcomes: success and failure.&nbsp; The ability to make things happen has nothing to do with intelligence &ndash; I&rsquo;ve found that even the smartest people procrastinate or buckle under pressure.&nbsp; So when you&rsquo;re hiring, always look for examples of times in the past where they had an ambitious challenge and overcame barriers to achieve.<br>2. The next thing to look for is creativity and intelligence.&nbsp; As the founder, you always think your ideas are brilliant &ndash; if you didn&rsquo;t then you never would have started this crazy thing.&nbsp; I soon learned that my first ideas are often wrong and it&rsquo;s important to surround yourself with people who are passionate about your product, smart and creative.&nbsp; The whole team works together to strategise major business challenges and design the product.&nbsp; More importantly, each member of a start-up runs their own department <br>3. Hire slowly and methodically.&nbsp;Check references!&nbsp; I know everyone says to do this but it&rsquo;s easy to get excited about someone and forget.&nbsp; Then when they don&rsquo;t work out everyone asks me what their references said, and it&rsquo;s embarrassing to admit I didn&rsquo;t check.&nbsp; Ask lots of different people to interview a prospective new team member; obtain a range of perspectives.&nbsp; By giving a protective hire a list of questions and evaluating how they approach the answers you can see how creative and smart they are, and you also discover if they have a problem getting things done on time.<br>4. When you do make a mistake (and you will) act fast.&nbsp; If someone is not right for us I generally can tell in the first few weeks, and have been pretty good at acting quickly.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s always a morale-breaker when the team loses a member but you can&rsquo;t afford to have an underperforming person hanging around, bringing down the standard.<br>I&rsquo;m happy to report that we now have one of the most passionate, creative, smart and productive start-up teams around.&nbsp; A start-up is a mission though a jungle.&nbsp; You don&rsquo;t want people who&rsquo;ll sit around hypothesising &ndash; you want warriors who&rsquo;ll get out there and try things.&nbsp; People whose drive and ambition will overcome anything.', 'Recruiting lessons for a start up', 'The most important thing to look for in a start-up team member is the ability to MAKE THINGS HAPPEN. The next thing to look for is creativity and intelligence. Hire slowly and methodically. When you do make a mistake (and you will) act fast.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 28, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0),
(45, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 24, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/11/28/spinning-the-feedback-loop/', '2012-11-28 00:00:00', 'Spinning the Feedback Loop', '', '<strong>Posse - Spinning the Feedback Loop</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/11/28/spinning-the-feedback-loop/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/11/28/spinning-the-feedback-loop/</a><br>I first heard of the concept of a &lsquo;<a href="http://hbr.org/2008/01/mastering-the-management-system/ar/1" target="_blank">Closed Loop Management System</a>&lsquo; in a Harvard Business Review article I read last summer.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s a process that big companies use which involves first developing a strategy, then translating it into measurable targets, planning operations, implementation, monitoring and learning before testing and adapting the strategy so that the team can develop the next iteration of the strategy.<br>Followers of Lean Startup methodology will know this principle as the &lsquo;<a href="http://theleanstartup.com/principles" target="_blank">Feedback Loop</a>&lsquo;. &nbsp;It makes sense in principle but is very hard to execute well.&nbsp; As you&rsquo;ll know from reading my blogs &ndash; I&rsquo;m no expert and I&rsquo;m still learning all this stuff as I go, but here are a few things I&rsquo;ve figured out that are important to making the feedback loop spin effectively.<br><strong>1. Listen to everyone.</strong>&nbsp; As a founder, you&rsquo;re naturally optimistic and you believe you&rsquo;re on-track to build a hugely successful company.&nbsp; If you didn&rsquo;t have a high level of self-belief then you&rsquo;d never be able to convince others to invest in your idea or join your team.&nbsp; Balance this optimism with a passion to constantly test your plans and product with users.&nbsp; Not just the initial model hypothesises but every single thing you do should be thoroughly tested before, during and after it&rsquo;s implemented.&nbsp; <br><strong>2. Take time out to think</strong>.&nbsp; After I&rsquo;ve listened to as many people as I can, including users, team members, board directors and my friends, I&rsquo;ll sneak away and spend time by myself to think.&nbsp; Through this, I can build a strategy.&nbsp; Once I have the strategy worked out, I take it back out to the team and test the ideas.&nbsp; If the strategy is good, everyone gets excited; if it&rsquo;s bad, everyone argues.&nbsp; <br><strong>3. Face big problems head on.</strong>&nbsp; One of my mentors in music gave me some great business advice once.&nbsp; &lsquo;If you think there&rsquo;s a problem &ndash; there&rsquo;s a problem.&rsquo;&nbsp; As the entrepreneur, you live and breathe the company, you can sense when something isn&rsquo;t working.&nbsp; Many startups that I&rsquo;ve seen fail, knew they had the problem that killed them long before they died.&nbsp; I think you have to tackle every major problem head on in the next spin of your management loop.<br><strong>4. Move fast.&nbsp;</strong> It&rsquo;s obvious that with limited time and resources you have a certain number of spins to get the product &ndash; market fit right.&nbsp; We still don&rsquo;t have ours 100% there, although our user engagement metrics suggest we&rsquo;re coming much closer.&nbsp; The faster you can create good new strategy, implement and test, the better your chances are of success.<br><strong>5. Be disciplined:&nbsp;</strong> It&rsquo;s so easy to want to react to every small problem, fix every bug and make lots of incremental improvements.&nbsp; Earlier this year we were sucked into addressing all of these as they came up.&nbsp; Weeks passed by without any major advances in the implementation of a strategy, so we&rsquo;ve learnt as a team to focus on getting out the big important things that we can learn from rather than making sure the site is perfect.', 'Making the feedback loop spin effectively', 'Listen to everyone. Take time out to think. Face big problems head on. Move fast. Be disciplined.', 'Rebekah campbell', 178, 25, '2014-11-24 12:16:24', '2014-11-24 12:16:24', 0);
