(60, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 140, 'http://amyjokim.com/2012/10/03/designing-sustained-engagement-3-questions-to-get-you-started/', '2012-10-03 00:00:00', 'Designing Sustained Engagement: 3 Questions to get you started', '', '<strong>Amy Jo Kim - Designing Sustained Engagement: 3 Questions to get you started</strong><br/><a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/10/03/designing-sustained-engagement-3-questions-to-get-you-started/" target="_blank">http://amyjokim.com/2012/10/03/designing-sustained-engagement-3-questions-to-get-you-started/</a> <br/> What makes a digital experience engaging over time? How do you grab people''s attention during onboarding - and keep them interested and coming back for months, even years? <br/> To drive sustained engagement, you need to think about who you''re designing for, what motivates them, and how their experience will unfold over time. &nbsp;As you''re formulating your product vision and engagement strategy, here are some good starter questions to ask.<br/> <strong>1) Who are your players? What''s their </strong><a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/19/social-engagement-whos-playing-how-do-they-like-to-engage/" target="_blank">Social Engagement Style</a><strong>?</strong> <br/> Knowing who you''re designing for is crucial, especially if you''re integrating game design into your service. Ever heard of Customer Development? This concept is&nbsp;about understanding and testing out WHO is going to use your service. <br/> Once you''ve identified your core target audience, you can use <a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/19/social-engagement-whos-playing-how-do-they-like-to-engage/" target="_blank">our Social Engagement Styles matrix </a>as an analytic framework to think through player motivations. Are you players motivated by Competition? Collaboration? Visible Achievement? Exploration? Self-Expression? What''s most important? What''s missing from their lives? How does their behavior shift at different times in their lifecycle? What qualities reinforce their identity, and tap into their aspirational view of themselves?<br/> <strong>2) How will you define, measure, visualize and reward&nbsp;</strong><a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/14/the-players-journey-designing-over-time/" target="_blank">Progress Over Time?</a> <br/> People are deeply engaged by learning new things, attaining skills, and making progress along a <strong>meaningful&nbsp;</strong>continuum. What can YOUR players get better at?&nbsp;What skills are they developing when they engage with your service<em>&nbsp;over time?</em>&nbsp;What metric are they improving - and what makes that metric meaningful? What new powers, access and privileges open up as they progress?<br/> Figuring out the right progress metrics for your system can be tricky. Your progress metrics should leverage the core value of your service - AND tap into the motivations and aspirations of your target players.&nbsp;<br/> <strong> 3) What </strong><a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/17/happy-habits-engagement-design-meets-positive-psychology/" target="_blank">Happy Habits</a><strong>&nbsp;drive sustained engagement during onboarding, habit-building and mastery?</strong> <br/> <a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/17/happy-habits-engagement-design-meets-positive-psychology/" target="_blank">Happy Habits </a>are engagement loops that stimulate ongoing positive emotions. What''s the emotional arc for first-time players? What''s the trigger (internal or external) that reminds them to return? What kind of feedback and sense of progress do you provide? What''s the emotional payoff?&nbsp;Think about the emotional arcs and loops that your players experience during onboarding, habit-building and mastery. If you can design a compelling feedback loop that helps your players gain skill and move towards mastery of something they care about, you''re off to a good start.', '3 Questions to ask when formulating your product vision and engagement strategy', 'Who are your players? What''s their Social Engagement Style? How will you define, measure, visualize and reward Progress Over Time? What Happy Habits drive sustained engagement during onboarding, habit-building and mastery?', 'Amy Jo Kim', 179, 32, '2014-11-24 12:49:44', '2014-11-24 12:49:44', 0),
(61, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 126, 'http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/17/happy-habits-engagement-design-meets-positive-psychology/', '2012-09-17 00:00:00', 'Happy Habits: Engagement Design meets Positive Psychology', '', '<strong>Amy Jo Kim - Happy Habits: Engagement Design meets Positive Psychology</strong><br/><a href="http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/17/happy-habits-engagement-design-meets-positive-psychology/" target="_blank">http://amyjokim.com/2012/09/17/happy-habits-engagement-design-meets-positive-psychology/</a> <br/> Recently, I''ve been immersed in a project that''s translating the science of happiness into a compelling, habit-forming digital service. I''ve been digging into the scientific literature on positive psychology and neuroscience correlates, and learning about the activities the reliably make people happier</a>. I''d like to share 3 key things I''ve learned from this journey.<br/> <strong>1) Investing in Meaningful Relationships makes people happier</strong> <br/> There&nbsp;are a variety of regular practices - &nbsp;including gratitude, kindness, mindfulness, and empathy - that have been shown to improve happiness in clinical trials. However, the most robust and widely-cited finding is the impact of relationships on happiness. In a nutshell, people who cultivate meaningful relationships report higher levels of happiness. <br/> <strong>2) Social Comparison makes people unhappier</strong> <br/> In the age of Gamification Everywhere, social comparison has become a default technique for motivating and engaging people. But happiness science reveals that judging yourself in relation to others is a mental habit that leads to envy, guilt, regret, and defensiveness</a>.&nbsp;Once you start comparing yourself to others, you''ve jumped onto a treadmill that never stops - there is ALWAYS someone else who is smarter/better/stronger/richer/more beautiful/more popular than you are.<br/> <strong>3) Happiness is a Habit -&nbsp;you CAN change the way you think and perceive the world</strong> <br/> Since my academic background, I''m familiar with the research on brain plasticity - which boils down to <em>You Are What You Think</em>. &nbsp;Brains turn out to be highly programmable - within<em>&nbsp;</em>certain limits,&nbsp;you can literally rewire your brain and stimulate growth and change through specific mental activities.<br/> There are a collection of well-researched techniques or &quot;interventions&quot; for developing a positive life outlook and generating feelings of happiness and well-being. When people do these regularly, their outlook and mood improves.&nbsp;Creating an engaging, compelling digital service to deliver these interventions is hard - and we''re just starting to understand what Happy Habits look like in action.', 'Activities the reliably make people happier - and unhappier', 'Investing in Meaningful Relationships makes people happier. Social Comparison makes people unhappier. Happiness is a Habit -  you CAN change the way you think and perceive the world.', 'Amy Jo Kim', 179, 102, '2014-11-24 12:49:44', '2014-11-24 12:49:44', 0),
(62, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/true-leadership-colours/', '2014-10-21 00:00:00', 'True Leadership Colours', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ The Leadership Colours</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/true-leadership-colours/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/true-leadership-colours/</a> <br>What colour is your leadership style? Shades of beige, or a riot of ideation and colourful innovation?<br>The time of beige leadership values and the self-propagating disaster that shadows them have an ever-shortening life span as innovation, business structure and cultural and societal changes evolve at an increasingly rapid speed. <br>According to a GallupÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s <em>State of the Global Workplace</em> worldwide survey, only 13 per cent of employees are actively engaged at work. To put it another way, approximately 180 million employees in the 142-country study are disengaged Ã¢â‚¬â€? yes, they are going to work and going through the motions of doing their jobs, but they are unlikely to be collaborating and making positive contributions to their employers and organisations. <br>According to Charles Handy, the best time to start a new Ã¢â‚¬ËœcurveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ is before you reach the peak of your existing one. That way, you will be starting something new when you still have the resources, and the spirit, to take it to new heights. <br>To remain relevant in tomorrowÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s world, the Ã¢â‚¬ËœbeigeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ leader, in whatever format, needs to be removed and replaced so a new curve can be started. In their place Ã¢â‚¬â€? in the new Ã¢â‚¬ËœcurveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Ã¢â‚¬â€? we will find strength, inspiration and influential leadership from those individuals who are authentic. Leaders who are equally aware of their own unique values and strengths, as well as their weaknesses. Leaders who have, in their own unique way, colour and vibrance.<br>We need leaders who are so comfortable in the space that they have the strength to lead and share, to learn and grow, who are actively curious and willing to give. Leaders who amplify others and build a culture that encourages and enables sharing, a culture of commercial collaboration that drives change and innovation. These leaders create the space and freedom to think, debate and ideate. This is a culture in which people form diverse skill bases and demographics Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and genders and industries have the opportunity to speak and be heard.<br>So pick up that paint brush and add a touch of colour and authenticity to your leadership style Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and maybe even see what magic is created when collaboration happens.', 'What touch of colour you need to add to your leadership style.', 'Leaders who are equally aware of their own unique values and strengths, as well as their weaknesses. Leaders who have, in their own unique way, colour and vibrance. Leaders who amplify others and build a culture that encourages and enables sharing, a culture of commercial collaboration that drives change and innovation. ', 'Janine Garner', 180, 49, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(63, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-stop-believing-power-can/', '2014-10-13 00:00:00', 'DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Stop Believing: The Power of Ã¢â‚¬ËœI CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner - DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Stop Believing: The Power of Ã¢â‚¬ËœI CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-stop-believing-power-can/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-stop-believing-power-can/</a><br>Often we think long and hard about what we want to achieve. We think, and we think, and we <em>think</em>.<br>Those that succeed as business leaders, as the incredible groundbreaking entrepreneurs whose stories we sit and devour, live by a very simple set of Ã¢â‚¬ËœcommandmentsÃ¢â‚¬â„¢. They recognise the inherent need to stop living in the abstract and instead bring oneself into the reality of Ã¢â‚¬Ëœyes I canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.<br>I can. The power of those two words is so strong, in life and in business. When we allow ourselves to not only trust in our own ideas, but to actually follow through on them and action them, we are letting go of years of ingrained negativity and naysaying. It is likely we have finally surrounded ourselves with the right people, because nothing propagates development of great plans like a great team. Having valued and trusted members of staff, or peers alongside us on the journey means being pushed and prodded in the right way to make decisions and stick by them. It means looking out instead of in, and bringing dreams to fruition.<br>It means, as the meme says, initiation, not just imagination.<br>The power of Ã¢â‚¬ËœI CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ is the power that people like Richard Branson live by. Just as a verb is a doing word, Branson is a Ã¢â‚¬ËœdoingÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ person. And itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a lesson we all need to learn when we um and ahhh with those new ideas. A Ã¢â‚¬Ëœwhat if I failÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t going to bring us the next stage of growth that we want.<br>What will do it is Ã¢â‚¬ËœI may fail, but I will try anyway, because you know what?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢<br>Ã¢â‚¬ËœI canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.', 'Why we need to think positively', 'Recognise the inherent need to stop living in the abstract and instead bring oneself into the reality of Ã¢â‚¬Ëœyes I can. When we allow ourselves to not only trust in our own ideas, but to actually follow through on them and action them, we are letting go of years of ingrained negativity and naysaying. Nothing propagates development of great plans like a great team.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 16, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(64, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20141006233440-31763519-the-power-of-you?trk=prof-post', '2014-10-06 00:00:00', 'The Power Of You', '', '<strong>Linkedin Ã¢â‚¬â€œ The Power of You</strong><br><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20141006233440-31763519-the-power-of-you?trk=prof-post" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20141006233440-31763519-the-power-of-you?trk=prof-post</a><br>Last week I received the most beautiful thank you note. It was a lovely thing to get in itself, but it also reinforced for me just how much power rests in each of us to create change and momentum for another; to begin a new flow in direction, or reinforce a decision. Individually we are capable of creating significant ripples of change even when we donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t realise it.<br>Are you aware of how your every day actions and words influence others, or are you going about your day oblivious to the moments of magic that you, yourself, have the ability to create? <br>This particular thank you note reminded me of a fabulous <a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/the-power-of-you/ted.com/talks/drew_dudley_everyday_leadership" target="_blank">Ted Talk</a> by Drew Dudley. Drew argues rather than viewing leadership in such traditional and static terms, that the impact that we can unknowingly have on another means we are <em>all</em> leaders Ã¢â‚¬â€œ spot on!<br>Everyday Leadership is a must have in our work toolboxes. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about making a conscious decision to have these abilities:<br><br><ul type="disc"><li>to walk the talk</li><li>to actively sponsor others</li><li>to <em>intentionally</em> support each other</li><li>to encourage action</li><li>to collaborate and share what you know and who you know to better someone else.</li></ul><br>This will secure the future pipeline of leaders.<br>When we share thoughts, knowledge and ideas openly, <em>with no expectation of anything in return</em>, when we are authentic in our behaviour, words and belief systems, the ability to drive change in others, whether it is in their actions, ideation or opinions is a powerful thing.<br>There are those that you inspire who will watch how you react and go about business; who listen to what you say, and what you do, and they will relish that little bit of help and encouragement to pump up their Ã¢â‚¬ËœJetsonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s bubbleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ of sanity and clarity.<br>And if that little bit of help Ã¢â‚¬â€œ that everyday action Ã¢â‚¬â€œ enables others to be safe in the belief that they can achieve their dreams Ã¢â‚¬â€œ<br>Then the power of you is an amazing place to live.', 'The abilities everyday leaders must have', 'To walk the talk. To actively sponsor others. To intentionally support each other. To encourage action. To collaborate and share what you know and who you know to better someone else.\n', 'Janine Garner', 180, 14, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(65, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/sharing-the-spotlight/', '2014-09-29 00:00:00', 'Sharing The Spotlight', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Sharing The Spotlight</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/sharing-the-spotlight/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/sharing-the-spotlight/</a><strong> </strong><br>Whether it was an idea, a publication, a launch, an event or a last-minute save, there is nothing more frustrating Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and morale sapping Ã¢â‚¬â€œ than seeing someone else take ownership (and the kudos) for what you have worked like a maniac on.<br>And it doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t matter if it was to down them acting deliberately or simply out of a lack of awareness; the feelings of bewilderment, hurt and being slammed by someone who is senior to you on a management scale remain.<br>In the collaborative workspace, it is essential as leaders to take others on the success journey Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and being vulnerable enough to allow others to stand fully in their own spotlights rather than always taking it for ourselves.<br><strong>ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about making clear statements, and ensuring that transparency is constant, and that success Ã¢â‚¬â€œ all team membersÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ success Ã¢â‚¬â€œ is celebrated. Our own included.</strong><br>These are some of the key points to bear in mind in ensuring there are no egos fighting inner battles when an individual success occurs within the team structure:<br><br><ul type="disc"><li><strong><em>Be prepared to partition rewards and recognition:</em></strong> give kudos to the person/people who developed the concept/product/launch, and then the team as a whole for supporting.</li><li><strong><em>DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be afraid to take a back seat:</em></strong> the reason you have surrounded yourself with a team is because they are brilliant at what they do. You are not a one man/woman band. Allow yourself to realise that you have a circle of excellence, and be humble enough to see their worth.</li><li><strong><em>Have clear areas of responsibility:</em></strong>this means when there is a success story, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easy to say Ã¢â‚¬Ëœyes, that credit needs to go to X and YÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.</li><li><strong><em>Make sure you take the time to celebrate your own successes and milestones:</em></strong> donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t put your own wins on the backburner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s when you will start to resent your team.</li></ul>', 'The key points to bear in mind when sharing the spotlight with your team', 'Be prepared to partition rewards and recognition. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be afraid to take a back seat. Have clear areas of responsibility. Make sure you take the time to celebrate your own successes and milestones.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 16, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(66, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/the-wrong-end-of-the-stick/', '2014-09-22 00:00:00', 'The Wrong End Of The Stick', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ The Wrong End Of The Stick</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/the-wrong-end-of-the-stick/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/the-wrong-end-of-the-stick/</a><br>Commercial collaboration. As anyone who talks to me knows, it is, I feel, the only way forward in a corporate (and wider) world of constant change, fear and uncertainty; and engaging fully as leaders and business owners is essential to success.<br>But letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s be realistic. As we discussed just this last week at LBDG Exclusive Dinners, to err is human Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and sometimes, collaborative experiences simply donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work out, whether on a large scale or small.<br><em>So what should we do if collabora-will</em> <em>turns into collabora-wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t?</em><br><em>Say Ã¢â‚¬Ëœwell, thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s obviously not the way to do business Ã¢â‚¬â€œ IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m going back to the closed door and me, myself and IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢?</em>Absolutely not.<br>If you have a setback, learn from it. Take the following realisations and apply them to your business area, company or enterprise:<br><br><ul type="disc"><li><strong>Did this fail because of a friendship: </strong>did you go into commercial collaboration with a friend or family member, without thoroughly considering all this would entail? Did you make clear delineations in terms of financing, areas of responsibility, and have it all signed and sealed? This is not an occasion to be Ã¢â‚¬ËœfluidÃ¢â‚¬â„¢. Be clear about who is doing what, and paying for it. And when you have to have the tough conversations, have them. If you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t, then you will definitely lose the personal relationship. Be prepared to step up, and you may salvage the non-book balancing side of things. More to the point, go in with eyes wide open, and with someone who has experience and knowledge.</li><li><strong>Did this fail because of intractable leadership style: </strong>whether it was your own, or someone elseÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s, sometimes the leopard cannot change its spots when it comes to leadership. Be prepared to accept this. There is a famous example of John Chambers, CEO of Cisco, who admitted he used to be a Ã¢â‚¬Ëœcommand and controlÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ leader, but has managed to change his style and has fostered such a successful atmosphere of collaboration within the company that there are now over 500 managers working in collaborative groups. ButÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ for every John Chambers and Cisco, thereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a SONY. If you are within an non-collaborative environment, sometimes you simply need to move on.</li><li><strong>Some partnerships arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t meant to be. </strong>ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s that simple. People are people; and some people are like oil and water. They are never going to mix. And thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s OK Ã¢â‚¬â€œ this may be the case between two individuals, or two companies. If this happens, look for an alternative viable solution. If you try to force collaboration, it wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work.</li></ul><br>Which is probably my biggest point. The whole thing about commercial collaboration is that you are dealing with people, rather than abstract concepts. So that comes back to you as a person. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t force a relationship Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and above all else, trust your gut. Your instincts are there for a reason. ', 'How to deal with setbacks from commercial collaboration', 'Did this fail because of a friendship. Did this fail because of intractable leadership style. Some partnerships arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t meant to be.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 17, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(67, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/try-a-little-tenderness/', '2014-09-01 00:00:00', 'Try A Little Tenderness ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Try A Little Tenderness</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/try-a-little-tenderness/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/try-a-little-tenderness/</a><br>There is a general perception in business that vulnerability in any form automatically equals weakness. Think about it; when was the last time you allowed yourself to be Ã¢â‚¬â€œ well, <em>you</em>in a corporate or business environment? As leaders, we tend to automatically don a suit of protective armour that shouts to the world Ã¢â‚¬ËœI am the best, the STRONGEST, because I am tough, and unyielding, and uncompromising, and I never fail! I have no weaknesses, none! And if you want to be on my teamÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ <em>you wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t have any either</em>!Ã¢â‚¬â„¢<br>HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a startling proposition.<br>What if we took the armour off and let our true selves show?<br>What if, just once, we allowed ourselves to be, in traditional parlance Ã¢â‚¬â€œ weak?<br>Being honest and authentic as a leader is a strength. Yes, you are making yourself vulnerable Ã¢â‚¬â€œ but you are also willing to be open and show your true personality and colours. The flow-on is greater engagement not only with your team but with your clients or customers. Likewise, admitting failure; you can''t get it right 100% of the time, but if failure comes as a result of passion, effort and striving for goals then donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t you want those working with you to understand that the game is worth the candle? Weakness, or Ã¢â‚¬ËœweaknessÃ¢â‚¬â„¢, can be a collaborative tool in so many ways.<br>Use your own particular weakness or vulnerability as a business strength. Use it to drive your determination and focus. If you hate speaking out and engaging with others in person but find it easy on a virtual basis, for example, express this to those in your circle of excellence. Use that spirit of trust and collaboration to help you improve your confidence.<br>To succeed in a truly collaborative commercial environment, we must accept our so-called weaknesses Ã¢â‚¬â€œ our abilities to be caring, to nurture, to actively listen, and to not only think outside the box, but to encourage our teams to think along with us.<br>Shake off the fatigue(s). And try a little tenderness.', 'Leaders need to be vulnerable too', 'Being honest and authentic as a leader is a strength. Use your own particular weakness or vulnerability as a business strength. Use it to drive your determination and focus. Use that spirit of trust and collaboration to help you improve your confidence.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 17, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(68, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 126, 'https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140820143034-31763519-the-5-club?trk=prof-post', '2014-08-20 00:00:00', 'The 5% Club', '', '<strong>Linkedin - The 5% Club</strong><br><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140820143034-31763519-the-5-club?trk=prof-post" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140820143034-31763519-the-5-club?trk=prof-post</a> <br>How many of you have heard of the Ã¢â‚¬â„¢5% ClubÃ¢â‚¬â„¢? Would you like to be a part of it?<br>They are the business owners, the self-starters, the entrepreneurs, the visionary CEOs, the ones who commit fully and wholeheartedly to the job of the dream Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and the dream of the job Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and work their way up the ladder.<br>HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the interesting thing about those amazing Ã¢â‚¬Ëœfive-percentersÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ though. If you ask any of them the question Ã¢â‚¬Ëœcould you have achieved this alone? Could you have seen this dream become a reality without support and collaboration and amazing thinkers around you?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢ Ã¢â‚¬â€œ I am willing to gamble that in the majority of cases the answer would be Ã¢â‚¬ËœnoÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.<br>Individually, yes, they are the super-nova with the idea that fires the imagination of the team Ã¢â‚¬â€œ but it takes the team to make that dream turn into a product, a concept, a package. As Richard Branson famously said, Ã¢â‚¬Ëœno-one can achieve success aloneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.<br><br>We <em>need</em> a team around us to:<br><br><ul type="disc"><li>challenge our thinking</li><li>force our curiousity</li><li>push our boundaries</li><li>help us be restless</li><li>pick us up when we fall</li><li>make us celebrate our little Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and big Ã¢â‚¬â€œ wins</li><li>strive for perfection, and, at the same time</li><li>understand that we are allowed to fail.</li></ul><br>Success is a lonely journey if you do it by yourself. Those who do stand by themselves rapidly realise that, and also miss out on that amazing cross-pollination that a team brings.<br>The world is such an exhausting place and we are moving so quickly in every aspect that itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s hard to stay focused! Technologically, advancement is so rapid that innovations are being forced every day in product design, functionality, delivery, how we market, how we communicate, with whom we communicate Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and via what forum.<br>Imagine doing this alone on the path to that 5% Club. Why not embrace collective thinking, energy, persistence and drive to add fuel and momentum to the trip to the top?<br>ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the secret that those in the Club already know.<br>So start your team engines.', 'Why we need a team to be successful', 'Challenge our thinking. Force our curiousity. Push our boundaries. Help us be restless. Pick us up when we fall. Make us celebrate our little Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and big Ã¢â‚¬â€œ wins. Strive for perfection, and, at the same time understand that we are allowed to fail.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 16, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(69, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 4, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/one-step-ahead/', '2014-07-28 00:00:00', 'One Step Ahead', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ One Step Ahead</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/one-step-ahead/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/one-step-ahead/</a><strong> </strong><br>How many times have you picked up a magazine on a flight or while sitting with a hard-won five minutes peace and quiet, and seen a brilliant idea Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and realised that your first reaction wasnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Ã¢â‚¬Ëœwow, I wish I had thought of thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢, but rather Ã¢â‚¬ËœI canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t believe I thought of something like thatÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ and did nothing about itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢. If the answer is at least once, then give yourself a good hard mental slap. If the answer is Ã¢â‚¬Ëœnever, because I act on my ideasÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ then congratulations Ã¢â‚¬â€œ you are one step ahead of the business pack. You have the edge.<br>Being an innovator, a disrupter, within your area of expertise, knowledge or ideation is not just about that a-ha moment. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about capitalising on it. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about realising the value of what you hold in your head or your hands and making it all happen. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about recognising a need and responding without letting fear take hold and therefore missing the golden opportunity. Sometimes itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about taking what someone else has done and putting a new spin on it, because letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s face it, there can only ever be one iPhone, one iPad, because there was only one Steve Jobs. <br>If you are a trailblazer you will seize an opportunity to take control of a situation and to see a project come to fruition. This is not just about having a dream. A true disrupter wants to see their idea, their project, actually come to life. They want to see it in action, whether it is a concept or a physical product. And this perhaps is where you need to ask yourself the question; do you have what it takes to be an innovator? Are you willing to give everything you have to follow your goal? Because being disruptive Ã¢â‚¬â€œ in terms of being willing to take chances and step out ahead of the crowd, to seize chances and be seen Ã¢â‚¬â€œ takes commitment.', 'What it takes to be an innovator?', 'ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about capitalising on it. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about realising the value of what you hold in your head or your hands and making it all happen. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about recognising a need and responding without letting fear take hold. Sometimes itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about taking what someone else has done and putting a new spin on it.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 15, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(70, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/c-is-for-confidence/', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 'Ã¢â‚¬ËœCÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Is For Confidence ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner - Ã¢â‚¬ËœCÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ Is For Confidence</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/c-is-for-confidence/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/c-is-for-confidence/</a><strong> </strong><br>Think about the number of times you have been in a restaurant, or a meeting, or a presentation, and that person walks in. You know the one I mean. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s THAT person. The one who effortlessly grabs everyoneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s eyes and attention. They arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t necessarily good looking, and they definitely arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t trying to capture anyoneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s glance. Nonetheless, they look as though they are moving with their own personal cheerleading squad and everyone wants a piece of their attention .<br>Call it an aura, call it presence if you like Ã¢â‚¬â€œ but it boils down to confidence. The confidence to know who you are, what you want, and where you are going; not just in life, but in your business direction.<br>Confidence is understanding yourself inside and out. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about being centred as a person in your own space. WhatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s your purpose? Your passion? ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s knowing your talk and walking itÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ and then being willing to share that talk with others from a place of generosity and authenticity. Because just as you may know who you are, if you pass that knowledge on, you are passing confidence on. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s like a positivity virus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ a vaccination against self-doubt.<br>Because the biggest killer of confidence in business, as in any of lifeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s journeys, is when we start to doubt ourselves, and the path that we are on. Part of growth is understanding when we donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know something, and being willing to say Ã¢â‚¬ËœI have no idea whatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s happening here Ã¢â‚¬â€œ I need that vaccination now thanks!Ã¢â‚¬â„¢<br>So many times we are told throughout our lives Ã¢â‚¬ËœyouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re simply not good enoughÃ¢â‚¬â„¢. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s very easy to simply shrug and say to ourselves Ã¢â‚¬Ëœwell, if someone says that, then it must be trueÃ¢â‚¬â„¢. You are the one who decides whether you are good enough. Nobody else. Once you take that step, I guarantee you that the first swish of those crepe paper pom poms will start being heard.<br>Because thatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the magic of confidence. And it comes from inside.', 'The magic of confidence', 'Confidence is understanding yourself inside and out. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about being centred as a person in your own space. WhatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s your purpose? Your passion? ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s knowing your talk and walking itÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ and then being willing to share that talk with others from a place of generosity and authenticity. ', 'Janine Garner', 180, 22, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(71, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-forget-to-ask-whats-in-it-for-me/', '2014-07-07 00:00:00', 'DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Forget To Ask: Ã¢â‚¬ËœWhatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s In It For Me?Ã¢â‚¬â„¢ ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner - Don''t Forget To Ask: "What''s In It For Me?"</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-forget-to-ask-whats-in-it-for-me/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/dont-forget-to-ask-whats-in-it-for-me/</a><br>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s in it for me?&rdquo; it&rsquo;s a question that makes a lot of people cringe. It&rsquo;s often seen as a selfish, self-serving query. When we make the biggest decisions of our lives, in any arena, &ndash; we are all, to a lesser or greater extent, making said decisions out of care for what <em>we&nbsp;</em>want. And if we aren&rsquo;t, then we absolutely should be.<br>Because let&rsquo;s get this straight &ndash; the starting point of any decision making process that involves you, has to <em>be</em> you. Unless <em>you</em> know your reason for what you are doing, either in your career, business or personal life, how can you possibly make the right choices and decisions? First and foremost, you should have enough belief in yourself, in your dreams and vision for your business and personal future. That vision is yours, and yours alone &ndash; and until you understand this, and are willing to embrace it and get it sorted, there will not be the ability to move forward.<br>This is particularly relevant to your business life, where the above question is definitely one of self-leadership, because it reflects the&nbsp;ability to own decisions and make proactive choices. If you are able to make firm and decisive choices about what you want on a personal level from your career and your business success story, chances are you are going to be an effective and proactive leader, who is able to be decisive and engage in proactive, value-connected work on a large scale.<br>You need to look after the self first, because only then can you give the best of yourself to others and further enhance yourself with an openness to receive. You are making sure that you are in charge of you.<br>Asking &ldquo;what&rsquo;s in it for me?&rdquo;&nbsp;creates&nbsp;a plan, a journey and provides your own inbuilt decision making tool. It helps to ground your personal values firmly and permanently.<br>Knowing what it is you want is a critical part of collaboration and gives you the ability to ask for the <em>right</em> help and support. Knowing what you want creates the direction of the journey &ndash; it allows you to see and hear opportunities as they present themselves, and equally to take control of decisions that you make along the way.', 'How to be an effective and proactive leader?', 'You should have enough belief in yourself, in your dreams and vision for your business. You need to look after the self first, because only then can you give the best of yourself to others and further enhance yourself with an openness to receive. Knowing what it is you want is a critical part of collaboration and gives you the ability to ask for the right help and support. ', 'Janine Garner', 180, 22, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(72, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 95, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/mirror-mirror/', '2014-05-04 00:00:00', 'Mirror, Mirror ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Mirror, Mirror</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/mirror-mirror/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/mirror-mirror/</a><strong> </strong><br>We have all been there at some stage of our business lives, whether it is with an idea or a product. One day we are the only one in town with this Ã¢â‚¬Ëœunique selling point''; the next, there are three people at our heels with a concept that feels horribly familiar. ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s OK, we say to ourselves comfortably, thereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s always room in the market for competition Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and besides, the original is always the best, right?<br>But what happens when business becomes personal and someone we trust showing an interest and excitement about what we do Ã¢â‚¬â€œ turns into imitation?<br>This is the key; if <em>you</em> allow it to be.<br>If you have a great idea, it is inevitable that others are going to see its inherent value, and either (in the worst scenario) directly copy it, or in some cases, improve on it. <br>If you believe in working openly and honestly, and yes, collaboratively, your intellectual property is going to be available to others. What is integral to you staying true to yourself is your ability to cope when someone chooses to (and I do put this term in quotation marks for a reason), Ã¢â‚¬ËœabuseÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ their knowledge of your vision. You have a product; they use what they have learned from you to make product.<br><br>My advice to you is this:<br><br><ul type="disc"><li>Do see it as flattery. If you werenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t doing something amazing, they wouldnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be trying to do it too.</li><li>Make sure that your core business ideas ARE protected Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the onus is on you to insure your intellectual property.</li><li>Remember that business is business, and lines will be crossed; sometimes the personal will be blurred Ã¢â‚¬â€œ it isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t nice, but it is human nature.</li><li>Be restless to stay ahead of the game Ã¢â‚¬â€œ at all times have a number of Ã¢â‚¬Å“new ideasÃ¢â‚¬Â? bubbling and in development.</li><li>DONÃ¢â‚¬â„¢T retreat into secret squirrel mode, but rather think long and hard about what you can do better, and ask for feedback from your closest supporters. Find your voice, and stand even more in your own spotlight.</li></ul><br>You may find that the relationship canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be resurrected, because the trust has gone from your perspective Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and this is OK. But donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t turn into the Ã¢â‚¬Ëœthey stole my ideaÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ person. You are better than that.', 'How to deal with imitators and protect your intellectual properties', 'Do see it as flattery. Make sure that your core business ideas ARE protected. Remember that business is business, and lines will be crossed. Be restless to stay ahead of the game Ã¢â‚¬â€œ at all times have a number of Ã¢â‚¬Å“new ideasÃ¢â‚¬Â? bubbling and in development. DONÃ¢â‚¬â„¢T retreat, but rather think long and hard about what you can do better, and ask for feedback from your closest supporters. ', 'Janine Garner', 180, 22, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(73, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/surfing-the-net/', '2014-04-24 00:00:00', 'Surfing The Net ', '', '<strong>Janine Garner Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Surfing The Net</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/surfing-the-net/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/surfing-the-net/</a> <br>Networking. A term that fills some with the excitement of possibility, some with a sense of absolute dread and others Ã¢â‚¬â€œ probably the majority of us Ã¢â‚¬â€œ with a combination of both feelings, the <em>Ã¢â‚¬Å“I really donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t want to but I know I mustÃ¢â‚¬Â?</em> crowd.<br>Networking is an absolute Ã¢â‚¬Ëœhas to happenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ for successful collaboration. The connections, skills, brain power and ideas which are openly discussed and shared through network creation in their turn create new opportunities, innovation and new solutions to existing problems. It is a domino effect Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the way your initial networks interact provide a guideline for the subsequent or flow-on networks that spring up from these collaborations. They will only benefit from your experience and way of working together.<br>Effective networking is a fundamental part of collaboration. The most innovative businesses and organisations are finding that collaboration and effective and powerful networking is giving them an edge.You only have to do the maths; I know one hundred people, they each know one hundred peopleÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ and the pyramid is built.. So how do you do it?<br>Building an effective network quite simply requires a conscious mind shift and attitude change. A shift from thinking about ME and what I will say, how interesting I am and what I can get from this conversation to thinking about WE.ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about a change in attitude, approaching the meeting of each new person with openness Ã¢â‚¬â€œ to listen, to learn, having a willingness to help and to contribute to their business thinking. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about making a personal commitment to deliver on any promises and, ultimately, to stay in touch.<br>Networking is about constantly exploring how you can contribute to anotherÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s success, how you can weave connections, knowledge and insight to benefit them. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about having no expectation of anything in return. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about give, give, give Ã¢â‚¬â€œ not take, take, take Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and keeping in touch because you want to Ã¢â‚¬â€œ not just when you want something.<br>As Richard Branson said <em>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Nobody can be successful alone.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</em><br>So why not try it together?', 'How to be effective at networking.', 'A shift from thinking about ME and what I will say, what I can get from this conversation.  A change in attitude, approaching the meeting of each new person with openness Ã¢â‚¬â€œ to listen, to learn, having a willingness to help and to contribute to their business thinking.  Making a personal commitment to deliver on any promises and to stay in touch.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 28, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(74, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://janinegarner.com.au/the-winners-attitude/', '2014-03-18 00:00:00', 'The WinnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Attitude', '', '<strong>Janine Garner - The WinnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Attitude</strong><br><a href="http://janinegarner.com.au/the-winners-attitude/" target="_blank">http://janinegarner.com.au/the-winners-attitude/</a> <br>Success. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s hard to put a label on it, but my personal definition is this: it is a culmination of ingredients Ã¢â‚¬â€œ physical and intellectual Ã¢â‚¬â€œ that we have the ability to control and influence if we choose to. <br>Sounds simple right?<br>And yet I constantly come across many business owners and thought leaders who will happily invest heavily in their mind and their work output Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and yet fail to invest equally in their overall well-being. The result? Burn-out. Exhaustion. An inability to think clearly. Total overwhelm. Reactive emotions. <br>I am an absolute believer that true success involves a 360 degree investment. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a long term strategy for an ever educated mind, a healthy body and a rested soul. In his book, Ã¢â‚¬Ëœ<a href="http://www.amazon.com/The-Power-Rest-Enough-30-Day/dp/B006Z2Z7Y6" target="_blank"><em>The Power Of Rest</em></a><em>Ã¢â‚¬Ëœ</em>, Matthew Edlund states that if we can combine the physical, the mental, the spiritual and the social the results are extraordinary.<br>A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude is critical to success. A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude is critical to achieving our business, career and personal goals Ã¢â‚¬â€œ those big picture dreams that we have for ourselves. A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude also is one of being brave enough to step out, re-group and re-set the hard drive to increase capability and capacity.<br>Part of that is admitting when it is time to say Ã¢â‚¬ËœenoughÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.<br>I appreciate itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not always easy. And yet I believe that time to stop and re-set is critical for us all. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not always easy to get away for four days, but it is easy to book a regular walk in the fresh air, have a coffee date with yourself and simply find time to stop.<br>Go on. Give it a go. Be brave.', 'The right attitude to be successful.', 'A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude is critical to success. A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude is critical to achieving our business, career and personal goals Ã¢â‚¬â€œ those big picture dreams that we have for ourselves. A winnerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s attitude also is one of being brave enough to step out, re-group and re-set the hard drive to increase capability and capacity. Admitting when it is time to say Ã¢â‚¬ËœenoughÃ¢â‚¬â„¢.', 'Janine Garner', 180, 98, '2014-11-24 13:39:36', '2014-11-24 13:39:36', 0),
(75, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140926063751-3885475-tips-for-applying-for-a-tech-accelerator?trk=prof-post', '2014-09-26 00:00:00', 'Tips for Applying for A Tech Accelerator', '', '<strong>Linkedin - Tips for Applying for A Tech Accelerator</strong><br><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140926063751-3885475-tips-for-applying-for-a-tech-accelerator?trk=prof-post" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/article/20140926063751-3885475-tips-for-applying-for-a-tech-accelerator?trk=prof-post</a><br><br>I''ve whipped together my thoughts on the written application you submit;<br><ul type="disc"><li>Writing less material is easier to digest and more likely to be digested at all. i.e write less. Be specific and donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t use buzzwords.</li><li>Do something to stand out from the other 179 applications.</li><li>Show revenue. If you can''t show revenue, show traction, if you can''t show traction, show tenacity. If you can''t show tenacity, go be tenacious. </li><li>Give me a hugely ambitious vision and a believable starting point.</li><li>Show us why this is more to you than something you thought about over the weekend.</li><li>When talking about your team, tell us what each of them will do.</li><li>Give us a video that lets us get to know you not just a walk through.</li><li>Come to events or contact us. If you connect with us 4+ times then we''ll remember you.</li><li>Be aware if people have tried this idea before. (Hint: 99% of the time they have). </li><li>Give something back. Create some content or do something that shows you''re prepared to share.</li><li>We''re after digital technology businesses, so show us you live and love technology.</li><li>We''re about people, so do anything you can to show us personality and emotion.</li><li>Read about the companies that got in last time. What were they like? Contact them?</li><li>Get someone who has built a tech business to read your application before you submit it.</li><li>Again, write less. It takes more time to write less, but it''s worth it.</li></ul><br>', 'Advise on written application when seeking funding', 'Write less. Stand out. Show revenue. Give ambitious vision. Show why it''s more to you. Tell your team''s individual function. Show a video. Connect. Be aware. Create content. Embrace technology. Show your personality and emotion. Read about companies that got in last time. Get someone to review your application. Write less.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 48, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0);
INSERT INTO `advices` (`id`, `co_author_first`, `co_author_last`, `challenge_id`, `decision_type_id`, `category_id`, `source_url`, `advice_decision_date`, `advice_title`, `advice_image`, `executive_summary`, `challenge_addressing`, `key_advice_points`, `publication_name`, `context_role_user_id`, `advice_views`, `advice_posted_date`, `advice_update_date`, `status_id`) VALUES
(76, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://pollenizer.com/sales-focus/', '2014-08-06 00:00:00', 'Sales Focus', '', '<strong>Pollenizer - Sales Focus</strong><br><a href="http://pollenizer.com/sales-focus/" target="_blank">http://pollenizer.com/sales-focus/</a> <br/> Startups are hard. But life is better when you have sales. Here is why I encourage people to spend a ratio of 50:1 on sales versus capital.<br/> The goal is to build a business, not start a startup. Good business is the creation of value and the realisation of that is profit, which is when your revenues are more than your costs. You want to keep your costs down but none of that matters without revenue.<br/> <strong>Sales shows value</strong> <br/> Product market fit is the goal of all startups and nothing says that those two things fit together in a real, business like way than sales. A customer saw so much value in the product that they gave you hard earned money for it.<br/> <strong>Sales pays for things</strong> <br/> Cash in the bank lets you pay for servers, 2 minute noodles, bandwidth. For team members, it&rsquo;s a great day when your equity is worth more than cash, so you would rather pay for things than give away equity.<br/> <strong>Sales pays for growth</strong> <br/> Having a scalable growth model means when you spend a dollar on sales and marketing, more than a dollar comes back. Without revenue, the only way to keep growing is diluting through capital raising or crossing your fingers for &lsquo;going viral&rsquo;.<br/> <strong>Sales attracts investors</strong> <br/> Of all the numbers we think about sales is the hardest for someone to reject. Visits, users, engagement and retention are all nice but nothing says &lsquo;there is something here&rsquo; to an investor like sales.<br/> <strong>Sales avoids investors</strong> <br/> On the flip side, having enough sales can mean that you don&rsquo;t need an investor. Who wants to raise money if they can fund costs and growth with sales?<br>So stop going to capital raising events and start going to sales events. Read sales books. Hire sales people. Be a salesperson.', 'Why you need to do more sales rather than raise capital', 'Sales shows value. Sales pays for things. Sales pays for growth. Sales attracts investors. Sales avoids investors.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 25, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(77, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/three-key-metrics/', '2014-03-06 00:00:00', 'Three Key Metrics', '', '<strong>Startup Focus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Three Key Metrics</strong><br><a href="http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/three-key-metrics/" target="_blank">http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/three-key-metrics/</a> <br>There are lots of metrics which you need to track, understand and build on to run a good business which is why I suggest trying to find three key numbers to know if itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s really working.<br><strong>Why 3?</strong> <br>The reason three is a good number is because it canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t possible include everything you need to track. You need to pick those that really matter. <br>The other reason why 3 is good, is it makes you find a simple way to communicate progress which is important for team, investors, spouses and yourself. <br><strong>Which 3?</strong> <br>The rule should be that if this number improves, your business is substantially working. It should be an indicator of real value. Something substantial that canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be faked, crammed for or easily replicable. <br>Here are some of the things I look for in a good metric.<br><strong>Value To Your Customer</strong> <br>One of the best metrics to track is the actual value you create for your customer. I often say that you need to create 10x value for new customers of a new product which means if the total cost of the product (including price, risk, time, etc) is $100 then you need to add $1,000 of value to get them to use it. So understanding the value your customers get and measuring it is obviously a great metric to track. <br><strong>Actioned confirmation of value</strong> <br>I like numbers which mean that there has been clear acknowledgement by a real customer that they got value out of the product. Unfortunately this doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t just mean a sale. A sale may mean that youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re good at sales. It doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t mean that you created value that the customer appreciated. The second sale does. Or a renewal does.<br>For a free product, it needs to be serious usage to show that people are really using your product. Typically this means usage multiple times over a sustained period. <br><strong>Externally Valued</strong> <br>Another test is would that number be meaningful to someone outside the organisation. i.e. an investor. This can also be looked at as sellable value Ã¢â‚¬â€œ if you had a bunch of that metric would someone buy this. People buy contracts with customers or seriously engaged users that are in some way locked in.<br><br><strong>Examples of Good Ã¢â‚¬Å“3 MetricsÃ¢â‚¬Â?</strong><ul type="disc"><li>Renewed paying customers.</li><li>People used the product three days in a row.</li><li>Gross profit from renewed customers.</li><li>Conversion of trial to paid Ã¢â‚¬â€œ means they saw the value and want to commit to it.</li><li>Money saved for your customers.</li><li>Time saved for your customers.</li><li>Money made for your customers.</li></ul>', 'The things you need to look for in a good metric', 'Value To Your Customer. Actioned confirmation of value. Externally Valued.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 24, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(78, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 24, 'http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/business-plans-for-startups/', '2014-03-04 00:00:00', 'Business Plans for Startups', '', '<strong>Startup Focus - Business Plans for Startups</strong><br><a href="http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/business-plans-for-startups/" target="_blank">http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/03/business-plans-for-startups/</a> <br>Planning is useful. Plans are most often useless. Especially in startups.<br>The process of planning is important and my suggestion is to scale your planning with your business.<br><ul type="disc"><li>Before you start Ã¢â‚¬â€œ keep it very simple and do a one page business plan, business canvas or my version of the canvas. <a href="http://bit.ly/focuscanvas">MickÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Focus Canvas</a></li><li>Discovery phase Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Use your canvas until you have spoken to at least 5 customers and done at least 5 experiments. After that, start a brand new canvas. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t edit the old one.</li><li>Validation phase Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Do a pitch deck to present, not to read through. Start with the Universal Pitch Deck and make sure all questions are answered satisfactorily. Make sure it flows as a story and there are no gaps. </li><li>Efficiency stage. You can either do a pitch deck to read through, as this will lead to a better flow, or you can do a 5 page business plan. No longer. Most of this should be dedicated to how you are going to make it efficient and your current hypothesis on scaling. Plus capital requirements. If you are raising more than $1m at this stage, you might need to refer to this as an Information Memorandum or IM in Australia. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a non-audited investor document.</li><li>Scale stage. If you are looking for real scale capital (which means that 90% of the money raised will be going to growing sales or customer acquisition) then you might need a 10-15 page business plan or IM. YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d be raising $2-10m at this time.</li></ul><br>Important note. A business plan will never get you funded. It will only stop you not getting funded. So if you have a good plan it might answer all the questions an already interested investor has and show to them that youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve thought it through.', 'Your guide to writing business plan', 'Before you start - do a one page plan.  Discovery phase - experiment. Validation phase - do a pitch deck. Efficiency stage. Scale stage.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 18, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(79, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 90, 'http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/location-still-matters-for-tech-businesses/', '2014-01-16 00:00:00', 'Location still matters for tech businesses', '', '<strong>Startup Focus - Location still matters for tech businesses</strong><br><a href="http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/location-still-matters-for-tech-businesses/" target="_blank">http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/location-still-matters-for-tech-businesses/</a> <br>Despite more communication and collaboration tools than ever, having a tech business team in the same location is still a big factor in increasing your chance of success.<strong>Yes, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s possible to run a team globally, but it is significantly harder than having them in the same room.</strong>This is why:<br><strong>Forming takes time.</strong><strong><br></strong>If the company or the team is new, it helps to have lots of small moments which arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t about the business to form the relationship. Your chance to have a chat over coffee, food, drinks goes way up and that is where trust and depth is established.<br><strong>Words arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t enough.</strong><br>Online communication tools miss body language, emotion and other elements which are critical in young relationships but also in difficult moments. Emails, instant messaging, project management tools and user stories are limited.<br><strong>Tiny sharing.</strong><br>Getting a business working, especially a new, innovative idea isnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t about day long workshops, spreadsheets, or moments of brilliance. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s 1,000 little conversations that slowly move you towards your vision.<br><br>There are conversations that you generally donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t have in an IM and you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t bother calling someone. But you do if they are 3 metres away.<br>Lots of tiny sharing is the duct tape that builds startups.<br>Yes, you can have a successful new company with a new team doing a new thing with everyone in different locations and different timezones. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s just much harder, more risky and less likely to succeed.', 'The downsides of building a global tech business', 'Forming takes time. Words arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t enough. Tiny sharing.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 22, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(80, NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 135, 'http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/exit-or-stay/', '2014-01-15 00:00:00', 'Exit or Stay?', '', '<strong>Startup Focus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Exit or Stay</strong><br><a href="http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/exit-or-stay/" target="_blank">http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/exit-or-stay/</a> <br>Stu Fox is taking the role of the Ã¢â‚¬ËœvultureÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ capitalist, saying Ã¢â‚¬Å“Sell, sell, sell!!!Ã¢â‚¬Â?. OK, no, heÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not doing that at all. The reason I asked Stu to join us in this chat is because he made some great points about how exits can be good for the entrepreneur and also good for the ecosystem. From my chat with Stu, here are my thoughts on why an exit can be the right thing to do;<br><ul type="disc"><li><strong>Change</strong>. Your circumstances may change, the customers may change, the market may change. Any of these may mean that the original vision and the passion to build towards it is no longer strong enough to sustain you. In this situation it may be best to sell the business and find a new vision/passion to pursue. </li><li><strong>Help needed.</strong> There are times when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re vision needs significant help from a partner in order to be achieved. You might need distribution, IP, or other things that are impossible or just too high risk to pursue on your own. Lots of buy outs donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t work out well, but some are just what is needed. Certainly having a strategic reason to buy a company leads to a better price, and hopefully a better outcome. </li><li><strong>Version 2.</strong> If itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s your first success, and youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made so many blunders, flearns and pivots along the way that youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re tired and want to have another crack, then selling the business, taking some money and starting a new company with your new wisdom and cash can be a good idea. </li></ul><br><strong>Exits for Momentum?</strong> <br>What is good for the founder is always the most important, but itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s also good to consider the benefits for the community. All other things considered, some companies meeting the above criteria and exiting Ã¢â‚¬ËœearlyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ instead of staying for the long haul can create a feeling of momentum in the market. <br><strong>Entrepreneurs Into Angels</strong> <br><strong>It Depends</strong> <br>Yep, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a soft answer, but obviously it depends on the situation. What Mike is going to say is that far too many people are aiming to exit rather than aiming to build a business that lasts 100 years. <br><strong>Exit Buddy</strong> <br>Having the experience of Stuart Fox and the confidence of Mike Cannon-Brookes is one thing but how does the average founder even take a breath and think about staying on for the long, long, long haul to build the vision they always wanted. There are a few good things we can do to at least support a tough, big decision;<br><ul type="disc"><li>Talk about it. The first big moment that exit is really considered is right at the start of a business. Am I building this to make a buck or because I do really care? Maybe we can influence that moment.</li><li>Exit buddy. The second big moment that an exit is considered is when a term sheet is put in front of you. Ã¢â‚¬Å“Do you really want to sell?Ã¢â‚¬Â? Ã¢â‚¬Å“Why did you start this business?Ã¢â‚¬Â? Ã¢â‚¬Å“What happens if you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t sell?Ã¢â‚¬Â?.</li></ul>', 'Why exit can be the right thing to do', 'Your circumstances may change, the customers may change, the market may change. There are times when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re vision needs significant help from a partner in order to be achieved. If itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s your first success, and youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made so many blunders, flearns and pivots along the way that youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re tired and want to have another crack, then selling the business and starting a new company with your new wisdom and cash can be a good idea.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 24, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(81, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/simplevshugestartuppitchingconflict/', '2014-01-14 00:00:00', 'The Simple vs Huge Startup Pitching Conflict', '', '<strong>Startup Focus - The Simple vs Huge Startup Pitching Conflict</strong><br><a href="http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/simplevshugestartuppitchingconflict/" target="_blank">http://www.liubinskas.com/2014/01/simplevshugestartuppitchingconflict/</a> <br>In any pitch one of the biggest challenges is to clearly demonstrate what your product does as while also showing it has huge potential.<br>This is made harder by the fact that investors want you to small, simple and focused because youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re early stage and they want a nice piece. <br><strong> Ã¢â‚¬Å“What are you?Ã¢â‚¬Â?</strong> <br>The first challenge is for the investor to know what you are. A demo is often the best way to really show what you do, but donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t just walk through the product, demo the value. If you can do this while youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re telling a story and creating a persona in the mind of the investor all the better. <br>The two things youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re after at this stage is understanding and empathy. <br>Knowing how to explain it simply and meaningfully is critical. Even if it sounds stupid and any good investor should know, just say it and get it out of the way:<br><ul type="disc"><li>Ã¢â‚¬Å“We are a web based application for businesses.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</li><li>Ã¢â‚¬Å“We are an online marketplace for catering.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</li><li>Ã¢â‚¬Å“We are an online software program that acts as your CFO.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</li><li>Ã¢â‚¬Å“We are a mobile application.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</li><li>Ã¢â‚¬Å“We are a table game.Ã¢â‚¬Â?</li></ul><br><em>Tip: In any pitch, say one thing multiple times to ensure itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s remembered.</em> <br><strong>Size Counts</strong> <br>Once people get what you are, you need to show them that you can be big. <br>There are lots of ways to show size and you need to experiment to see what resonates. Saying that youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re product is in a $100B market is OK but itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s too big to grasp and becomes meaningless. Also investors become skeptical of these big numbers so make sure that it clearly correlates. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s OK if itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a little bit expansive but make sure itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a logical leap. <br><strong>The Weet Bix Test</strong> <br>When planning any pitch I do the Corn Flakes test. What will the person you pitch to say to their significant other the morning after your pitch, over their Weet Bix.<br>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Morning honey, how was the pitch event last night?Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Good, I saw this company called Zibbet.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Yeah, what do they do?Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Um, they have replaced Etsy as the go to market place for hand crafted goods globally and do $1m in revenue per month.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br>Ã¢â‚¬Å“Wow, sounds good, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll get the cheque book.Ã¢â‚¬Â?<br>The morale of the story is;<br>You have to find out what works for your business and your style of pitching, but make sure that along with the one thing you say multiple times that you also make sure you:<br><ul type="disc"><li>Clearly and simply articulate what you do, even if itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s boring.</li><li>Excitedly and convincingly say how big you could be, even if itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s crazy.</li></ul>', 'Startup Pitching Tips', 'What are you? - demo the value, telling a story and creating a persona in the mind of the investor. Size Counts - show them that you can be big. The Weet Bix Test - find out what works for your business and your style of pitching. Clearly and simply articulate what you do. Excitedly and convincingly say how big you could be.', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 28, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(82, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 40, 'http://pollenizer.com/how-to-prioritise-your-user-flow/', '2013-07-18 00:00:00', 'How to prioritise your user flow', '', '<strong>Pollenizer - How to prioritise your user flow</strong><br><a href="http://pollenizer.com/how-to-prioritise-your-user-flow/" target="_blank">http://pollenizer.com/how-to-prioritise-your-user-flow/</a> <br>Here is a quick idea if youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re having a healthy, assertive debate about user flow through your startup.<br>Key to a good flow for me is to be able to tell a logical story. It should actually flow without any huge leaps of faith. I also like it when there is one strong path to follow. A single path is easier to optimise, especially for first time users. Be aggressive. Guide them to the value. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t leave it to chance.<br><br>This is bad;<br><ul type="disc"><li>A user finds the website somehow.</li><li>They read the headline, read the page, read all the material.</li><li>They fill out a 3 page form with all their information.</li><li>We email them and activate their accountÃ¢â‚¬Â¦</li></ul><br>This is good;<br><ul type="disc"><li>A user clicks a google ad and comes to the home page.</li><li>They read the headline and browse down to look at features.</li><li>They click free trial and they give us their email address.</li><li>They start their free trial, get hooked and start paying us.</li></ul><br>This is better;<br><ul type="disc"><li>A user clicks a google ad and comes to a landing page for that ad.</li><li>They read the headline and click a single big button to take the next step.</li><li>They take a few more quick, obvious steps and already start using the product and get the value.</li><li>They have created some value and now want to sign up or take the next stepÃ¢â‚¬Â¦.</li></ul>', 'Tips to a better user flow.', 'To be able to tell a logical story. It should flow without any huge leaps of faith. There is one strong path to follow. ', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 29, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(83, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://pollenizer.com/focus-on-a-niche-the-width-of-your-nose/', '2012-10-03 00:00:00', 'Focus On A Niche The Width of Your Nose', '', '<strong>Pollenizer - Focus On A Niche The Width of Your Nose</strong><br><a href="http://pollenizer.com/focus-on-a-niche-the-width-of-your-nose/" target="_blank">http://pollenizer.com/focus-on-a-niche-the-width-of-your-nose/</a> <br>One of Stuey''s mates starts telling us about his business. I asked a few questions and, for the sake of this quick letter, here''s what unfolded: What''s your niche?<br>This guy was a landscaper. But there are literally hundreds, maybe thousands, of landscapers in Sydney and it turns out that he works all over Sydney.<br>He advertises on Google, get calls from all over the joint"  It turns out that the most proÃ¯Â¬Â?table work that this guy performs is decking jobs within about a 5-10km radius of where he lives.<br>So, I said - mate, why don''t you just jump on Google Maps for 4 hours and look in the backyard of every house within your neighbourhood and work out whether they need a deck. Then you could afford another 4 hours to write each one of them a personal letter offering to come and install a deck. <br>The point is...<br>Until you''re working in a market so tight that it can be measured and deÃ¯Â¬Â?ned by where its people live, what they do, how old they are, how much they earn, where they typically spend their money and what they care about, the world is just too big and loud for you to ever get noticed. Or, more simply, Ã¯Â¬Â?nd a ridiculously small niche and service the heck out of it.<br>It seems scary to turn your back on the mass market because of its<br>size and potential but, until you do, it''s going to be awfully tough for you to<br>get known.<br>Here are some beneÃ¯Â¬Â?ts from Ã¯Â¬Â?nding a niche no wider than your nose:<br>1. SEO becomes super cheap<br>2. Customer acquisition costs halve<br>3. You get market-monopoly style margins<br>4. You can integrate vertically to grow (ie you can sell your<br>customers things beyond your original product because they trust<br>you because you''re THE expert in your Ã¯Â¬Â?eld).', 'BeneÃ¯Â¬Â?ts from Ã¯Â¬Â?nding a niche no wider than your nose', 'SEO becomes super cheap. Customer acquisition costs halve. You get market-monopoly style margins. You can integrate vertically to grow. ', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 37, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(84, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://pollenizer.com/everyone-is-your-customer/', '2012-09-27 00:00:00', 'Everyone Is Your Customer', '', '<strong>Pollenizer Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Everyone Is Your Customer</strong><br><a href="http://pollenizer.com/everyone-is-your-customer/" target="_blank">http://pollenizer.com/everyone-is-your-customer/</a> <br>After reading this great blog post by <a href="http://blog.asmartbear.com/stealth-mode.html" title="Stealth Mode for Startups by Jason Cohen" target= "blank">Jason Cohen on Stealth Mode</a> I thought IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d share some other great UnStrategies for building startups.<br><ul type="disc"><li><strong>Everyone is your customer.</strong> The bigger your market, the bigger your business. Make something for everyone to maximise the width of your funnel. Keeping it generic is the best way to make sure everyone can use it. To start with, just put it out there and see what comes back.</li><li><strong>First mover advantage is key.</strong> Once you tell more than 3 people, people will start copying you because the idea is so brilliant. What will startle most people is that no one had thought of it before.</li><li><strong>Once itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s built, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s done.</strong> DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t worry about bringing on tech people. You just need tech people to build it, then you can run it. Most web businesses can be updated every few years.</li><li><strong>Apps are easy money.</strong> You can get them done on Odesk for $500 and then make millions.</li><li><strong>Viral marketing is the best marketing.</strong> With just a twitter account and Facebook page people will start telling all their friends about you. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t spend a dollar on marketing.</li><li><strong>Research is fact</strong>. By doing focus groups and surveys you will be able to be sure that a business will work. Numbers donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t lie.</li><li>.<strong>com means global.</strong> By having a .com and being online means that you are available in 186 countries.</li><li><strong>Free is unbeatable.</strong> How can someone not use a free product? TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d be stupid. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s valuable and doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t cost anything.</li><li><strong>Patent NOW.</strong> One day Microsoft, Apple or Google (or all 3) will try and copy you and youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be able to sue them. Your first dollar spent should always be on lawyers.</li></ul>', 'Some great UnStrategies for building startups.', 'Everyone is your customer. First mover advantage is key. Once itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s built, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s done. Apps are easy money. Viral marketing is the best marketing. Research is fact. .com means global. Free is unbeatable. Patent NOW. ', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 40, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(85, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://pollenizer.com/the-temptation-of-white-labelling/', '2012-01-18 00:00:00', 'The Temptation of White Labelling', '', '<strong>Pollenizer Ã¢â‚¬â€œ The Temptation of White Labelling</strong><br><a href="http://pollenizer.com/the-temptation-of-white-labelling/" target="_blank">http://pollenizer.com/the-temptation-of-white-labelling/</a> <br>White labelling your product might sound like a great way to have a second revenue stream and make some fast cash, but it is hard, a big distraction and often just means youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re not strong enough yet.<br>Ideas in no particular order:<br>Focus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ If you want to be a direct to customer business AND a white label business when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re a startup you are going to find it very very very hard. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s two different businesses. Different customers, different products, different marketing, different all round. White label is a great business model Ã¢â‚¬â€œ so if you want to do it, do it, but close down your direct to customer business and focus on White Label.<br>Not ready Ã¢â‚¬â€œ often times when you speak to potential customers early in your life as a business they will ask if you white label. What they are really saying is Ã¢â‚¬Å“YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve got a good base idea here, but our brand is stronger than your product and our skills can finish it off.Ã¢â‚¬Â? ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s fine, it just means that customer is not ready for you yet. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t bust your gut to look after them because most likely they still wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be happy. When someone wants a white label product they expect it to really work. Most likely youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re not going to be able to give them this and youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll spend a lot of time trying to keep it going.<br>Scale Ã¢â‚¬â€œ white labelling can get you a small number of large customers, but often not a large number of customers. Make sure youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve got your market worked out and pricing else you might sell yourself into a corner.<br>Customer contact Ã¢â‚¬â€œ you also lose contact with the users. There is now someone between you and the daily usage. This is harder earlier on when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re still concocting your magic and need lots of good feedback.<br>Brand Ã¢â‚¬â€œ youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re brand is now a behind the scenes brand, not an in-front brand. ThatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s fine, lots of great companies are like this, but just be aware.', 'Some ideas when white labelling', 'If you want to do it, do it, but close down your direct to customer business and focus on White Label. Not ready - when someone wants a white label product they expect it to really work. Scale - Make sure youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve got your market worked out and pricing. Customer contact Ã¢â‚¬â€œ you also lose contact with the users. Brand Ã¢â‚¬â€œ youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re brand is now a behind the scenes brand, not an in-front brand (just be aware).', 'Mick Liubinskas', 181, 68, '2014-11-24 13:52:36', '2014-11-24 13:52:36', 0),
(86, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/four-strategies-to-effectively-listen-to-your-gut/', '2014-06-18 00:00:00', 'Four Strategies for Listening to Your Gut', '', ' <strong>Unreasonable.is - Four Strategies for Listening to Your Gut</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/four-strategies-to-effectively-listen-to-your-gut/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/four-strategies-to-effectively-listen-to-your-gut/</a><br/>I recently wrote <a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/listening-to-your-gut-lets-give-it-the-credit-it-deserves/" target="_blank">this post</a> on how we need to rebrand the notion of a gut-instinct as being an individualÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Ã¢â‚¬Å“faster intelligence.Ã¢â‚¬Â? This gives gut reactions the credit they deserve. Rebranding the expression is only the first step, though. We need to develop mechanisms to make this faster intelligence louder, more lucid, and more pronounced. Below are four examples of how to liberate your faster intelligence. <br><br/><strong>1. Flip a coin.</strong><br/>Need to make an extremely important decision that could change the course of your life for the months or years to come? An easy way to help make that decision is to simply flip a coin. If you are torn between a binary decision, flip a coin and assign tails to Ã¢â‚¬Å“yesÃ¢â‚¬Â? and heads to Ã¢â‚¬Å“no.Ã¢â‚¬Â? Then, when the coin lands on either side, listen to the immediate gut reaction you feel to the results of the coin toss. If you feel a sense of sadness or disappointment, then you know that you need to do the opposite of what the coin told you.<br><br/><strong>2. Drink beer.</strong> <br/><a href="http://www.foundrygroup.com/" target="_blank">The Foundry Group</a> in Boulder has a simple value that I love. Before they will invest into a prospective startup, they ask themselves if the team they are going to invest in passes the Ã¢â‚¬Å“beer test.Ã¢â‚¬Â? In short, is it a team of individuals who they would enjoy having a beer with. If the answer is yes, then they move forward with looking at the deal; if the answer is no, they wonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t place the investment and they discontinue exploring the opportunity.<br><br/><strong>3. Eat dinner.</strong><br/>An incredible team leader, <a href="http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/caroline-whaley/47/3b/524" target="_blank">Caroline Whaley</a>, once told me a simple framework for knowing if you are working with the right team or not. She asked me to consider that if I went to dinner with my team, are there people IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d rather sit next to and others who IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d hope I didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t get sat next to? If the answer here is yes, that likely means you need to have a serious heart to heart conversation with the people you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t want to sit next to as something is clearly off.<br><br/><strong>4. Surround yourself.<br/></strong> ThereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a saying that you are the amalgamation of the five people who you spend the majority of your time with. If this is true, then I highly recommend ensuring that you spend a great deal of time with the type of people who will help give you permission to follow your intuition and listen to your faster intelligence. If none of the people you spend the majority of your time with encourage you along this trajectory, then I suggest seeking out a new friend or two, or immersing yourself into a new community, in addition to your current friends.', 'Four examples of how to liberate your faster intelligence.', 'Flip a coin. Drink beer. Eat dinner. Surround yourself.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 51, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(87, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/listening-to-your-gut-lets-give-it-the-credit-it-deserves/', '2014-06-06 00:00:00', 'Listening to Your Gut Ã¢â‚¬â€œ LetÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Give it the Credit it Deserves', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - Listening to Your Gut Ã¢â‚¬â€œ LetÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Give it the Credit it Deserves</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/listening-to-your-gut-lets-give-it-the-credit-it-deserves/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/listening-to-your-gut-lets-give-it-the-credit-it-deserves/</a> <br/>A few months ago, I was fortunate to catch up for an hour with <a href="http://www.alexbogusky.com/" target="_blank">Alex Bogusky</a>. Part way through our conversation we started to share some of the more significant entrepreneurial mistakes weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve made over the past year, these regrets were correlated directly to a time that we Ã¢â‚¬Å“out-smartedÃ¢â‚¬Â? our initial gut reaction. <br/>I am now convinced we need to rebrand the expression, Ã¢â‚¬Å“listen to your gut.Ã¢â‚¬Â? I think rebranding is the first step to preventing our rational minds from Ã¢â‚¬Å“out-thinkingÃ¢â‚¬Â? our raw intuition. <br><br/><strong>A Re-branding is Needed</strong><br/>I think that the reason we often ignore our gut is because it has been improperly branded. When we think of it as a gut reaction, it feels like our decision making process is nothing more than a fleeting feeling in our abdomen. In reality, as a good friend <a href="http://unreasonable.is/video/sometimes-life-throws-you-a-curveball/" target="_blank">Eduardo Garcia</a> recently told me, listening to your gut is your bodyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s millisecond reaction to a situation that is the result of all the decisions, experiences, and lessons youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve had throughout your entire life. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s your body making an intuitive response at the apex of all your life experiences. When you think about it in this light, you can start to see why listening to oneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s gut is actually a reputable source for making tough decisions. If I were to re-brand the word IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢d change it from Ã¢â‚¬Å“listen to your gutÃ¢â‚¬Â? to Ã¢â‚¬Å“listen to your faster intelligence.Ã¢â‚¬Â? <br><br/><strong>A Prediction</strong><br/>Just a few weeks ago I was sharing with George Kembel. George told me that he believes in the years to come we are going to see a massive shift in how leaders, teachers, parents, designers, and entrepreneurs make their decisions. George believes (and I agree) that soon, listening to your gut is going to become a compelling reference for making hard decisions and for making strategic decisions. <br/>So, I say letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s all get ahead of this trend and together, letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s re-brand the expression so that we give our gut-reaction the credit it deserves. If you call it your faster-intelligence youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll give yourself that important permission, and the confidence needed to follow it. The second step to making this as mainstream as George suggests, I believe, is to start building simple frameworks around how we can more easily hear and listen to this faster intelligence.', 'How and why listen to our gut', 'As individuals and as a society we need to start listening to our gut intuition and giving it the decision making credit it deserves. To give ourselves this permission, we ought to rebrand the expression to something like Ã¢â‚¬Å“listening to our faster intelligence.Ã¢â‚¬Â? In years to come we are going to see a massive shift in how leaders, teachers, parents, designers, and entrepreneurs make their decisions.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 38, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(88, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/theres-a-formula-to-doing-business-with-friends/', '2014-04-11 00:00:00', 'Debunking a Myth Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Why & How to Do Business With Friends', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - Debunking a Myth Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Why & How to Do Business With Friends</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/theres-a-formula-to-doing-business-with-friends/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/theres-a-formula-to-doing-business-with-friends/</a> <br/>If IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned anything over the years, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s that you should only do business with friends: with people you trust, admire, enjoy being around, and with people who make you laugh. Of course, there are good ways and there are bad ways of going about working with friends: Below IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve included what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned from trial and error about diving into working relationships and partnerships with those I consider to be my closest friends. <br/>How to do business with friends:<ul><li><strong>Communicate. Communicate. Communicate.</strong> The importance of sincere, authentic, and frequent communication cannot be understated. I do weekly 1-on-1 calls with all my partners and teammates, weekly meetings, daily quick standup meetings, once a month 48 hour work-sessions and once a quarter for a longer retreat. We talk about points of tension, points of gratitude, concerns, Ã¢â‚¬Å“yellow flags,Ã¢â‚¬Â? life beyond work, personal goals and aspirationsÃ¢â‚¬Â¦etc. This level of communication pay dividends and ensure that tensions never build up and that our team culture values authentic, frequent, and honest communication.</li><li><strong>Vest your ownership.</strong> Most co-founders start their companies by evenly splitting their ownership in the business between the friends they start the company with. But often times, this will end up in a disaster. For example, if you start a business with your best friend and split the equity 50/50, what if one year into the business your friend decides to take a full time job on Wallstreet? They will still own 50% of the company and now that they arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t actively working on the business, this will likely ruin your friendship. Instead, I recommend that you vest equity over a 4 year period and that you install what is called a one year Ã¢â‚¬Å“cliff.Ã¢â‚¬Â? This means that if any of the partners left the company within 12 months of starting the business, they will not get any equity (i.e. this is the Ã¢â‚¬Å“cliffÃ¢â‚¬Â?). By planning not just for the best but also for the potential of plans changing, you will save both your friendship and, likely, your company in the process. </li><li><strong>Make damn certain your motivations are inline.</strong> A good friend of mine had a brilliant team behind a new startup and everyone was motivated to make it happen. But when she sat down with her co-founders, she realized that their motivations were unsynchronized. Immediately, she listened to her intuition and decided not to continue with the startup. Typically with friends, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easy to dive into a startup opportunity or a working relationship that is exciting, fun, and could be lucrative. But if your motivations arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t aligned, whether itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s in a few months or a few years, your partnership will undoubtedly fall apart. </li><li><strong>DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t live together for too long.</strong> Although itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a fun way to start a new business and it ensures that you are all fully immersed, my feelings are that if you want to live with your friends + co-founders, do so with an exit strategy in mind (i.e. give it a set time commitment and after 6 months or 12 months, plan on living elsewhere). You will still likely see one another 16 hours a dayÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ but giving yourselves just a little space is important for any relationship.</li></ul>', 'How to do business with friends', 'Communicate. Vest your ownership. 3. Make damn certain your motivations are inline. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t live together for too long. ', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 22, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(89, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/are-you-climbing-the-right-mountain/', '2013-09-09 00:00:00', 'Effectiveness > Efficiency: Are You Climbing the Right Mountain?', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - Effectiveness > Efficiency: Are You Climbing the Right Mountain?</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/are-you-climbing-the-right-mountain/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/are-you-climbing-the-right-mountain/</a> <br/>When I started to take entrepreneurship seriously in my freshman year of University, I was obsessed with Ã¢â‚¬Å“moving quicklyÃ¢â‚¬Â? and being as efficient as possible. I saw productivity and my ability to grind through work as my edge. Today, I can say confidently that my focus point then, although important, was misguided. Nearly a decade later, and after having found or co-found 9 companies since, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve come to believe something different. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s best explained by this equation: effectiveness > efficiency.<br/>I used to scoff at the belief that working smart trumped working hard. From observation alone, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve never met an entrepreneur who has done something historically significant without pulling routine all-nighters. A big part of me has always agreed with Thomas Edison who said: Ã¢â‚¬Å“Genius is one percent inspiration, ninety-nine percent perspiration.Ã¢â‚¬Â? However, today, I now believe itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not that working hard trumps working smart. Instead, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s that as a team and as an individual, you must first work smart, then hard. Working hard first is an empty sense of productivity to an end not worth caring about. <br/>The most important question, far more important than the pace at which you reached the summit, is whether or not you climbed the right mountain. Today, I believe one of the most common causes of failure in the startup world is simple: you climbed the wrong mountain and you felt great the entire way up because you were moving at an incredibly fast pace. I am the first to attest, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve done this time and time again. IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve raced for the summit before I considered fully the context, our resources, the competition, or market timing. Today, at <a href="http://unreasonablegroup.com" target="_blank">Unreasonable Group</a>, we now ask ourselves once a week, Ã¢â‚¬Å“are we climbing the right mountain?Ã¢â‚¬Â? Climbing the right mountain is a new core value of our team. We live by it. And in my limited experience as an entrepreneur, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m willing to bet that living by this value is going to allow us to live much longer.', 'The key to being more productive', 'As a team and as an individual, you must first work smart, then hard. The most important question, far more important than the pace at which you reached the summit, is whether or not you climbed the right mountain.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 15, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(90, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 32, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/never-listen-to-the-experts-when-building-a-brand-listen-to-your-gut/', '2013-08-29 00:00:00', 'DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Waste Money On Ã¢â‚¬Å“ExpertsÃ¢â‚¬Â? When Building A Brand Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Listen To Your Gut', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Waste Money On Ã¢â‚¬Å“ExpertsÃ¢â‚¬Â? When Building A Brand Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Listen To Your Gut</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/never-listen-to-the-experts-when-building-a-brand-listen-to-your-gut/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/never-listen-to-the-experts-when-building-a-brand-listen-to-your-gut/</a> <br/><strong>Let me begin with the obvious:</strong> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m not a branding expert, not by a long shot. This is just one guyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s opinion on what not to do when creating a brand.<br/>Disclaimers aside, I think, for entrepreneurs, brand consulting firms and PR firms are the last outlet you want to explore when establishing your brand and getting your word out there. <br><br/><strong>Brands must resonate</strong><br/>A good brand resonates with the people you are trying to affect. And we resonate and feel most connected with authenticity, audacity, boldness, vulnerability, and the imperfections that come along with being human. Your brandÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s genesis must originate from your core and from the emotive reasons you are creating it. If you are an entrepreneur, you are about to dedicate the next 5 to 50 years towards solving a problem you desperately care about with an idea you obsessively believe in. Let that obsession and the vulnerability that comes along with trying to do something far larger than yourself, shine through your brand. Take the time to work with your team and build a brand that comes from you. Find the essence of why you do what you do and it is that essence that will pull on the heart strings and capture the intrigue of your customers and followers.<br><br/><strong>Great Brands donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t come from consensus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ They come from your gut</strong><br/>Bill Cosby when asked what the key to success was he responded by saying:<br/>I donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know the key to success, but the key to failure is trying to please everyone. <br/>If you are going to make a truly authentic and edgy brand, one that really resonates, I do not believe you can build this through consensus. Most consultancies and PR firms use a consensus based decision-making framework and although sometimes that is critical, when building a brand, this will ensure yours is average. A good example is how we even chose the name for the Unreasonable Institute. <br/>The first person I asked, naturally, was my mother (<em>as she is right about everything 99.99% of the time</em>). We then did a survey of 6 different names (<em>Unreasonable Institute one of them</em>) and sent it out to a friend base of a few hundred individuals. I then asked a few Ã¢â‚¬Å“expertsÃ¢â‚¬Â? in branding for their opinions on the Ã¢â‚¬Å“UnreasonableÃ¢â‚¬Â? name and they all agreed it was just too bold and one even said, too Ã¢â‚¬Å“irrationalÃ¢â‚¬Â?. They thought it might upset some people and that many others wouldnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t understand it. HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s the truth, they were probably right. But what IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned over the years is that you need to have Ã¢â‚¬Å“outsidersÃ¢â‚¬Â? to have Ã¢â‚¬Å“insidersÃ¢â‚¬Â? when it comes to a brand. You want to have a niche, an exclusive group who can say, proudly and unequivocally that they are Ã¢â‚¬Å“x.Ã¢â‚¬Â? (<em>Ã¢â‚¬ËœxÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ being the variable brand name, in our case, x=Ã¢â‚¬ËœunreasonableÃ¢â‚¬â„¢</em>).', 'Listening to your gut when establishing your brand', 'Brands must resonate - Your brandÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s genesis must originate from your core and from the emotive reasons you are creating it. Great Brands donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t come from consensus Ã¢â‚¬â€œ They come from your gut.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 24, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0);
