(91, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://unreasonable.is/skills/the-key-to-powerful-relationships/', '2013-07-22 00:00:00', 'The 7 Steps to Creating Powerful Relationships (Networking 101)', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - The 7 Steps to Creating Powerful Relationships (Networking 101)</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/skills/the-key-to-powerful-relationships/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/skills/the-key-to-powerful-relationships/</a> <br/>IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve never liked this age-old adage because it polarizes a phenomenon too complex to be black and white. Really, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about how you treat the people you know and donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about being excited and confident about what you do know and honest about what you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know. And if you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know someone, ideally this blog post will allow you to approach and get to know anyone.<br/>The 7 To Dos<br/><br/><strong>1) The Person You Are Talking To Is The Messiah In The Room.</strong><br/>One of the most important keys to building powerful relationships is never to avert your eyes when you are talking with someone else. Holding eye contact, even amidst a bustling room or people chatting nearby enables you to be fully present in your conversations and shows the other person how important they are to you. Assume, therefore, that the person you are conversing with is the momentary messiah.<br><br/><strong>2) Listen & Learn. Then Speak.</strong> <br/>When you meet someone, never start by talking about yourself. Ask them not just what they do, ask them why they do what they do and how they got to be doing what they do (i.e. their story). This will allow you to listen and to identify their interests, passions, and what excites them. You always want to connect on a human level (not just a professional level) and the key is to understand stories and interests. Learn what gets them excited and then get them excited. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s just that simple. <br><br/><strong>3) Be Vulnerable</strong> <br/>Your greatest strength in establishing powerful relationships is to be honest about your greatest weaknesses. The truth is that moments of vulnerability are the very moments when we connect most with other people. People are also much more likely to find you credible when youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re honest up-front about the risks of your venture or when you answer Ã¢â‚¬Å“I honestly donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know the answerÃ¢â‚¬Â? instead of trying to come up with a clever defense on the spot. <strong><br><br/>4) IsnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Networking Slimy?</strong><br/>When we think about networking, we think of people who cleverly manipulate others to get what they want. Instead, Keith Ferrazzi, the greatest networker in the world, defines networking as Ã¢â‚¬Å“sharing my knowledge and resources, time and energy, friends and associates, and empathy and compassion in a continual effort to provide value to others, while coincidentally increasing my own.Ã¢â‚¬Â? In other words, you should be seeing how you can help other people achieve their full potential. Relationships are built on trust. You gain trust by helping others, not by asking what they can do for you.<br><br/><strong>5) You Have to Make the Ask (no excuses):</strong> <br/>One of the most important rules of building relationships and networking is simply to ask. It all boils down to being truthful. If someone can really help you with something, do not be hesitant to ask. Indeed, most people are reluctant to ask for money, for advice, or for anything that could help them to a realized dream. When you ask for help, and if you do so genuinely, the worst anyone will say is Ã¢â‚¬Å“no.Ã¢â‚¬Â? Then you are no worse off than if you hadnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t asked for help at all! <strong><br><br/>6) Follow Up and Follow Through:</strong><br/>After any great conversation, follow-up by simply letting the person know how much you appreciate their time and thoughts. And if you want to distinguish yourself from nearly 99% of everyone out there, follow-through on the promises you make. The key to this statement is to make certain that when you tell someone you are going to do something, you will have the time to do it well.<br><br/><strong>7) Conviction is Paramount</strong> <br/>If you are going to get others excited about what you are doing you have to believe in what you are doing more than anyone else in the world. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be afraid to express your excitement and your unreasonable ambition. Remember though, you must be confident about what you do know, but equally important about what you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know. This level of transparency is key to building quality relationships and to networking. People are perceptive. If you arenÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t genuine, they will know it.', '7 To do''s when networking.', 'The Person You Are Talking To Is The Messiah In The Room. Listen & Learn. Then Speak. Be Vulnerable. IsnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Networking Slimy? You Have to Make the Ask (no excuses). Follow Up and Follow Through. Conviction is Paramount.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 20, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(92, NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 124, 'http://unreasonable.is/skills/nine-key-resources-for-beautiful-design/', '2013-07-04 00:00:00', '10 Key Resources For Beautiful (& Easy) Design', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - 10 Key Resources For Beautiful (& Easy) Design</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/skills/nine-key-resources-for-beautiful-design/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/skills/nine-key-resources-for-beautiful-design/</a> <br/>Today it is simpler than ever to create exceptionally designed websites, info-graphics, pitch decks, and products. Having now designed well over a dozen websites <em>(including this one)</em>, IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve learned that great design is not about coming up with an original idea from scratch. Instead, you can build upon many of the resources and ideas that already exist in the world. And, when you combine them in new waysÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ you are able to do great things quickly. This post exists to give you resources that have already done that for you. If you leverage the resources below, you will be shocked at how quickly you can come up with beautiful designs for your startup, company, campaign, or event. <br><br/><strong>1. Choosing the right font.</strong><br/><a href="http://dafont.com" target="_blank">dafont.com</a>. They have over 17,000 fonts, many of which will blow your mind, and they are all free and easy to install. <br><br/><strong>2. Finding the perfect color palette.</strong><br/>There are a number of sites that will help you select color palettes. These two are my favorite:<ul type="disc"><li><a href="http://kuler.adobe.com" target="_blank">Kuler.com</a>. Kuler has thousands of pre-set color palettes (<a href="https://kuler.adobe.com/#themes/rating?time=30" target="_blank">click here</a>) and they have a brilliant interface to help you make your own color palettes (<a href="https://kuler.adobe.com/#create/fromacolor" target="_blank">click here</a>).</li><li><a href="http://www.colourlovers.com/" target="_blank">Colourlovers.com</a>. This site has thousands of beautiful and uniquely designed color palettes. Great inspiration!</li></ul><strong>3. Textured backgrounds (a trick of the trade).</strong><br/><a href="http://subtlepatterns.com/" target="_blank">Subtlepatterns.com</a>. A good friend of mine, Evan Walden, recently shared this resource with me and IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m in love. The site has hundreds of patterns to give anything you design texture and lifeÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ and itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s 100% free.<br><br/><strong>4. Deciding which video player to use.</strong><br/><a href="http://vimeo.com" target="_blank">vimeo.com.</a>This is my personal opinion, but I think everything looks more beautiful in a Vimeo video player than on YouTube. I highly recommend using Vimeo for all your video uploads.<br><br/><strong>5. Iconography mattersÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ use this resource.</strong><br/><a href="http://thenounproject.com" target="_blank">thenounproject.com.</a>This is one of my favorite sites on the web right now. It contains an icon for nearly every noun in the world. This site is truly an incredible gift and the database of icons continues to grow each day. <br><br/><strong>6. Building websites.</strong><ul type="disc"><li><a href="http://Wordpress.org" target="_blank">WordPress.org</a> & <a href="http://www.squarespace.com/tour/overview/" target="_blank">Square Space</a>. With WordPress you can build a beautifully designed website, that comes with a template, in a matter of hours (instead of months). For an even simpler interface that is also beautifully designed, check out <a href="http://www.squarespace.com/tour/overview/" target="_blank">Square Space</a>. We built <a href="http://unreasonableatstate.com/" target="_blank">Unreasonableatstate.com</a> in hours with their platform. From my experience with it, Square Space is great for very simple content centric websites (i.e. not complicated platforms). WordPress is much more flexible and powerful and has a much larger user base / base of templates.</li><li><a href="http://Themeforest.com" target="_blank">Themeforest.com</a> has a library of over 7,000 WordPress templates <em>(many of which are outstandingly beautiful)</em>. </li></ul><strong>7. Creating business cards.</strong><br/><a href="http://graphicriver.net/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&term=business+card" target="_blank">Use this link</a>. They have over 6,000 business card templates.<br><br/><strong>8. Making pitch decks.</strong><br/><a href="http://graphicriver.net/search?term=presentation&category=presentation-templates" target="_blank">Graphic River</a> has over 500 presentations already built and <a href="http://www.haikudeck.com/" target="_blank" title="Haiku Deck">Haiku Deck</a> is a brilliant resource for anyone with an ipad. In minutes you can build out a beautifully designed deck directly on your ipad. <br><br/><strong>9. Designing your logo.</strong><br/><a href="http://99designs.com/logo-design" target="_blank">99designs.com</a> & <a href="http://www.crowdspring.com/logo-design/" target="_blank">CrowdSpring.com</a>. These sites will put tens of thousands of graphic designers on creating the perfect logo for you. On average, if you request a logo to these communities, you will get over 100 logos back that are customized to your needs. What is most amazing though is that if you donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t like any of the logos, you pay nothing. <strong>10. Newsletter.</strong> <a href="http://mailchimp.com" target="_blank">Mail Chimp</a>. There is not a platform for making, monitoring, and designing newsletters that compares to Mailchimp.', '10 Resources you can use when building & creating designs', 'Choosing the right font. Finding the perfect color palette. Textured backgrounds. Deciding which video player to use. Iconography matters. Building websites. Creating business cards. Making pitch decks. Designing your logo. Newsletter.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 28, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(93, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://unreasonable.is/opinion/reflection-on-japans-startup-culture/', '2013-02-27 00:00:00', 'JapanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Startup Culture Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Seven Key Takeaways', '', '<strong>Unreasonable.is - JapanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Startup Culture Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Seven Key Takeaways</strong><br/><a href="http://unreasonable.is/opinion/reflection-on-japans-startup-culture/" target="_blank">http://unreasonable.is/opinion/reflection-on-japans-startup-culture/</a> <br/>As part of having the world follow along with our journey around the globe, myself and George Kembel are going to start writing a quick reflection on key takeaways from each country we visit throughout the voyage. Our focus will be on the innovation cultures, startup communities, and creative ecosystems of the places we visit and the people we meet. This first post is a reflection on time spent in Japan. <br><br/><strong>Seven Takeaways From Japan</strong> <br><br/><strong>1. Etiquette is Paramount:</strong> Whether this is in regards to how your greet people or how important it is to delicately exchange business cards with both hands, or even how you should never pour your own sake, Japanese culture seemed to be centered around tradition, piety, and overt politeness.<br><br/><strong>2. Business Cards=SomeoneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Face:</strong> In Japan, a business card is seen as a representation of a personÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s identityÃ¢â‚¬Â¦ Specifically, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s seen as analogous to oneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s face. So when someone hands you a card, you must accept it with a bow and with two outstretched arms, you must admire it for an extended period of time, and you need to be careful to not fold it and to never let them see you put their card in your pocket. <br><br/><strong>3. Looks can be deceiving: </strong>I heard again and again that the greatest hindrance to having a vibrant entrepreneurial eco-system in Japan is rooted in people being too polite. Often times, someone will tell you that they love your idea or that they would like to work with you in one way or another. They will then go home and the truth will come out <em>(i.e. they think your idea is awful and they would never work with you)</em>. Without having a culture of constructive criticism and honest dialogue, itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s difficult for entrepreneurs to be challenged and to quickly get market feedback and advice from investors and mentors that they need to hear.<br><br/><strong>4. No dinner parties:</strong> It is very uncommon to go over to a friendÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s or a colleagueÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s house for dinner. In fact, it is so uncommon that I met two individuals who told me that in the past 5 years, both of them had only eaten 3 times in another friends or co-workerÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s house. Real networking happens over meals at restaurants and in the Karaoke bars.<br><br/><strong>5. Karaoke is no Joke:</strong> What I quickly learned is that in Japan, deals happen while you are making a fool of yourself and singing at the top of your lungs. Karaoke, although it may seem silly, is dead serious when it comes to business.<br><br/><strong>6. Design is Everywhere:</strong> While walking throughout the streets of Japan, there is an incredible amount of intention, design, and thought that seems to go into nearly every building, piece of art, garden, meal, greeting, and walkway. In todayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s world, where design is now obligatory, I feel that this attention to detail will give Japan a real leg up on other creative communities and startup ecosystems.<br><br/><strong>7. Incremental vs. Exponential:</strong> I heard again and again from entrepreneurs, politicians, and investors that what is holding Japan back most from having an explosive startup scene is that the Japanese are by-and-large risk adverse. The focus of most startups is on the 10% increase in efficiency or profit instead of on the 10x Ã¢â‚¬Å“moonshotÃ¢â‚¬Â? idea.', 'Seven business practices from Japan.', 'Etiquette is Paramount. Business Cards = SomeoneÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Face. Looks can be deceiving. No dinner parties. Karaoke is no Joke. Design is Everywhere. Incremental vs. Exponential.', 'Daniel Epstein', 182, 90, '2014-11-24 14:05:12', '2014-11-24 14:05:12', 0),
(94, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://blackbird.vc/the-physics-of-startup-financings/', '2014-05-01 00:00:00', 'The Physics of Startup Financings', '', '<strong>Blackbird Ventures - The Physics of Startup Financings</strong><br/> <a href="http://blackbird.vc/the-physics-of-startup-financings/" target="_blank">http://blackbird.vc/the-physics-of-startup-financings/</a> <br/>Or Why You CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Raise a Series A <br/> There is a fundamental paradox in the startup world: A lot more founders try to raise money than successfully do. But for those that do, they raise on incredibly friendly valuation terms relative to other areas of the business world. The reason is growth and itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s useful to apply the metaphors of physics to understand why. <br/> One of the most unanswerable questions I get as investor is Ã¢â‚¬Å“what do my metrics need to be to raise a series AÃ¢â‚¬Â?. I can give a guide on numbers but the reality is that the static one dimensional numbers ($100k MRR, 1m MAU or whatever the most important metric for the business is) are only half the story. <br/> IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll use the three simple concepts of physics Ã¢â‚¬â€œ distance, velocity and acceleration Ã¢â‚¬â€œ and use a SaaS business and monthly recurring revenue (MRR) to explain why. <br/> A common piece of advice, is that you need $100k MRR to raise a Series A ($5-10m) in todayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s market. But the problem with that simple answer is that itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s not about the $100k figure (the distance in this analogy) nor even about how quickly MRR is growing (velocity), itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s about how quickly the change in MRR is growing (acceleration). <br/> If you have a startup who grows to $100k MRR by adding $2k MRR each month for 50 months (4+ years), you are unlikely to be able to raise a Series A. If the $2k MRR you are adding doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t itself growing ever bigger (acceleration), the business is not a great candidate for venture financing. <br/> So the first step investors tackle is evaluating the foundation of the building (how engaged and happy are the customers, how often do they use the product, how rarely do they unsubscribe from it etc.) and then they bet on the law of compounding growth and hang on for a long period of time. <br/> The rate of growth really matters alot. Acceleration letÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s you keep that rate of growth. And itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s all about the acceleration not the distance.', 'Why You CanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t Raise a Series A', 'If you have a startup who grows to $100k MRR by adding $2k MRR each month for 50 months, you are unlikely to be able to raise a Series A. If the $2k MRR you are adding doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t itself growing ever bigger (acceleration), the business is not a great candidate for venture financing. Evaluate the foundation of the building (how engaged and happy are the customers, how often do they use the product, how rarely do they unsubscribe from it etc.).', 'Niki scevak', 183, 89, '2014-11-24 14:15:16', '2014-11-24 14:15:16', 0),
(95, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 126, 'http://blackbird.vc/ambition/', '2013-07-05 00:00:00', 'Ambition', '', '<strong>Blackbird Ventures Ã¢â‚¬â€œ Ambition</strong><br/> <a href="http://blackbird.vc/ambition/" target="_blank">http://blackbird.vc/ambition/</a><strong> </strong><br/> Ambition is not binary or static. Ambition is not something that exists or doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t from the beginning, you arrive at it after a journey.<br/> The concept of ambition is fascinating to me. Like urging a developer to talk to customers, the most common theme of advice I give to Australian entrepreneurs is to dial up their ambition. But those words are superficial and the truth is more subtle.<br/> Ambition is the process of turning over a series of rocks and discovering what works and what doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t. Ambition is the reaction to positive information: do you grow thirsty and change your behaviour to be more aggressive or do you continue along your merry way?<br/> Facebook was originally started as a way for a few college kids to meet girls and not even to be a company. Two years later, <a href="http://www.inc.com/allison-fass/peter-thiel-mark-zuckerberg-luck-day-facebook-turned-down-billion-dollars.html" target="_blank">it was so clear to Mark Zuckerberg Facebook should reject a billion dollar offer from Yahoo</a> that the board meeting lasted less than 10 minutes. The journey of ambition had been reached.<br/> To use a poker analogy: You canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t possibly know at the beginning if youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll win, but do you move all-in on the flop when your hand dramatically improves? That is to be ambitious.', 'The concept of Ambition', 'The process of turning over a series of rocks and discovering what works and what doesnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t. The reaction to positive information: do you grow thirsty and change your behaviour to be more aggressive or do you continue along your merry way?', 'Niki scevak', 183, 116, '2014-11-24 14:15:16', '2014-11-24 14:15:16', 0),
(96, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/11/05/the-simple-truth-about-how-to-be-more-effective/', '2014-11-05 00:00:00', 'The Simple Truth About How To Be More Effective', '', '<strong> The Simple Truth About How To Be More Effective</strong><br/><a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/11/05/the-simple-truth-about-how-to-be-more-effective/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/11/05/the-simple-truth-about-how-to-be-more-effective/</a><br/>Here&rsquo;s a challenge. It will take one minute- and WILL make a huge difference to your ability to achieve goals and success in what you do. And- it is simple. Up for it?<br>I was in Saigon last week. My colleague presented to the team an impressive plan for the first few months of 2015 &ndash; a plan to improve performance across their business. It was well thought out. Comprehensive. All the right actions were there. About 12 things that needed to be done. The team understood. And were aligned.<br>Now- at this stage I would normally have said...<br>', 'How to simplify your workflow ', '<ul> <li>Do less - and get more from it.</li><li>DROP things - to let them go. </li><li>Focus on the &lsquo;right things&rsquo; to get done.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 71, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(97, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/28/why-applying-the-brake-helps-you-accelerate-your-career/', '2014-10-28 00:00:00', 'Why Applying The Brake Helps You Accelerate Your Career', '', '<strong> Why Applying The Brake Helps You Accelerate Your Career</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/28/why-applying-the-brake-helps-you-accelerate-your-career/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/28/why-applying-the-brake-helps-you-accelerate-your-career/</a> <br/> I did something really weird in Melbourne last week. You see - I turned left. And by doing so, I was reminded of the biggest mistake I continue to make, in my life and career. Do you make it too? If &lsquo;yes,&rsquo; then STOP! And turn left, like me. Here&rsquo;s why.<br/> The day started early. Emails and calls, even while walking to the six hour intense training session for 30 of our STW Group up and comers that I then led. As soon as the session finished, it was back to urgent emails and phone messages, and a quick sit down...<br>', 'Why you need to slow down to accelerate your career', '<ul> <li>Sometimes you have to slow down to speed up.</li><li>Work to become a thought leader</li><li>Think about &lsquo;Brand You&rsquo;</li><li>Attend the talk, &lsquo;turn up&rsquo; when others just can&rsquo;t be bothered</li><li>Push yourself to be the very best you can be.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 21, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(98, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/14/the-key-to-a-winning-team-will-be-music-to-your-ears/', '2014-10-14 00:00:00', 'The Key To A Winning Team Will Be Music To Your Ears', '', '<strong> The Key To A Winning Team Will Be Music To Your Ears</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/14/the-key-to-a-winning-team-will-be-music-to-your-ears/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/10/14/the-key-to-a-winning-team-will-be-music-to-your-ears/</a> <br/> A chance meeting in Melbourne gave me a new insight into how to build winning teams. Here&rsquo;s what happened- and the lesson in it for you, your business, your life. <br/> We arrived at the restaurant. My 12 year old mate suddenly grabbed my arm: <em>&ldquo;LOOK! Look who it is!! It&rsquo;s it&rsquo;s Archie Thompson! And Besart Berisha!&rdquo; </em>- two strikers from the Melbourne Victory football club. The entire team was in the private dining room. We approached Thompson. He graciously chatted, and then invited us into the team dinner room. We looked in from the door. What an inspiring group of young people...<br>', 'How to build winning teams', '<ul> <li>If you are a leader, listen to the music in and from your team- does it feel right, strong, harmonious, on key? If not, then look squarely in the mirror, because YOU are the composer. </li><li>Give your team better music to work with. </li><li>You always have the choice to change the players.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 17, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(99, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/30/what-the-media-tycoon-told-me-about-building-success/', '2014-09-30 00:00:00', 'What The Media Tycoon Told Me About Building Success', '', '<strong> What The Media Tycoon Told Me About Building Success</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/30/what-the-media-tycoon-told-me-about-building-success/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/30/what-the-media-tycoon-told-me-about-building-success/</a><br/> I had been losing heart recently about something I love doing. Then, at breakfast last week with one of the most powerful media industry leaders in Australia- he said something that gave me the compass point to getting my mojo back. Simple. Powerful. It&rsquo;s a secret to success.<br/> CEO Mike asked me to join him at a breakfast meeting in Melbourne with a genuine icon of the Australian media industry. This leader had agreed to share his thoughts on how to build long term success in doing business in Indonesia. <br/> <strong>&ldquo;If you want to make progress, you simply have to keep schlepping around.&rdquo;...</strong> <br/>', 'How to build long term success', '<ul> <li>If you want to make progress, you simply have to keep schlepping around.</li><li>Keep turning up.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 16, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(100, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/24/how-to-keep-strong-when-the-pressure-is-on/', '2014-09-24 00:00:00', 'How To Keep Strong When The Pressure Is On', '', '<strong>How To Keep Strong When The Pressure Is On</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/24/how-to-keep-strong-when-the-pressure-is-on/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/24/how-to-keep-strong-when-the-pressure-is-on/</a> <br/> I gave a presentation yesterday to a room of STW colleagues. I got to a slide I&rsquo;d presented a thousand times, and yet its message struck me hard- as if I was hearing it for the first time. It was a message of hope, and of resilience. Here it is.<br>Our lives and roles can&rsquo;t always be a bowl of cherries- sometimes the pressure builds, tensions rise, relationships get tested, issues complicate. Constant pressure depletes energy &ndash; it pulls you down, clouds judgment. You can feel trapped in the relentlessness of it all. The fun goes. It becomes a grind. We can become, quite simply, unhappy - right there deep inside. Know what I mean?...<br>', 'How to be more effective and efficient every day ', '<ul> <li>Try to become a &lsquo;learned optimist.&rsquo; </li><li>Train yourself to react positively to the things that happen to you in your job and life. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 14, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(101, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/09/how-to-find-inspiration-when-you-need-it/', '2014-09-09 00:00:00', 'How To Find Inspiration When You Need It', '', '<strong> How To Find Inspiration When You Need It</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/09/how-to-find-inspiration-when-you-need-it/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/09/09/how-to-find-inspiration-when-you-need-it/</a><br/> I have been looking for clues as to what genuinely inspires me. And I found it when a colleague did not like a suggestion I made. There it was. The answer. Right in front of me. Now- does this hold true for you? Is this a key to your inspiration?<br/> <em>&ldquo;You must get closer to the client work,&rdquo;</em> I encouraged my colleague, who spends most of his time &lsquo;managing&rsquo; business issues. He looked uneasy. Silent. <em>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s up? &ldquo;Well,&ldquo;</em> he replied hesitantly. <em>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just that the client work thing it&rsquo;s kind of not what I do these days I am just, well, not sure I am able to do it anymore.&rdquo;<br/></em>And there it was. The secret to inspiration. You see, it was clear what my colleague needed to do...<br>', 'The secret to inspiration', '<ul> <li>To truly thrive, learn what makes you uncomfortable, and then attack it - head on.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 18, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(102, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/08/13/the-most-important-question-to-ask-if-you-want-to-thrive/', '2014-08-13 00:00:00', 'The Most Important Question To Ask If You Want To Thrive', '', '<strong> The Most Important Question To Ask If You Want To Thrive</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/08/13/the-most-important-question-to-ask-if-you-want-to-thrive/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/08/13/the-most-important-question-to-ask-if-you-want-to-thrive/</a><br/> Here&rsquo;s a very personal question. It&rsquo;s likely the first time you&rsquo;ll really think about this issue. The answer might surprise you, and can &ndash; literally- energise your future. Here is that critical question- for you, and for me.<br>My last Possums post suggested inspiration comes from &lsquo;getting started.&rsquo; If we get cracking on a project, even if we don&rsquo;t feel like it, then very quickly the ideas and momentum- and inspiration- comes too. My view was that environments can inspire (eg: for me, say, Rome, or the artefacts and furniture in my office, etc), &nbsp;but it&rsquo;s taking action that really counts.<br>Then a wise colleague generously shared a powerful insight that has sat front and centre in my mind...<br>', 'The questions to answer if you want to thrive', '<ul> <li>Who are the people in your life who give you heart? Who depletes you? </li><li>Are you an Energiser or a Depleter? </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 17, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(103, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/23/how-to-get-lashings-of-inspiration-whenever-you-want-it/', '2014-07-23 00:00:00', 'How To Get Lashings Of Inspiration- Whenever You Want It', '', '<strong> How To Get Lashings Of Inspiration- Whenever You Want It</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/23/how-to-get-lashings-of-inspiration-whenever-you-want-it/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/23/how-to-get-lashings-of-inspiration-whenever-you-want-it/</a><br>Something powerful happened to me strolling through the streets of Rome in June. Crumbling grandeur, faded pastels, blue skies, Vespas aplenty. I sucked it all in and then, kapow, it happened. Here it is. It&rsquo;s the secret to getting inspired.<br>I felt energised. My creative juices flowed. My heart beat a little faster. I kind of felt anything was possible. That I was invincible and that my journey had only just begun. It was a rare and special feeling. And I wanted more. And that&rsquo;s the point. The environment lifted my spirits, but all I did was keep walking those streets, sucking in more of that feeling.<br>It&rsquo;s not hugely helpful. You see- I don&rsquo;t live in Rome. My life is elsewhere...<br>', 'The secret to getting inspired', '<ul> <li>Inspiration is for amateurs - the rest of us just show up and get to work. </li><li>Sit down and get started. </li><li>Hard work supersedes inspiration.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 19, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(104, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/09/7000-reasons-to-read-this-post-it-will-change-everything/', '2014-07-09 00:00:00', '7,000 Reasons To Read This Post! It Will Change Everything', '', '<strong> 7,000 Reasons To Read This Post! It Will Change Everything</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/09/7000-reasons-to-read-this-post-it-will-change-everything/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/07/09/7000-reasons-to-read-this-post-it-will-change-everything/</a><br>I tried a &lsquo;Facebookesque&rsquo; (just kidding) secret experiment with you last week and got the result expected. There were 7,000 opportunities for you to prove me wrong. But no-one took it. This is what happened, and this is what I learnt. It changes everything.<br>Three years of weekly Possums posts (except for Christmas breaks). Around 150 weekly stories. Never a missed week. Always dispatched by Martine around 11 am Sydney time on Wednesdays (today an exception due to my being offline for 12 hours). I decided last week not to write a Possums post. Instead, I&rsquo;d await the deluge from 7,000 aggrieved subscribers and followers asking me why I had not posted. Actually- I expected the result I got. Which was this. Zero. Donut. Not a fricken brass razoo. Silence.<br>Now- here&rsquo;s the point. I have been reflecting on what I do and how I do it for a couple of weeks while on holiday. how can I best add more value?...<br>', 'How to add more value to your work', '<ul> <li>Do less and lead more. </li><li>The key is not to prioritize what&rsquo;s on your schedule, but to schedule your priorities. </li><li>Focus on the big problems - where the big impact is. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 18, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(105, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 32, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/24/a-simple-lesson-from-calvin-klein-to-help-you-achieve-great-things/', '2014-06-24 00:00:00', 'A Simple Lesson From Calvin Klein To Help You Achieve Great Things', '', '<strong> A Simple Lesson From Calvin Klein To Help You Achieve Great Things</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/24/a-simple-lesson-from-calvin-klein-to-help-you-achieve-great-things/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/24/a-simple-lesson-from-calvin-klein-to-help-you-achieve-great-things/</a><br/> The image of a bronzed Adonis-like man, clad only in white briefs, got me very excited last week. My heart pumped faster. I was inspired. Energised. And I bet you feel the same way when you read why this happened to me. Here is that story.<br>The darkened seminar room at the Cannes Creativity Conference was a sanctuary, away from the glare of a brutal six months of relentless pressure, tough issues and a unforgiving workload. I was feeling depleted, and two days of presentations from global thought leaders on their insights on &lsquo;what&rsquo;s now and what&rsquo;s next&rsquo; had failed to lift my spirits. Until the global Chief Creative Officer of Calvin Klein took the stage at an &lsquo;off Broadway&rsquo; session, to explain how the company had built a global brand. What a story....<br>', 'Branding Lesson from Calvin Klein', '<ul> <li>Dance with controversy. </li><li>If you want to connect with an audience, say or do something that provokes- something that creates tension and conflict, and thus genuine engagement. </li><li>Face reality and speaking the truth.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 19, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(106, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/17/one-critical-decision-that-will-turbo-charge-your-career-and-its-fun/', '2014-06-17 00:00:00', 'One Critical Decision That Will Turbo-Charge Your Career  &ndash;  And ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Fun!', '', '<strong> One Critical Decision That Will Turbo-Charge Your Career - And It&rsquo;s Fun!</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/17/one-critical-decision-that-will-turbo-charge-your-career-and-its-fun/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/17/one-critical-decision-that-will-turbo-charge-your-career-and-its-fun/</a><br/> If you want to have more fun every day, be a better employee, client service person, deliver more value, then stop spending big time trying to improve weaknesses. No kidding. Instead- do this one thing and accelerate forwards. Here it is.<br>I love feedback- so long as it is positive! And I get a lot of it- much of which I don&rsquo;t like.<br>Consistently through my career I have been told of the areas I need to work on- my weaknesses. Oh yes- there are plenty of them. I have tried. Promise. Really- I have. Worked hard at them- at addressing these &lsquo;weaknesses&rsquo;. Made progress. One inch at a time. I still get the same feedback on the &lsquo;development areas&rsquo;, but not as robustly as before...<br>', 'How to  accelerate your career ', '<ul> <li>Put passion, big energy, enthusiasm, extra hard yards in making your strengths unbelievably great.</li><li>Be less focused on working on &lsquo;weaknesses&rsquo;, and put much more energy on building on your strengths.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 15, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(107, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/10/the-key-to-achieving-goals-simple-and-powerful-yet-damned-hard-to-do/', '2014-06-10 00:00:00', 'The Key To Achieving Goals- Simple and Powerful, Yet Damned Hard To Do', '', '<strong> The Key To Achieving Goals- Simple and Powerful, Yet Damned Hard To Do</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/10/the-key-to-achieving-goals-simple-and-powerful-yet-damned-hard-to-do/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/10/the-key-to-achieving-goals-simple-and-powerful-yet-damned-hard-to-do/</a><br/> There is a simple, unglamorous, obvious key ingredient to achieving goals, dreams, aspirations. It is right here in front of us, but so damned hard to do. Are you able to do it? If you can, victory is yours. Here it is.<br/> The World Cup is upon us. It was while watching a documentary last night on the fortunes of six superb Manchester United players from the 1990s that I was reminded of this powerful insight, shared with me on Friday by CFO Lukas.<br/> Lukas inadvertently gave me the message for today&rsquo;s Possums when he told me this: <em>&ldquo;Well, it&rsquo;s time to quote from that movie...</em><br>', 'Facing your challenges to achieve your goals', '<ul> <li>You have never failed if, every time you get knocked down, you stand up again. </li><li>Setbacks are table stakes. </li><li>It&rsquo;s how you tackle setbacks that counts. Press on.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 28, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(108, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/04/the-key-to-falling-in-love-with-your-job-again/', '2014-06-04 00:00:00', 'The Key To Falling In Love With Your Job Again', '', '<strong>The Key To Falling In Love With Your Job Again</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/04/the-key-to-falling-in-love-with-your-job-again/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/06/04/the-key-to-falling-in-love-with-your-job-again/</a><br>I have discovered the secret to making sure your job is filled with great moments, experiences and buzz. It&rsquo;s the key to preventing staleness, stagnation and depletion. Seriously - they should make a movie about it. Here it is.<br>I got the clue watching the movie <em>&ldquo;The Grand Budapest Hotel&rdquo;</em> in a Singapore hotel room last week. The aged hotel owner, who occasionally returns to the hotel where he started out as a Bell Boy, always stays in the smallest room, with no bathroom. Later, in the flashbacks, we see it&rsquo;s the room he lived in as a young lad, when he was learning the trade, and having a blast. That reminded me of another great movie, <em>&ldquo;Citizen Kane&rdquo;</em>, where the defeated, miserable, sad media tycoon, on his deathbed, murmurs <em>&ldquo;Rosebud...Rosebud...&rdquo;</em>...<br>', 'Preventing staleness, stagnation and depletion in your job', '<ul> <li>If you want to be in a service industry, make sure you LOVE delivering outstanding client service, get deeply invested in your clients, you care about their brand, their business, their success, their well-being. </li><li>Chase the opportunities to spend time doing what you really, really love. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 17, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(109, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/28/top-10-tips-to-building-powerful-influence-in-business-and-in-life/', '2014-05-28 00:00:00', 'Top 10 Tips To Building Powerful Influence- In Business and In Life', '', '<strong> Top 10 Tips To Building Powerful Influence- In Business and In Life</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/28/top-10-tips-to-building-powerful-influence-in-business-and-in-life/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/28/top-10-tips-to-building-powerful-influence-in-business-and-in-life/</a><br>What is the most valuable thing the most influential people in your life have given you? What is it that has made all the difference? Here&rsquo;s the answer. It is the secret to building genuine and deep influence. Do you do it?<br>Critical to business success is building our <strong>&lsquo;footprint of influence,&rsquo;</strong> that hard-to-describe ability to be perceived as someone who is able to help and assist- someone with substance and genuine credential- someone people reach out to for counsel- someone who is wanted and needed.<br>Before I share the <em>Top 10 Tips To Building Powerful Influence</em>, here&rsquo;s the one thing the most influential people I know always do.<br>', 'The habits of highly influential people', '<ul> <li>Be generous in giving people your time, and energy. </li><li>Don&rsquo;t criticise, condemn or complain. </li><li>Give honest and sincere appreciation. </li><li>Arouse in the other person an eager want. </li><li>Become genuinely interested in other people. </li><li>Remember that a person&rsquo;s name is to that person the sweetest and most important sound in any language. </li><li>Be a good listener - Encourage others to talk about themselves. </li><li>Smile. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 16, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(110, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/07/listen-to-this-the-most-powerful-tip-i-know-for-business-success/', '2014-05-07 00:00:00', 'Listen To This- The Most Powerful Tip I Know For Business Success', '', '<strong> Listen To This- The Most Powerful Tip I Know For Business Success</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/07/listen-to-this-the-most-powerful-tip-i-know-for-business-success/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/05/07/listen-to-this-the-most-powerful-tip-i-know-for-business-success/</a><br>When colleague Dave says these four powerful words of advice, I know they are pure gold. Yet I struggle to follow them. If you want to succeed in whatever you do, then don&rsquo;t be like me. Listen to Dave, and embrace these four magical words. Here they are.<br>First, a story. Tom Peters says this: <em>&ldquo;I hate MBA programs but if I was to design my own MBA program it would have two streams...Strategic Listening One and Strategic Listening Two.&rdquo;</em> Peters knows being a great listener is the key to being effective, adding value, making a contribution.<br>Now- before you tune out, do you want to know Dave&rsquo;s four &lsquo;golden&rsquo; words of advice on how to become an outstanding listener?...<br>', 'How to be a great listener', '<ul> <li>Shut up. </li><li>Keep as present as you can. </li><li>Listen to what is being MEANT. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 16, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(111, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/30/a-price-of-leadership-now-is-the-time-for-you-to-pay-it/', '2014-04-30 00:00:00', 'A Price Of Leadership &ndash; Now Is The Time For You To Pay It', '', '<strong> A Price Of Leadership &ndash; Now Is The Time For You To Pay It</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/30/a-price-of-leadership-now-is-the-time-for-you-to-pay-it/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/30/a-price-of-leadership-now-is-the-time-for-you-to-pay-it/</a><br>Do you lead a team, client account, practice area, office, business? If you do- then read this now. But beware. You probably won&rsquo;t like its vitally important message for these times of change. Read on- if you dare!<br>It&rsquo;s ANZAC Day &ndash; the annual remembrance of those fallen in Australia&rsquo;s conflicts. In watching the documentaries of war stories and legends, I revisit my dark secret. You see- I am a coward at heart. Big time. I look at what those men and women did, risked, attempted, and then think about how I would act in similar circumstances. In truth, I can&rsquo;t imagine anything except terror, self-preservation and ducking for cover.<br>Fact is, in the face of great threat and unimaginable horror, ordinary people do find the courage to step up- to do amazing acts of bravery, to risk all to help and protect others- to show leadership under fire. And many paid the ultimate price for that. Lest we forget...<br>', 'Leadership lessons we can learn from heroes', '<ul> <li>The cost of leadership is self-interest. </li><li>Run towards the danger facing your area of responsibility. </li><li>Have the courage to tell those who need to know the hard truths facing the business and team. </li><li>Be prepared that your ideas might not be right- but at least have them- fire up the debate- NOW. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 20, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(112, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/15/the-secret-to-how-to-motivate-others-and-yourself/', '2014-04-15 00:00:00', 'The Secret To How To Motivate Others- And Yourself', '', '<strong> The Secret To How To Motivate Others- And Yourself</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/15/the-secret-to-how-to-motivate-others-and-yourself/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/15/the-secret-to-how-to-motivate-others-and-yourself/</a><br>I flew to New Zealand recently. A colleague flew likewise an hour after me. <em>&ldquo;Hey- I watched &ldquo;Blue Velvet&rdquo; on the flight- what a movie!&rdquo;</em> he told me. And then there&rsquo;s me. You see, embarrassingly, this is what I did for those three hours. But please- don&rsquo;t tell anyone. Shhhhh.<br>I spent the flight to NZ searching for my blibula spot.<br>Are you brave enough to truthfully identify and share what your &lsquo;blibula&rsquo; spot is? Huh? What&rsquo;s that? Calm down. Relax. This is what it is. <em>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a spot on a dog&rsquo;s stomach which when rubbed, causes his leg to rotate wildly.&rdquo;</em>...<br>', 'The four keys that drives most employees', '<ul> <li>Our most important hot button is quite simply, self-interest. </li><li>The key in both life and business is being able to find out what someone&rsquo;s hot button is. </li><li>People only change their ways when what they truly believe matters is threatened.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 21, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(113, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 159, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/08/how-to-keep-clients-coming-back-for-more-and-more/', '2014-04-08 00:00:00', 'How To Keep Clients Coming Back For More- And More', '', '<strong> How To Keep Clients Coming Back For More- And More</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/08/how-to-keep-clients-coming-back-for-more-and-more/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/08/how-to-keep-clients-coming-back-for-more-and-more/</a><br>My favorite hotel stuffed up a critical &lsquo;moment of truth&rsquo; last week. So basic. So damaging. And a powerful lesson for us all. If you have clients, then read this post. Follow this one tip, and you&rsquo;ll keep clients longer- much longer. Here&rsquo;s how.<br>I&rsquo;ve stayed at the hotel once a month for 14 years. Loyalty personified. Last Tuesday, having booked my normal style of room on an important visit accompanied by family, I was given the worst room in the hotel- wrong bed configuration, and a heavy smoker clearly having recently frequented it. Wrong. All wrong. I asked to change rooms. Hotel fully booked. I asked again. Minimal response. <em>&ldquo;But it was not what I booked,&rdquo;</em> I pleaded. &nbsp;Bad luck- it&rsquo;s all we have. I rushed off to a meeting. Tried to resolve by phone. The outcome- it does not matter. Here&rsquo;s the point....<br>', 'How to handle customer complains', '<ul> <li>Focus all your attention on ensuring Zero Moments of Dissatisfaction. Do what is needed to fix it. </li><li>Work every day to minimizing Moments of Dissatisfaction.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 17, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0);
INSERT INTO `advices` (`id`, `co_author_first`, `co_author_last`, `challenge_id`, `decision_type_id`, `category_id`, `source_url`, `advice_decision_date`, `advice_title`, `advice_image`, `executive_summary`, `challenge_addressing`, `key_advice_points`, `publication_name`, `context_role_user_id`, `advice_views`, `advice_posted_date`, `advice_update_date`, `status_id`) VALUES
(114, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/01/four-habits-to-keep-you-positive-and-strong-every-day/', '2014-04-01 00:00:00', 'Four Habits To Keep You Positive And Strong, Every Day', '', '<strong> Four Habits To Keep You Positive And Strong, Every Day</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/01/four-habits-to-keep-you-positive-and-strong-every-day/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/04/01/four-habits-to-keep-you-positive-and-strong-every-day/</a><br>I get lots of feedback. From all walks of my life. Most of it &lsquo;constructive&rsquo; - where I must improve, miss the point, could do better, need to stop or start doing something. Most of it fair. Still- it can wear you down. I cope with it, positively, through these four powerful habits. Do you do this too?<br>They say &lsquo;feedback is the food of champions.&rsquo; Ok- I get that and agree. I know I have to embrace feedback, to learn and grow from it. I am getting better at it. &nbsp;Often, though, &nbsp;people forget to give you positive reinforcement. They think you don&rsquo;t need it.&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;Hey- you&rsquo;re a strong person- you can manage. Man up!&rdquo;</em>&nbsp;I don&rsquo;t know about you- perhaps you don&rsquo;t need it- the positives. But I sure as hell do.<br>So this is a story about me. But I hope it helps you, if you are like me....<br>', 'The powerful habits you needed to practice', '<ul> <li>Be kind to yourself. </li><li>Be optimistic. </li><li>Give yourself opportunities for positive feedback. </li><li>Be grateful.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 18, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(115, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/25/how-to-triumph-during-times-of-rapid-change/', '2014-03-25 00:00:00', 'How To Triumph During Times Of Rapid Change', '', '<strong> How To Triumph During Times Of Rapid Change</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/25/how-to-triumph-during-times-of-rapid-change/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/25/how-to-triumph-during-times-of-rapid-change/</a><br>I am most times the oldest guy in the room. And I am only 53. Where did everyone else go? What happened to all those colleagues who somehow are now somewhere else- off the radar? How did I survive to still be in the room, contributing, learning? Here&rsquo;s how. Simple. Powerful.<br/> This &lsquo;change&rsquo; thing is pretty damned confusing, and frightening. When the rate of change inside a company is slower than the rate of change outside that company- then the end is in sight. So too with our careers- if we are not evolving our &lsquo;value proposition&rsquo;, then the clock is ticking before we will no longer be &lsquo;on the team.&rsquo; Harsh- but true.<br/> But stay calm...<br>', 'Help shape the way you respond to the challenges of change', '<ul> <li>Become indispensable. </li><li>For business, be a trusted advisor (credibility, reliability, intimacy). </li><li>Do I deliver powerful outcomes? Am I expert in something? Do I think enough about, and have a point of view about, the future? Do my colleagues see me as supportive and trustworthy?</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 25, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(116, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/11/the-first-rule-of-crisis-management-use-it-every-day-to-succeed/', '2014-03-11 00:00:00', 'The First Rule Of Crisis Management- Use It Every Day To Succeed!', '', '<strong> The First Rule Of Crisis Management- Use It Every Day To Succeed!</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/11/the-first-rule-of-crisis-management-use-it-every-day-to-succeed/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/03/11/the-first-rule-of-crisis-management-use-it-every-day-to-succeed/</a><br>18 months ago a tumor was found on my vocal chords. I walked from the specialist&rsquo;s surgery straight to my office and for the next four hours devoted myself to the first rule of crisis management. It&rsquo;s a rule that helped me then, and helps me every day- in business and in life. Do you do it?<br>Imagine you were advising the Mayor of Toronto. An allegation of substance abuse is made. All hell breaks loose. What do you do next?<br>Remember what actually happened next?... <br>', 'Planning for the worst case scenarios', '<ul> <li>Sit quietly with the potential worst case scenarios. </li><li>Quietly plan exactly what you would do &amp; write down all the options. </li><li>Develop an action plan. Review the plan. Go forth and tackle the situation head on.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 28, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(117, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/19/what-four-brave-men-and-women-told-me-this-week-could-you-do-it/', '2014-02-19 00:00:00', 'What Four Brave Men And Women Told Me This Week- Could You Do It?', '', '<strong> What Four Brave Men And Women Told Me This Week- Could You Do It?</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/19/what-four-brave-men-and-women-told-me-this-week-could-you-do-it/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/19/what-four-brave-men-and-women-told-me-this-week-could-you-do-it/</a><br>Three men. One woman. Separately. Talking to me over coffee tables. Each did something inspiring. Surprising. Their actions oozed courage. And epitomize a habit critical to coping in tough times, at work and in life. Are you up for it?<br>Four conversations. Four very different relationships. In each, something rare happened. You see, each told me of something causing them sadness, pain, anxiety, stress, fear. I was privileged. They exposed vulnerability. And, I know, felt better and stronger for having taken that step, and for talking about it. And here&rsquo;s the point- it&rsquo;s about something I am getting better at doing, and encourage anyone who will listen to do so as well. Do you do this?...<br>', 'Lessons on how to deal with anxiety', '<ul> <li>Recognize and respect your anxiety and sadness when it bubbles within you. Don&rsquo;t bottle it up. </li><li>Have the courage to talk about it with someone you trust. </li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 27, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(118, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/12/why-taking-the-exit-door-is-the-key-to-surviving-in-fast-changing-times/', '2014-02-12 00:00:00', 'Why Taking The Exit Door Is The Key To Surviving In Fast Changing Times', '', '<strong> Why Taking The Exit Door Is The Key To Surviving In Fast Changing Times</strong><br/><a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/12/why-taking-the-exit-door-is-the-key-to-surviving-in-fast-changing-times/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/12/why-taking-the-exit-door-is-the-key-to-surviving-in-fast-changing-times/</a><br>It was 3 a.m. in my hotel room in New York. The fire alarm shattered the calm. What happened next stays with me vividly, every day. It sums up why so many fail to survive life threatening crises, or survive the change underway in business. Here&rsquo;s why.<br>I thought the alarm would stop. It didn&rsquo;t. All on our floor headed out into the corridor, dazed and scared. Someone screamed. I smelt smoke. The fire escape beckoned. But I stopped. I did not want to go through that door. And that hesitation sums up why so many fail to adapt to the tsunami of change underway in business. It&rsquo;s summed up in an expression I heard last week. Simple. Powerful. Says it all. Here it is. Read it, embrace it, and survive.<br>', 'The key to surviving fast', '<ul> <li>Progress always involves risks. </li><li>You can&rsquo;t steal second base and keep your foot on first. </li><li>Change can also be inspiring. Feel the fear. Embrace it.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 29, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(119, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/05/something-incredibly-powerful-to-help-you-triumph-in-tough-times/', '2014-02-05 00:00:00', 'Something Incredibly Powerful To Help You Triumph In Tough Times', '', '<strong> Something Incredibly Powerful To Help You Triumph In Tough Times</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/05/something-incredibly-powerful-to-help-you-triumph-in-tough-times/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/02/05/something-incredibly-powerful-to-help-you-triumph-in-tough-times/</a><br>Wow! The year has started with a breathtaking avalanche of change, challenge, opportunity. It&rsquo;s intense. To cope with this tsunami of uncharted waters, we need one thing constantly by our side. Without it, we simply won&rsquo;t make it. Here it is.<br/> Former Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating is passionate about <strong>the power of confidence.</strong><br/> <em>&ldquo;Confidence,&rdquo;</em> he says. <em>&lsquo;is not something you can get by swallowing every now and then a can of &lsquo;confidence&rsquo; spinach. It has to be continually with you.&rdquo;</em>...<br>', 'Tips to help you triumph in tough times', '<ul> <li>Confidence is preparation. </li><li>Preparation delivers confidence. </li><li>Take a step back if you feel you are losing the edge.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 33, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(120, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/01/28/heres-the-best-advice-you-will-get-all-year/', '2014-01-28 00:00:00', 'HereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s The Best Advice You Will Get All Year', '', '<strong> Here&rsquo;s The Best Advice You Will Get All Year</strong><br/> <a href="http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/01/28/heres-the-best-advice-you-will-get-all-year/" target="_blank">http://chrisjohnsavage.com/2014/01/28/heres-the-best-advice-you-will-get-all-year/</a><br>Stretching out&nbsp; before us is the new year, winking optimism, opportunity, freshness and renewal. And to help you make this a great year, I am going to share some brilliant advice I have just received. It is a gem- and if you deliver on it, will make 2014 an outstanding year. Promise. Here it is.<br>I love the &lsquo;fresh start&rsquo; that January brings. It lifts my spirits, and makes me feel &lsquo;anything is possible.&rsquo; I plan accordingly! Sadly, history tells me that by about March, I will have sunk back into the depths of deadlines, &lsquo;to do&rsquo; lists, pressure, and a string of broken promises with myself. I lose sight of what drives, inspires and gives me purpose. But not this year. No, no, no! You see- I read a piece of advice while on my break that I know will make this year a triumph of mindfulness and happiness. It can for you too. If you&rsquo;re up for it. Here&rsquo;s that gem.<br>', 'Best advice from Chris Savage this year', '<ul> <li>Take more time, cover less ground. </li><li>Be clear what gives you pleasure, and do more of it. </li><li>Find time for a weekly one hour &lsquo;Fresh Air Session&rsquo; with myself.</li></ul>', 'Chris Savage', 190, 85, '2014-11-26 18:08:51', '2014-11-26 18:08:51', 0),
(122, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://500hats.com/niche-to-win', '2012-07-15 00:00:00', 'Niche 2 Win, Baby.', '', '<strong>Dave McClure - Niche 2 Win, Baby. </strong><br><a href="http://500hats.com/niche-to-win" target="_blank">http://500hats.com/niche-to-win</a> <br>The secret for start-ups to succeed is to find your <strong>Niche</strong> &ndash; that is, the initial customer segmentation / product differentiation combo that enables you to beat your more established, mature competition with a much crappier product.<br><strong>This strategy is called &ldquo;Niche to Win&rdquo;.</strong><br>Most VCs (especially those with limited operational marketing experience, or in a few cases, those with too much good fortune with big wins) have no understanding of this. They commonly and foolishly advise founders: a) &ldquo;You&rsquo;re thinking way too small&rdquo;, or b) &ldquo;Your market isn&rsquo;t big enough for us&rdquo;, or c) &ldquo;We only fund Ambitious Entrepreneurs who want to Change The World&rdquo;.<br>While this perspective isn&rsquo;t completely irrational coming from large-fund VCs (&gt;$250M+) who need big exits &amp; returns to satisfy their LP investors, it&rsquo;s incredibly unhelpful in the short-term for entrepreneurs just getting started, who may be a year or three from understanding their mature market opportunity.<br>In fact it&rsquo;s a bit counter-intuitive, but the crappier you are and can still find minimum viable success, the quicker and better you&rsquo;ll be at identifying initial customer-problem framework opportunities that will create possibility for your still tiny little startup to grow up and succeed.<br>You can compete with a much less mature product but much more focused customers, more specific problems, more targeted marketing (that probably costs less to acquire customers ready to purchase), and thus a more differentiated offering. In fact, your product could be far inferior, far more expensive, and far more profitable than a big competitor&rsquo;s product that was designed for a much bigger, undifferentiated audience, but with crappy untargeted marketing. Also likely, because they&rsquo;re a big company, they&rsquo;ll move and innovate much slower than you, so you&rsquo;ll always be ahead of them and they&rsquo;ll never ever catch you.<br>Ultimately, if you <em>do</em> want to become a bigger company, you will have to grow your market, change product offerings, and compete in multiple customer demographics against those big incumbents &ndash; but in the first few months of existence, your job is simply to establish a foothold, to get an initial MVP out the door, and SURVIVE.<br>If that&rsquo;s your goal, then focusing on a big, world-changing vision is EXACTLY the wrong thing to do. You need to narrow your field, find a very targeted customer, and work on a simple, crappy, focused solution for your customer.', 'Find your niche for your startup to succeed', 'The crappier you are and can still find minimum viable success, the quicker and better youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll be at identifying initial customer-problem framework opportunities. You can compete with a much less mature product but much more focused customers, more specific problems, more targeted marketing, and thus a more differentiated offering. In the first few months of existence, your job is simply to establish a foothold, to get an initial MVP out the door, and SURVIVE.', 'Dave McClure', 189, 52, '2014-11-26 18:09:21', '2014-11-26 18:09:21', 0),
(123, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://500hats.com/why-menus-suck-food-tech-revolution', '2012-12-28 00:00:00', 'Why Menus Suck + Other Deep Thoughts on the Food Tech Revolution.', '', '<strong>Dave McClure - Why Menus Suck + Other Deep Thoughts on the Food Tech Revolution.</strong></br><a href="http://500hats.com/why-menus-suck-food-tech-revolution" target="_blank">http://500hats.com/why-menus-suck-food-tech-revolution</a></br><strong>Menus Suck.</strong></br>in the next few paragraphs, i will attempt to explain why i believe this is a manifesto for innovation &amp; investing in the coming <strong>Food Tech Revolution</strong>, and why the market opportunity is nothing less than HUGE. <br>first, here are a few frequent <strong>problems</strong> i have when i sit down for a meal:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>too many items to choose from, many of which i don&rsquo;t understand</li><li>no/few pictures (too small, poor quality), don&rsquo;t know what i&rsquo;m ordering</li><li>they don&rsquo;t know what i like; i can&rsquo;t remember what i got b4 (good/bad)</li><li>have any of my friends eaten here? do they like/hate some dishes?</li><li>can&rsquo;t get waiter&rsquo;s attention, 3x times or more (ordering, refills, payment)</li><li>places i visit frequently should give discounts to come back regularly</li><li>places i visit infrequently should give discounts to try them 1x or 2x</li><li>while waiting/eating i might enjoy music, movies, games, other media</li></ul><br>okay, that&rsquo;s plenty of things to fix. let&rsquo;s take a look at these in more detail.<br><strong>Problem #1: Too Many Items, Not Enough Pictures, Simpler &amp; More Obvious Recommendations.</strong><br>The biggest problem with most menus is that there&rsquo;s just too much stuff to choose from, and most of it doesn&rsquo;t have associated pictures, certainly not high-quality pictures. While some smart restaurants do feature a few specials (some even with pictures), most places fail at this very simple (largely offline!) innovation. Fewer items with pictures &amp; more obvious recommendations would streamline production, reduce cost, reduce time for customers to order, for kitchens to prepare, and increase customer satisfaction.<br><strong>Problem #2: Not Online, No Order History, No Reviews, No Friends, No Loyalty Program. Also, No A/B Testing.</strong><br><strong>First</strong>, it would be great if the restaurant knew something about my order history and user profile data, and customized the menu selection to my favorite tastes and interests. This would again streamline choice, reduce time &amp; confusion, and increase customer satisfaction. <br><strong>Second</strong>, if there were any kind of online reviews, it would be great to combine this with the actual menu so i can see whether other people loved or hated specific dishes. <br><strong>Third</strong>, it would be even <em>better</em> if i could see if any of my friends had eaten at the restaurant before, and whether <em>they</em> liked or hated anything in particular. My level of trust would go up even more.<br><strong>Fourth</strong>, by managing customer order history, favorites &amp; specials, and social connectivity, it should be easy to implement a loyalty program and retention marketing program that could increase purchase behavior, customer satisfaction, and frequency. And, by aggregating data across the entire customer base, restaurants should be able to learn how to optimize their inventory, pricing, and marketing campaigns dramatically better than ever before.<br><strong>Problem #3: Have to Wait FOREVER for Waiter to Order, Re-Order, &amp; Pay. Also, Nothing To Do While I&rsquo;m Waiting.</strong><br>Obviously, one of the biggest pains in the ass when you&rsquo;re at a restaurant is trying to get the waiter&rsquo;s attention that you need something, and/or waiting around for them to notice that you 1) need a menu / are ready to order, or 2) have a question about something on the menu, or 3) need some water or another drink, or 4) want to order dessert, or 5) are ready to pay can we get the check? or 6) hey i&rsquo;ve got a question about my bill, or 7) hey i&rsquo;d really like that check now please? <br>In any case, being able to message and connect with the wait staff / kitchen staff, and being able to pay online and whenever you want is likely to improve customer satisfaction (and worker satisfaction!) dramatically, as well likely to reduce turnover time and streamline overall operations. Not to mention, having the ability to check and confirm your order online, as you eat it, and the ability to modify and add/upsell as you go would be absolutely awesome. Again, being able to combine payment with purchase history, social referrals, and customized specials and time-sensitive offers (price optimization for inventory, etc) could be absolutely huge.<br>Furthermore, once you have connectivity / tabletop devices, the opportunity to do other things while you&rsquo;re waiting can be a great benefit.', 'The problem with menus', 'Too Many Items, Not Enough Pictures, Simpler & More Obvious Recommendations. Not Online, No Order History, No Reviews, No Friends, No Loyalty Program. Also, No A/B Testing. Have to Wait FOREVER for Waiter to Order, Re-Order, & Pay. Also, Nothing To Do While IÃ¢â‚¬â„¢m Waiting.', 'Dave McClure', 189, 58, '2014-11-26 18:09:22', '2014-11-26 18:09:22', 0),
(124, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://scrmhub.com/blog/brands-really-segmenting-social-audience/', '2014-07-31 00:00:00', 'Are brands really segmenting their social audience?', '', '<strong>Scrmhub - Are brands really segmenting their social audience?</strong><br><a href="http://scrmhub.com/blog/brands-really-segmenting-social-audience/" target="_blank">http://scrmhub.com/blog/brands-really-segmenting-social-audience/</a> <br>I was chairing a breakfast yesterday morning in Sydney for <a href="https://twitter.com/bandt" target="_blank" title="B&T Magazine">@BandT</a> #MadWeek on the topic of social and mobile marketing. We got onto the topic of audience segmentation and were brands really at the point where they had the data and the means to segment their audience. When I asked the audience if they thought they were advanced enough in their social program to really segment their audience, the response was overwhelmingly NO! When asked if they thought they should be, the answer was overwhelmingly YES!<br>Many brands have spent considerable effort and money trying to build social audiences of scale. So why do they&nbsp;not know more about the makeup of that audience? <br>It seems obviously compelling that as a brand interacts with consumers on a social channel, where that individual often provides a considerable amount of information about themselves (of their own free will), why would the brand not try to gather that information and use it to better understand the consumer. Yet many marketers are still fixated on building&nbsp;scale, and not on building depth of understanding.<br>Does size of our audience help us to sell more product or drive revenue? No, not in and of itself. Only by connecting with customers more deeply and building that relationship, or by converting more prospects to customers, do we grow sales. <br>As we build the depth of understanding, it opens a world of possibilities for driving our social marketing investment&nbsp;harder. We can obviously do some of the following:<br><br><ul type="disc"> <li>You can start by transitioning from &ldquo;en-masse&rdquo; to segmented marketing based on known and desired customer behaviour.</li><li>We can obviously measure&nbsp;which&nbsp;segment of your audience is the most viable to target, so you&nbsp;can start avoiding the scatter gun approach many brands currently employ. Just the simple exercise of using Facebook Custom Audiences is more effective, if you know which audience is the most likely to convert from prospect to customer.</li><li>We can obviously start A/B testing our audience against offers, and track conversion.</li><li>And when we have really started to gain insights, we can start getting quite personal with offers and focusing on re-engaging each member of our audience on a continuous cycle, designed to build brand loyalty and advocacy.</li></ul><br>Segmentation is a major transition point in social marketing, that all brands should be working on. The technology is upon us to make this possible. If you are not yet evolving your data set to achieve this, then you are now outside the most progressive brands who are actively working on strategies and technology to achieve this.', 'Tips to segmenting your social audience', 'Transitioning from "en-masse" to segmented marketing based on known and desired customer behaviour. Measure which segment of your audience is the most viable to target. Start A/B testing our audience against offers, and track conversion. Start getting quite personal with offers and focusing on re-engaging each member of our audience on a continuous cycle.', 'David Fairfull', 191, 30, '2014-11-26 18:18:57', '2014-11-26 18:18:57', 0),
(125, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 40, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/1-online-selling-mistake-even-smart-business-owners-make/', '2014-11-24 00:00:00', 'The #1 Online Selling Mistake Even Smart Business Owners Make', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - The #1 Online Selling Mistake Even Smart Business Owners Make</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/1-online-selling-mistake-even-smart-business-owners-make/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/1-online-selling-mistake-even-smart-business-owners-make/</a> <br>If you already have an offline business (selling either products or services) and are trying to sell online, you might be disappointed with the results you are getting online. The biggest reason is that your customers treat you differently.<br><strong>Here&rsquo;s how a sale works offline and online</strong><br>Think about a typical customer buying from an offline store &ndash; for example, a tourist in a new city who wants to buy some sunglasses. Here are four things that happen in the buying process:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>First, they <strong>choose</strong> &ndash; for example, by walking through a shopping mall or seeing a retail store on the street. </li><li>Typically, there are only <strong>a few options</strong> to choose from, and they choose one of them. </li><li>Generally that store has a <strong>reputation</strong>, because of the brands they sell, because many other customers are also in the store, or because it just <em>looks</em> reputable. </li><li>When they walk into the store, the <strong>sale</strong> starts. Even if a sales assistant does not come up to them immediately, they eventually talk to a salesperson, who guides them through the sale. </li></ul><br>Now contrast that with your online store, which also sells sunglasses. Consider a customer who comes to your Web site for the first time:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>They might <strong>stumble on</strong> you &ndash; say, through a Google or a link on somebody else&rsquo;s Web site. </li><li>When they did a Google search, there were <strong>many options</strong> for them to choose from &ndash; sometimes thousands and even millions. </li><li>Unless you are a well-known brand, you are an <strong>unknown</strong>. They can&rsquo;t see other customers buying at the same time, they can&rsquo;t be sure you will still be there next week if there are any problems, and they know that even scammers can build nice Web sites. </li><li>They don&rsquo;t immediately start a sales process. There isn&rsquo;t a live person there to chat with them about what they want, and answer their objections. There is still a lot of <strong>marketing</strong>. </li></ul><br><strong>Here&rsquo;s the biggest difference between offline and online sales </strong><br><ul type="disc"> <li>Offline, your customers are fairly comfortable about you when they enter your store. </li><li>Online, they have a lot of doubts. </li></ul><br>This might sound simplistic, but it&rsquo;s an important point. <strong>Your customer&rsquo;s frame of mind is different</strong>.<br>If you&rsquo;re planning to sell anything online, you have to work very, very hard to get the customer in the right frame of mind before you even start showing them your product or service.<br>Start with the four factors I&rsquo;ve mentioned: they are stumbling on you, you&rsquo;re just one of many options, you&rsquo;re an unknown, and you have to do a lot of marketing. If you don&rsquo;t address and manage these effectively, you will fail at online sales.', 'The four factors you need to address when selling online', 'They are stumbling on you, youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re just one of many options, youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re an unknown, and you have to do a lot of marketing.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 16, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(126, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 126, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/can-trust-team-members-use-good-judgement/', '2014-11-20 00:00:00', 'Can You Trust Your Team Members To Use Good Judgement?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - Can You Trust Your Team Members To Use Good Judgement?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/can-trust-team-members-use-good-judgement/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/can-trust-team-members-use-good-judgement/</a> <br>Nordstrom, the US department store, has the best social media policy in the world &ndash; and it created it long before social media existed. <br>The entire employee manual goes like this:<br>We&rsquo;re glad to have you with our Company. Our number one goal is to provide outstanding customer service. Set both your personal and professional goals high. We have great confidence in your ability to achieve them.<br>Rule #1: Use best judgement in all situations.<br>There are no additional rules.<br>Please feel free to ask your department manager, store manager, or division general manager any question at any time. <br>You might say it&rsquo;s impossible to create an employee manual that gives people so much leeway. After all, there are procedures to follow, policies to uphold, legislation to meet, and rules to enforce.<br>That might be true, but these are generally constraints imposed by HR, legal and other administrative roles in your organisation. What about just thinking about the people &ndash; in other words, your own team members? Are you confident enough in their judgement that you could trust them?<br>If not you&rsquo;re not alone. Most leaders and managers &ndash; if they are being honest &ndash; would admit they can&rsquo;t yet trust their team members to that extent.<br>If you have children, you know this intuitively. Young children don&rsquo;t know about the dangers of electricity, so you protect all your wall sockets when they start crawling. <br>Of course, your team members aren&rsquo;t children, but some organisations treat them as if they are &ndash; and are then surprised when they (metaphorically) stick a knife in an electrical socket or fall into the swimming pool.<br>Your people are smart, talented, savvy citizens who already know how to exercise good judgement in other areas of their life. They raise families, operate heavy machinery to get to your office, organise events, and manage dozens of other complex situations every day. Is it possible that they might be able to do the same at work &ndash; if you just gave them the chance?', 'Are you confident enough with your employees judgement that you could trust them?', 'Most leaders and managers Ã¢â‚¬â€œ if they are being honest Ã¢â‚¬â€œ would admit they canÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t yet trust their team members to that extent. Your people are smart, talented, savvy citizens who already know how to exercise good judgement in other areas of their life. ', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 11, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(127, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/manage-information-overload-sending-better-e-mail/', '2014-11-18 00:00:00', 'Manage Your Own Information Overload By Sending Better E-Mail', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - Manage Your Own Information Overload By Sending Better E-Mail</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/manage-information-overload-sending-better-e-mail/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/manage-information-overload-sending-better-e-mail/</a><strong> </strong><br>Most e-mail time management techniques look at ways for you to manage your inbox. But sometimes you contribute to your own inbox problem by the way you <em>send</em> e-mail to others. With a few simple techniques, you can improve the e-mail you send, which helps the person receiving it, but also reduces the need for replies and unnecessary discussion.<br>This is not just about being thoughtful and considerate of other people - It also helps your own productivity, because your e-mails will be clearer and easier to understand, so other people won&rsquo;t have to keep writing back asking for more information.</p><strong>Agree on the protocol</strong>If most of your e-mail is sent between a few people, agree how frequently you (and everybody else) will be checking e-mail, so you have the appropriate expectations and don&rsquo;t fall into the trap of checking e-mail too often &ldquo;just in case something urgent turns up&rdquo;.<br><strong>Put it in context</strong><br>When somebody receives your e-mail, you don&rsquo;t know where they are, when they are reading it and what else is happening in their day. So don&rsquo;t assume they will remember anything about any earlier discussion. Give them enough context to be able to understand this message fully. Include relevant text from any earlier messages, ensure the subject line is appropriate, and re-read it carefully before sending it.<br><strong>Ask for an action</strong><br>Don&rsquo;t make the other person guess what you want and when you want it; <em>ask for it</em>. This is especially important if you&rsquo;re a leader or manager, because team members might view all e-mails from &ldquo;the boss&rdquo; as very important and very urgent.<br><strong>Use different messages for different topics</strong><br>Don&rsquo;t combine multiple topics in the one message. It makes it harder for the other person to read, understand, act on, and file for reference. Even adding a trivial request to a message immediately complicates it for the other person, because they now have to reply to two completely unrelated requests.<br><strong>Send less e-mail</strong><br>Consider whether you really do need to send it. Don&rsquo;t send e-mail to ask questions that you could ask Google or internal documentation; don&rsquo;t send e-mail to more people than necessary; think twice before you hit Reply All; consider whether a long drawn-out e-mail discussion should really be resolved some other way; and of course, don&rsquo;t use e-mail for emotionally sensitive topics.', 'Techniques you can improve in the emails you send', 'Agree on the protocol. Put it in context. Ask for an action. Use different messages for different topics. Send less e-mail.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 13, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(128, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/remove-distractions-workplace/', '2014-11-10 00:00:00', 'Remove Distractions From Your Workplace', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - Remove Distractions From Your Workplace</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/remove-distractions-workplace/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/11/remove-distractions-workplace/</a><strong> </strong><br>What is the biggest barrier to getting things done? <em>You are!</em> Yes, you. Learn how to focus and you&rsquo;ll get much more done.<br>People often complain about constant interruptions and constant distractions in our fast-moving world. And they are right. But these are two totally different things! Interruptions happen because of other people, but distractions happen because of ourself. You can certainly do things to minimise interruptions, but you have far more control over distractions &ndash; so tackle them first.<br><strong3>1. Know what matters</strong>It&rsquo;s easier to say No to distractions when you have a bigger Yes driving your decisions. Know what&rsquo;s really important to you, and make sure you focus on those things.<br>Don&rsquo;t just make goals once a year, and then forget about them for the rest of the year. Instead, spend 15 minutes at the start of every day to list three important things you want to do that day. Whenever you get distracted or tempted by something else, go back to your list and check whether you&rsquo;re still on track.<br><strong>2. Force focus</strong><br>When many of our distractions come from the screen in front of us, taping cardboard to our glasses won&rsquo;t help. But there are high-tech equivalents, such as <a href="http://anti-social.cc/" target="_blank">the app Anti-Social</a>, which blocks social media sites for a block of time. <a href="http://gottcode.org/focuswriter/" target="_blank">FocusWriter</a> help with specific tasks for giving you a distraction-free screen for writing.<br><strong>3. Work in sprints</strong><br>If you just can&rsquo;t imagine spending an hour or two on one task, don&rsquo;t! Split up your time into smaller segments, so you can work really hard in that short segment and then take a break.<br>This is the thinking behind <a href="http://pomodorotechnique.com/" target="_blank">The Pomodoro Technique</a>. You do a short &ldquo;sprint&rdquo; of work for 25 minutes, then take a 5-minute break, then get back to work for 25 minutes, and so on. The idea is that 25 minutes is long enough to get into a task, but not too long that you&rsquo;ll get distracted.<br><strong>4. Start keeping track</strong><br>Finally, it might be enlightening to just keep track of your time every day. That way, you&rsquo;ll know where your time goes, and that might be enough to convince you to take better care of it.<br>You can do this the old-fashioned way with a grid marked in 15-minute segments, where you just record (honestly!) what you&rsquo;re doing during the day. Or use an online tracking tool like <a href="https://www.rescuetime.com/" target="_blank">RescueTime.com</a> to automate this for you.', 'How to minimise distractions', 'Know what matters. Force focus. Work in sprints. Start keeping track.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 9, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(129, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 80, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/five-steps-stunning-slides/', '2014-10-29 00:00:00', 'Five Steps to Stunning Slides', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - Five Steps to Stunning Slides</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/five-steps-stunning-slides/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/five-steps-stunning-slides/</a><strong> </strong><br>Most webinar presenters don&rsquo;t do enough work on their slides to keep their audience engaged. That&rsquo;s not the only cause of poor webinars, of course, but it&rsquo;s one of the biggest.<br>In a webinar, your slides are not visual aids; they <em>are</em> the visuals. So you need to do more with them to engage your audience.<br>Here are five ways to create stunning slides for your next webinar.<br><strong>1. More slides</strong><br>Use more slides than you would in an in-person presentation, so your audience sees the screen changing often. Otherwise it&rsquo;s just too easy for them to ignore the screen and start checking e-mail or doing other work while listening to your webinar in the background.<br><strong>2. Make your slides more visual</strong><br>No more boring bullet lists! Your slides should be visual, not just a bunch of words.<br>This applies to all presentations, but especially to webinars, where again you need to keep your audience&rsquo;s attention on the screen. <br><strong>3. &ldquo;Build&rdquo; complex slides</strong><br>If a slide contains a lot of information, build it up step by step, talking through each step as you do so.<br>Look at the information on your slide and decide whether you can build up the slide piece by piece. It&rsquo;s easier for your audience to follow, and keeps them engaged while you go through your explanation.<br><strong>4. Make them load faster</strong><br>Slides with large pictures take longer to transmit over the Internet, so some of your audience might see them loading in a slow, jerky way. So as much as you want to make your slides visual, you don&rsquo;t want to fill them with big photos either. For slides that need pictures, use smaller pictures.</br><strong>5. Design them faster</strong><br>Finally, you need a system to build your slide decks fast; otherwise it&rsquo;s just too tempting to just slap something together with a bunch of bullet lists.<br>Subscribe to a stock photo library service like <a href="http://istock.com" target="_blank">istock.com</a> so you can find good pictures quickly. Also learn how to use PowerPoint&rsquo;s &ldquo;Smart Art&rdquo; feature, which turns bullet lists into visually appealing diagrams.', '5 Ways to create stunning visuals', 'More slides. Make your slides more visual. Ã¢â‚¬Å“BuildÃ¢â‚¬Â? complex slides. Make them load faster. Design them faster.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 8, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(130, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/prevention-better-cure-right/', '2014-10-27 00:00:00', 'Prevention Is Better Than Cure Ã¢â‚¬â€œ But Only If You Do It Right', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Prevention Is Better Than Cure &ndash; But Only If You Do It Right</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/prevention-better-cure-right/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/prevention-better-cure-right/</a><strong> </strong><br>Our world is moving so fast that we don&rsquo;t give ourselves much room to play safe. For example:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>An unhappy employee can send an offensive tweet that reaches millions in a few hours </li><li>An online security breach can be exploited by hackers before it&rsquo;s even discovered </li><li>Leaders can&rsquo;t hide behind job titles, brand names and personal charisma when everybody can Google them instantly </li></ul><br>That&rsquo;s why the old saying &ldquo;Prevention is better than cure&rdquo; is so relevant today. It&rsquo;s more relevant than ever before, because cures can be so costly. So if you can spend a small amount to prevent a problem, it can have a huge upside to the risk of making a mistake.<br><strong>What can YOU do to prevent problems in your organisation?</strong>You might not be in the business of designing self-driving cars, but you might be able to design a way of preventing common problems.<br><strong>One word of caution, though </strong> <br>Don&rsquo;t try to control everything! Don&rsquo;t fall into the trap of trying to prevent problems by adding extra layers of bureaucracy, control, hierarchy, documentation, systems, or processes. <em>Sometimes</em> this can be useful, but it can also create extra friction for everybody.<br>If you&rsquo;re going to add extra protection, make it simple, low-cost protection (like a bicycle helmet). But then look at the <em>cause</em> of the problem to find better ways to prevent it. You&rsquo;ll get much better leverage &ndash; and at lower cost &ndash; by looking upstream to the cause.', 'What can you do to prevent problems in your organization', 'DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t try to control everything. Make it simple, low-cost protection. Look at the cause of the problem to find better ways to prevent it.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 9, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(131, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/price-webinar-series-corporate-client/', '2014-10-15 00:00:00', 'How Do You Price a Webinar Series for a Corporate Client?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - How Do You Price a Webinar Series for a Corporate Client?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/price-webinar-series-corporate-client/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/price-webinar-series-corporate-client/</a><strong> </strong><br>One of my clients recently asked me about how to price a webinar series for her corporate clients. Her situation is that she already offers this as a public webinar series, and now wants to offer it to her corporate clients. Of course, they could just pay the same price as the public attendees, but she wants to offer them some other options as well.<br><strong>What&rsquo;s the best pricing model?</strong><br>First, of course, it&rsquo;s difficult to provide any specific advice that applies to all situations. So if you&rsquo;re in a similar situation, please consider these as general guidelines, and use them as a starting point for determing your own prices.<br>Here are some of the factors to consider:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Public program:</strong> Because you are already offering this program, that pricing gives you a starting point. You either offer a discount if they buy in bulk, or charge more if they are getting a customised / tailored / enhanced private version. </li><li><strong>Tiers:</strong> Yes, this is typically the way this works, with bigger discounts at the higher tiers. Make the upper tiers very attractive (i.e. big discount), because they will see high perceived value, whereas it costs you very little. </li><li><strong>Access to you:</strong> If they are getting a pre-recorded version of the program, without any access to you, they will value it less. If the webinars are live, of course they get access to you during the webinars. But you can also offer more access &ndash; e.g. e-mail/Skype support, bonus live sessions, bonus Q&amp;A sessions. </li><li><strong>Renewal:</strong> Do they buy it for a one-off fee, or do they need to renew their licence each year? If they do have to renew, make sure you can justify <em>why</em> they need to renew &ndash; e.g. because they get updated material, or additional training, or additional resources.</li> <li><strong>Additional resources:</strong> Do they get additional resources that the general public don&rsquo;t get? If so, you can charge a higher fee for these resources &ndash; e.g. private coaching, private follow-up sessions, the organisation&rsquo;s branding throughout. </li></ul><br>Finally, if this is the first time you&rsquo;re doing this, try to arrange this so that you don&rsquo;t lock yourself into the pricing forever. The more you can position this as a one-off deal for one particular client, the better. That gives you the flexibility to experiment, and then refine it next time.', 'Factors to consider when choosing a pricing model for your webinar', 'Public program. Tiers. Access to you. Renewal. Additional resources.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 10, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(132, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 41, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/find-time-win-social-media-battle/', '2014-10-06 00:00:00', 'Find The Time to Win The Social Media Battle', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Find The Time to Win The Social Media Battle</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/find-time-win-social-media-battle/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/find-time-win-social-media-battle/</a><strong> </strong><br>In the early days of the Web &ndash; and even before the Web &ndash; when only a few people controlled the publishing of information, businesses could focus on a few specific promotion channels. Before the Web, this would be brochures, flyers, newspapers, magazines, TV, radio, and so on.<br>Then the Web came along, and businesses turned to the online equivalent of the brochure or flyer: the Web site. You promote yourself, your products and your services.<br>That&rsquo;s great, and is still important. But it&rsquo;s not enough. Social media gives everybody power, and people find you now through all your online channels.<br>The <strong>truth</strong> is this: <em>If you&rsquo;re not active on social media, you&rsquo;re losing business.</em><br>But the <strong>challenge</strong> is this: <em>How can you find the time to do it all?</em><br><strong>The answer: Contribute regularly, but not always your own material.</strong><br>The top social media influencers in the world blog at least daily, and spend most of their time online. If you have the time to do that &ndash; or to pay somebody else to do that for you.<br>But most of us don&rsquo;t have that sort of time. So, instead of always looking to create new material, look at other ways of demonstrating your expertise online. Broadly, you have four options:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Comment with value</strong>: Look at what other people are sharing, and comment on it, but in a meaningful and useful way. Don&rsquo;t just click a Like or Share button. Instead, publish a book review on Amazon.com, write a meaningful blog comment, contribute with something useful on a Facebook post, and so on. </li><li><strong>Curate with context</strong>: Share other people&rsquo;s material with your network. You can do this by sharing links to blog posts you read, YouTube videos you watch, podcasts you listen to, e-books you download, and so on. Of course, your followers could find that material directly themselves, but you&rsquo;re taking the trouble to read, filter and share only what&rsquo;s relevant to them. In other words, you&rsquo;re putting the context around it so they know it&rsquo;s right for them. </li><li><strong>Collate with perspective</strong>: Look for patterns in the world and bring them together in a relevant and meaningful way for your network. It&rsquo;s your job as an expert to take a &ldquo;big picture&rdquo; view of specific things and point out patterns that others don&rsquo;t see. </li><li><strong>Create unique material</strong>: Finally, of course, you do need to generate and share your own ideas. Publish them on your blog and YouTube, and then distribute them through social media platforms. </li></ul><br>Use all these four methods &ndash; commenting, curating, collating and creating &ndash; to build a powerful social media presence.', 'Four options you can demonstrate your expertise online', 'Comment with value. Curate with context. Collate with perspective. Create unique material.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 7, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0);
