(133, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 39, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/people-really-webinar/', '2014-10-01 00:00:00', 'What Are People Really Doing During Your Webinar?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; What Are People Really Doing During Your Webinar?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/people-really-webinar/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/10/people-really-webinar/</a><br>What are people really doing on your conference call? According to Intercall, the world&rsquo;s largest conference call company, most of them are doing other work, reading e-mail, eating or preparing food, or going to the bathroom. <br>As a webinar presenter, you do have the added advantage of visuals (slides and maybe video), but most webinar visuals are so poor that this isn&rsquo;t enough to really engage.<br><br><strong>How can you engage them better?</strong><br>Here are some simple and practical ways to engage your audience before, during and after your webinar so you get your message across and achieve your outcomes:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Solve their problems:</strong> Understand their biggest questions, concerns, problems and goals, and make sure your material addresses them. Otherwise, nothing else matters. </li><li><strong>Start on time:</strong> Starting late sends a message that you&rsquo;re inconsiderate at best and incompetent at worst. Value their time and attention, and start on time. </li><li><strong>Involve them:</strong> If you have a one-hour webinar, don&rsquo;t spend the first 50 minutes lecturing to them and then stop for questions. Break for questions throughout your webinar, just as you would do in an in-person presentation. </li><li><strong>Build better slides:</strong> Put more effort into building your webinar slide deck. In a webinar, your slides are not just visual aids; they <em>are</em> the visuals. </li></ul><br>Finally, keep in mind that sometimes people <em>will</em> wander away (mentally, even if not physically) in favour of something that seems more urgent or more important. You can&rsquo;t assume you will have them 100% of the time, but the ideas above will help you minimise that time.', 'Practical ways to engage your audience ', 'Solve their problems. Start on time. Involve them. Build better slides.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 7, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(134, '', NULL, NULL, 5, 124, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/use-online-collaboration-tools-build-synergy-distributed-teams/', '2014-09-24 00:00:00', 'Use Online Collaboration Tools to Build Synergy in Distributed Teams', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - Use Online Collaboration Tools to Build Synergy in Distributed Teams</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/use-online-collaboration-tools-build-synergy-distributed-teams/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/use-online-collaboration-tools-build-synergy-distributed-teams/</a><strong> </strong><br>There are many anecdotes about breakthroughs occurring through conversations around a water cooler, chance encounters in a hallway, and healthy banter at the office canteen. These informal moments help spark conversations and could lead to interesting ideas. <br>Of course, these opportunities for synergy don&rsquo;t occur in distributed teams. Leaders can try to create similar opportunities &ndash; for example, by chatting informally at the start of an online meeting or bringing teams together in person regularly. However, these manufactured interactions don&rsquo;t provide the same value and can often be perceived as time-wasters.<br>A better solution is to build more collaboration into the team process, first during recruitment and induction, and then in ongoing activities.<br>Here are some examples of online collaboration tools that can help your distributed teams:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Webinars</strong> are ideal for internal presentations, such as product education, reporting, and sharing messages throughout the organisation. </li><li>Use <strong>the recording feature</strong> to record webinars for future on-demand viewing. This way, you build up a collection of resources for training, induction, and ongoing reference. </li><li>Use <strong>microphones</strong> to allow participants to speak out loud, rather than just typing their questions in a chat room. </li><li>Use <strong>videoconferencing</strong> for team meeetings. Of course, you could just do teleconferencing (audio but no video), but allowing participants to see each other makes a stronger connection. </li><li>Use <strong>collaborative mind mapping tools</strong> for exploring ideas within the team. </li><li>Use a <strong>virtual whiteboard</strong> for facilitating discussion, capturing ideas, and brainstorming. </li></ul><br>There is one other point worth noting about teamwork: Virtual teams don&rsquo;t suffer as much from the negative personality issues within in-person teams &ndash; for example, stereotyping, power battles, petty quarrels, and personality conflicts. This means that when they are allowed to collaborate effectively, they can produce better results with less friction.', 'Online collaboration tools you can use in your teams', 'Webinars, recording feature, microphone, videoconferencing, collaborative mind mapping tools, virtual whiteboard.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 8, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(135, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 157, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/channel-chaos-new-rules-high-performance-productivity/', '2014-09-22 00:00:00', 'Channel The Chaos - The New Rules for High Performance and Productivity', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Channel The Chaos &ndash; The New Rules for High Performance and Productivity</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/channel-chaos-new-rules-high-performance-productivity/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/channel-chaos-new-rules-high-performance-productivity/</a><strong> </strong><br>The new principles for high performance and super productivity are <strong>direction</strong> (rather than goals), <strong>signals</strong> (rather than interruptions), <strong>collaboration</strong> (rather than meetings), and <strong>flow</strong> (rather than time management).<br><strong>Direction: Know What Matters</strong><br>Think compass, not map. Know where you&rsquo;re heading, and be willing to change your path to get there as things change around you.<br>This doesn&rsquo;t mean you can&rsquo;t make any plans at all. It just means you have to be willing to change your plans while still holding firm on your direction.<br>If you set a goal, know <em>why</em> you want to achieve that goal, and then you can be flexible about <em>how</em> you&rsquo;ll get there.<br><strong>Signals: Get Smart</strong><br>Keep in mind that <em>information overload is part of your job</em>. Your customers and clients <em>want</em> you to take on the information overload burden on their behalf, sift through all the conflicting messages, and tell them what&rsquo;s most relevant to them.<br>So don&rsquo;t complain about information overload &ndash; get smart about it instead. Figure out your system to:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Get more high-quality information coming in (and less of the low-quality junk) </li><li>Process that information more efficiently and effectively </li><li>Share it faster and distribute it more widely </li></ul><br><strong>Collaboration: Work Together</strong><br>Working together is more important than ever before, but the Internet has made it both easier and harder.<br>It&rsquo;s easier to find and connect with the best people for a project but it takes a whole new set of skills to work effectively with them. Learn how to:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Cooperate with them to achieve your own goals, </li><li>Collaborate with them to achieve joint goals, and </li><li>Accommodate them to suit your different work styles </li></ul><br><strong>Flow: Manage Your Energy</strong><br>Instead of time management, think <em>energy management</em>. How can you manage your energy to get important work done? Here are some ideas:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>If you&rsquo;re a morning person, wake up early and start working on these projects. And if you&rsquo;re a night owl, of course you do this at the end of the day. </li><li>Use something like <a href="http://pomodorotechnique.com/" target="_blank">The Pomodoro Technique</a> to do your work in &ldquo;sprints&rdquo; throughout the day. </li><li>Manage your e-mail in-box so it doesn&rsquo;t rule your life. </li></ul>', 'The new principles for high performance and super productivity ', 'Direction: Know What Matters. Signals: Get Smart. Collaboration: Work Together. Flow: Manage Your Energy.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 7, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(136, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 41, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/social-media-strategy-business-just-fun/', '2014-09-16 00:00:00', 'A Social Media Strategy for Business, Not Just For Fun', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - A Social Media Strategy for Business, Not Just For Fun</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/social-media-strategy-business-just-fun/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/social-media-strategy-business-just-fun/</a> <br>I recently ran a webinar about social media for business, and described a social media strategy for business owners. One of my key messages was that, if you want to position yourself as a leader, you should <em>use social media mainly (about 80%) for distributing content, not for having conversations (at most 20%).</em><br>After the webinar, one person tweeted this:<br>&ldquo;And you have 80% stress and 20% fun in life? not for me friend :-)&rdquo; <br><strong>Here&rsquo;s the thing: I agree with him!</strong><br>A lot of social media consultants do spend a lot of time on social media. And they do measure their fun in life by their online time and their online friends.<br>And there&rsquo;s nothing wrong with that. If you want to use social media for fun &ndash; for connecting with friends and family &ndash; that&rsquo;s great! Go for it! And if you do spend all your time on social media, then you&rsquo;ll be able to do a lot better than the strategy I recommend to most business owners.<br><strong>But most of us aren&rsquo;t in that boat.</strong><br>You know social media is important, so you want to use it, but you don&rsquo;t want to have to spend all day on it.<br>That&rsquo;s why I like the &ldquo;use social media for building authority&rdquo; approach. It means you create a strong social media presence with a clear strategy. The idea is to position yourself as an authority in your field, get people to subscribe to you by e-mail, and then continue providing value to them until they are ready to do business with you.<br>It&rsquo;s not the only social media strategy around. But it&rsquo;s one you can <em>do</em> with limited time and resources.', 'Social media strategy for business owners', 'Position yourself as an authority in your field, get people to subscribe to you by e-mail, and then continue providing value to them until they are ready to do business with you.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 10, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(137, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 78, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/ready-fluid-workforce/', '2014-09-11 00:00:00', 'Are You Ready for a More Fluid Workforce?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Are You Ready for a More Fluid Workforce?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/ready-fluid-workforce/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/ready-fluid-workforce/</a> <br>For most of the past 200 years, the workplace of the office worker has been well, an office. It still is. It was the only practical option: That&rsquo;s where teams could meet, that&rsquo;s where the files were stored, that&rsquo;s where the typing pool was, that&rsquo;s where people put stuff in your (physical!) inbox.<br><strong>Telecommuting created distributed teams</strong><br>Now we have many more distributed teams, where some people work from home, others work from other offices around the world, and others work from cafes or shared working spaces.<br>Distributed teams and the virtual workplace reduced some of the friction of the physical office, and improved productivity.<br>But, although it fixes the problem of <em>when</em> and <em>where</em> people work, it doesn&rsquo;t address the issue of <em>who</em> does the work.<br>What are the chances that the people you employed &ndash; possibly many years ago &ndash; just happen to be the best people in the world for your key project right now? In the past, it wasn&rsquo;t practical to use anybody else, but now you (literally!) have the whole world at your fingertips.<br><strong>The workforce of the future is fluid</strong><br>Your future work<em>force</em> is not defined by its work<em>place</em>. A team comes together &ndash; from anywhere in the world &ndash; for a task, does the work, and then disperses. Sometimes the entire team disbands, sometimes the core remains. But the key is that you&rsquo;re getting the best people for the job.<br><strong>Get ready for the fluid workforce</strong><br>Even if you aren&rsquo;t fully ready to embrace the idea of a fluid workforce, here are four key questions to position yourself for it in the future:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><em>Team Members:</em> Are your current teams really the <strong>best people</strong> to complete your current projects and meet your goals? Did you really choose the best people, or just make the best you could of the people you have? </li><li><em>Performance:</em> Are you measuring and rewarding people for <strong>results achieved</strong> (rather than time spent)? </li><li><em>Supervision:</em> Can your people really work independently, and simply report back at <strong>agreed touchpoints</strong> (rather than having to follow prescribed systems, processes and rules)? </li><li><em>Interdependence:</em> Do team members <strong>accommodate</strong> each other&rsquo;s needs, even outside scheduled meetings and events? </li></ul>Rate your teams on a scale of 0 to 10 for each of these four questions, and that will give you a good idea of how well you&rsquo;ll be ready to build the fluid workforce of the future.', '4 Key questions to get ready for a fluid workforce', 'Are your current teams really the best people to complete your current projects and meet your goals? Are you measuring and rewarding people for results achieved? Can your people really work independently, and simply report back at agreed touchpoints? Do team members accommodate each otherÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s needs, even outside scheduled meetings and events? ', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 11, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(138, '', NULL, NULL, 8, 95, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/protect-intellectual-property/', '2014-09-09 00:00:00', 'How Do You Protect Your Intellectual Property?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; How Do You Protect Your Intellectual Property?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/protect-intellectual-property/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/protect-intellectual-property/</a><br>A client recently asked me this question:<br>&ldquo;Can you give any advice on any steps we should take to protect my intellectual property at this point. I&rsquo;ve not really taken steps in this regard and don&rsquo;t know if I need to in any way?&rdquo; <br>First, to clarify: She was not asking about legal protection &ndash; copyright, trade marks, patents, etc. Rather, she wanted to know what she could do to prevent clients from copying the material she was providing to them.<br>The trouble is that with digital (i.e. electronic) material, it can be extremely complicated to stop people copying it. There are some sophisticated copy-protection schemes, but they can be difficult to set up, and can cause problems for some legitimate uses.<br><strong>Here are some options </strong><br>In general, there are a number of things you can do to protect your material:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>First, of course, make your contract clear about what they are getting. If you can provide valuable resources at a fair price, there&rsquo;s less temptation for them to abuse it. </li><li>Put clear ownership information on all your materials (including a copyright notice, even though this is not legally required). </li><li>If it&rsquo;s easy to protect something, do so. For example, if they don&rsquo;t need to edit a document, give it to them as PDF rather than Word. </li><li>If there are easy ways for you to monitor them, do so. For example, one of my clients licences his online courses to clients, and they send him the list of names to enrol in the course. This is a bit of extra work on his part, but enables him to easily keep track of the number of users &ndash; and bill the client accordingly. </li><li>Don&rsquo;t worry about the really determined IP thief. It creates too much of a burden for you and your legitimate clients. For example, in that previous example of the client with online courses, there&rsquo;s nothing to stop a client from enrolling one person and then sharing the material with everybody else. But it&rsquo;s too much effort to prevent that sort of abuse. </li><li>That said, if you do find somebody using your materials illegally, raise the issue with them. Sometimes they are doing it unknowingly and would pay if they knew, others are doing it knowingly but would back down if detected, and others will simply ignore you and go on doing it. But you&rsquo;re still no worse off by raising the issue. </li></ul>', 'Tips you can do to protect your material', 'Make your contract clear about what they are getting. Put clear ownership information on all your materials. If itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s easy to protect something, do so. If there are easy ways for you to monitor them, do so. If you do find somebody using your materials illegally, raise the issue with them.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 6, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(139, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 35, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/can-keep-offering-incentives-encourage-sales/', '2014-09-02 00:00:00', 'How Can You Keep Offering Incentives To Encourage Sales?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - How Can You Keep Offering Incentives To Encourage Sales?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/can-keep-offering-incentives-encourage-sales/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/09/can-keep-offering-incentives-encourage-sales/</a><strong> </strong><br>One of my clients was running a week-long seminar, and had a dilemma with her marketing campaign. She wrote to me asking for my advice:<br>&ldquo;In our first campaign, there were $11,500 worth of bonuses as an incentive for people to sign up. This went well, but if I run another campaign before the seminar, I can&rsquo;t use bonuses to incentivise them to buy because then it would be unfair to those who signed up at the first opportunity.&rdquo; <br>So, of course, when the shoe is on the other foot, and <em>you</em> are the business making a special offer, you don&rsquo;t want to annoy your loyal customers in the same way.<br>But there might be legitimate reasons to provide an incentive.<br><strong>So how can you do it the right way?</strong><br>Just because you&rsquo;ve made one special offer doesn&rsquo;t mean you can&rsquo;t do it again.<br>The trick, of course, is that you don&rsquo;t want to do anything that upsets the people who have already registered. They should always feel the most special, because they made the biggest commitment by signing up first. So yes, you don&rsquo;t want to offer anybody else the same bonuses, and you don&rsquo;t want to offer anybody else something extra.<br>Here are some examples of bonuses you could offer if you were in my client&rsquo;s position:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Special dinner with the presenter during the seminar </li><li>A special webinar/teleconference (you can call it, say, a &ldquo;masterclass&rdquo;?) after the seminar </li><li>Facilitate a 3-month online mastermind group (by webinar, teleconference or Google Hangout) after the seminar </li><li>Special &ldquo;Hot Seat&rdquo; opportunities during the seminar. You won&rsquo;t have space for everybody, but if there are, say, 5 hot seats available, they are drawn at random from the people who register early. </li><li>90-day &ldquo;Ask the Expert&rdquo; e-mail access after the seminar </li></ul><br><br>These are all easy to deliver but will still be considered valuable.<br>Of course, your business is different, so these ideas might not work for you. But use the principle of looking for things you could use in your offer &ndash; even if you have already made an earlier offer.', 'Some examples of bonuses you could offer to your clients', 'Special dinner with the presenter during the seminar. Special webinar/teleconference. Facilitate a 3-month online mastermind group. Special Ã¢â‚¬Å“Hot SeatÃ¢â‚¬Â? opportunities during the seminar.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 10, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(140, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/set-best-price-webinar/', '2014-08-27 00:00:00', 'Set the Best Price For Your Webinar', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Set the Best Price for Your Webinar</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/set-best-price-webinar/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/set-best-price-webinar/</a><strong> </strong><br>Most presenters don&rsquo;t know how to price their webinars, and as a result they usually price them too low. <br>Here are two <em>bad</em> ways and three <em>good</em> ways to set your webinar price.<br><strong>Bad Idea #1: Cost plus</strong><br>This is setting your price on a &ldquo;cost plus&rdquo; basis &ndash; in other words, based on the cost to you.<br>Webinars themselves have a very low cost, so it&rsquo;s hard to justify your pricing based on your cost, because almost everything is pure profit to you. However, you might consider this as one factor in setting the price &ndash; such as advertising, paying guest presenters, or paying somebody to be the host while you&rsquo;re the presenter. You should also factor in the cost of your own time.<br><strong>Bad Idea #2: Competitor pricing</strong><br>This works well for well-understood products and services, where customers typically make decisions by comparing prices. Unfortunately, this usually isn&rsquo;t the case for webinars, because they are still novel. Your customers probably can&rsquo;t find another competing webinar to compare with; and even if they did, it&rsquo;s not like comparing breakfast cereals, cars or mobile phone plans.<br><strong>Good Idea #1: Equivalent product</strong><br>Start by considering the price of an equivalent in-person presentation, and set your price accordingly. If you deliver the same value to your participants, there&rsquo;s no reason why you shouldn&rsquo;t charge a similar price. <br>However, when setting your price this way, you do have to be careful of two things:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Value, like beauty, is in the eye of the beholder. For instance, some people like the opportunity to get out of the office, enjoy interacting with others at a workshop.</li><li>You have to work hard to convince attendees your webinar does in fact offer the same, or comparable, value to an in-person presentation. <strong></strong></li></ul><br><strong>Good Idea #2: High demand</strong><br>If there is a high demand for your topic area, obviously you can charge a higher price. However, in my experience, business owners often over-estimate their value, and are disappointed when their market doesn&rsquo;t share their belief! It&rsquo;s easy to fool yourself into thinking your topic really is in high demand. So when assessing demand, be sure you&rsquo;re doing this from your market&rsquo;s viewpoint.<br><strong>Good Idea #3: Urgent need</strong><br>Topics that address current needs are in high demand, and usually command a higher price. We&rsquo;ve talked about high demand already, but I want to address urgency separately because this is one area where you can actively demonstrate urgency in your client&rsquo;s mind.<br>A more respectful approach is to explain why now, more than ever, your topic is important and relevant. Tell them how the world has changed in ways to create threats and risks they might not even have considered.', 'Bad ways and good ways to set your webinar price', 'Bad Idea #1: Cost plus. Bad Idea #2: Competitor pricing. Good Idea #1: Equivalent product. Good Idea #2: High demand. Good Idea #3: Urgent need.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 9, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(141, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 40, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-easy-ways-score-referrals-renewals-repeat-business/', '2014-08-19 00:00:00', '5 Easy Ways to Score More Referrals, Renewals, and Repeat Business', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; 5 Easy Ways to Score More Referrals, Renewals, and Repeat Business</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-easy-ways-score-referrals-renewals-repeat-business/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-easy-ways-score-referrals-renewals-repeat-business/</a><strong> </strong><br>Most people think online marketing is just about getting new leads. But if you use it for referrals, renewals, and repeat business, it can be much easier, more cost-effective and more profitable.<br>So here are five simple ways to get more repeat, referral and renewal business through your Web site and other online marketing tools <br><strong>1. Publish a regular client newsletter.</strong><br>Do your clients only hear from you when you send them a bill? Publish a monthly (at least) e-mail newsletter just for clients, with high-value material that your general subscribers don&rsquo;t get.<br>That material doesn&rsquo;t even have to be your own. You can &ldquo;curate&rdquo; and share other people&rsquo;s material, as long as you do it with permission (or just link to it).<br><strong>2. Make them special offers.</strong><br>Give clients access to products and services that others don&rsquo;t get. Or give them <em>special</em> access &ndash; such as bundling in other products and services at the same time.<br><strong>3. Encourage them to invite a friend.</strong><br>If you run special events for clients, allow them to invite a friend or two. This is better than just asking for a referral, because the client is doing a favour to their friend, not to you.<br><strong>4. Recommend other people in your network.</strong><br>Your clients have come to <em>you</em> to solve a problem, but in solving that problem you&rsquo;re likely to discover other problems as well. Even if you can&rsquo;t solve them yourself, refer them to others who can. Your client will appreciate you taking the time to think beyond your narrow scope of business.<br><strong>5. Be accessible and current.</strong><br>If clients do refer people to your Web site, is it easy for those people to contact you? They are more valuable than somebody who just stumbles over your site, so make sure you make their life easy. For example:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>List full contact information <em>(including a phone number!)</em> on every page. </li><li>Make it easy for <em>somebody who knows what they are looking for</em> to find it. </li><li>Don&rsquo;t force them to jump through hoops to get to the information they need. </li></ul>', 'Online marketing techniques to get more business', 'Publish a regular client newsletter. Make them special offers. Encourage them to invite a friend. Recommend other people in your network. Be accessible and current.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 11, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(142, '', NULL, NULL, 7, 78, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/help-team-become-agile/', '2014-08-14 00:00:00', 'Help Your Team Become More Agile', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera &ndash; Help Your Team Become More Agile</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/help-team-become-agile/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/help-team-become-agile/</a><strong> </strong><br>A large organisation offers a more stable day-to-day work life. There&rsquo;s a buffer between teams and the outside world, so people work in a stable, predictable environment, with less stress and more confidence they can cope with the work. Even when external pressures occur, the organisation can absorb, delay or counter them so they don&rsquo;t affect normal operations.<br>When you work in this sort of environment, it&rsquo;s easier for you to plan, project, budget and allocate resources. It&rsquo;s easier for you to motivate your team members with clear and predictable goals, milestones, bonuses and other performance rewards. You can also promise a more secure, reliable, predictable workplace &ndash; so it&rsquo;s easier to get, engage and keep key people.<br>When a crisis occurs, you might lose staff, projects, and even your job &ndash; through no fault of your own, and without any recourse. It&rsquo;s bad enough when a lone sailor loses his life; it&rsquo;s a tragedy of a whole other magnitude when it happens to a large ship.<br><br> <strong>Take a leaf from a small, agile business </strong><br>Small organisations deal with crises (some imagined, some real) regularly. Because they are more exposed, these workplaces can be more uncertain, frantic and frightening. However, they can also be more dynamic, more exciting and more inspiring.<br>Give your team the best of both worlds, by showing them the excitement of a dynamic work life while still enjoying the relative security of a stable workplace. You can do this in three ways:<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Lift them up:</strong> Expose your team members to higher roles, so they can see over the metaphorical walls (or physical cubicle partitions!) in their regular work. </li><li><strong>Bring the outside in:</strong> Subscribe to industry magazines and journals &ndash; both in print (which you can leave lying around in common areas, or circulate among the team) and electronic form. </li><li><strong>Take the inside out:</strong> Encourage your team members to step outside the workplace and participate in business networking events (and yes, in real life, not just online!) </li></ul><br>By giving them opportunities &ldquo;above their pay grade&rdquo;, you help them avoid the false sense of security they might otherwise feel.', '3 Ways to help your team become agile', 'Lift them up: Expose your team members to higher roles. Bring the outside in: Subscribe to industry magazines and journals. Take the inside out: Encourage your team members to step outside the workplace and participate in business networking events.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 25, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(143, '', NULL, NULL, 3, 41, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-tips-revamp-linkedin-strategy/', '2014-08-12 00:00:00', '5 Tips to Revamp Your LinkedIn Strategy', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - 5 Tips to Revamp Your LinkedIn Strategy</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-tips-revamp-linkedin-strategy/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/5-tips-revamp-linkedin-strategy/</a> <br>LinkedIn has added so many features recently that it&rsquo;s easy to get confused about how it works and what to do with it. But if you focus on the things it does best, you can get a lot of value from it.<br><strong>1. Profile</strong><br>Use LinkedIn to post your &ldquo;CV&rdquo; or &ldquo;resume&rdquo;, so people who do want to know more about you can find something. This is not a traditional CV you would write when seeking a job. Rather, it&rsquo;s a promotional profile piece that positions you as an expert and authority. <br><strong>2. Networking</strong><br>Think about going to a business networking function. The people you hate there are those that are too self-promoting while the people you love are those who take an interest in you and genuinely look for ways to help you.<br>LinkedIn is the same. Don&rsquo;t promote yourself too much. Position yourself as a trusted advisor, not a pushy salesperson.<br><strong>3. Testimonials</strong><br>In the physical world, you might write a testimonial, or bring it up in conversation with your friend. But what if you don&rsquo;t know your friend is looking for that service? And what if the supplier hasn&rsquo;t promoted your testimonial well?<br>LinkedIn solves both these problems by letting you put testimonials (LinkedIn calls them &ldquo;Recommendations&rdquo;) right there on the supplier&rsquo;s profile. It also encourages the supplier to reciprocate by writing a testimonial for you as well.<br><strong>4. Introductions</strong><br>The world works on recommendations, referrals and introductions. If I introduce you to somebody I know, that person already trusts you (to some extent). <br>LinkedIn works the same way in the online world. Use it to reach out to people you would like to reach, not just by contacting them out of the blue, but through somebody who knows you both. <br><strong>5. Peers and colleagues</strong><br>Finally, keep in mind that most of your LinkedIn connections are <em>not</em> your prospects. They are peers and colleagues who are connected to you for mutual gain. <br>On the contrary, LinkedIn can be one of your best sources of businesses. But think of it as getting business <em>through</em> your connections, not <em>from</em> them. In other words, they are more likely to refer you than to buy from you.', 'Focus on these 5 Linkedin tips to get more value', 'Profile. Networking. Testimonials. Introductions. Peers and colleagues.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 16, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(144, '', NULL, NULL, 5, 139, 'http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/best-membership-site-software/', '2014-08-07 00:00:00', 'What is the Best Membership Site Software?', '', '<strong>Gihan Perera - What is the Best Membership Site Software?</strong><br><a href="http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/best-membership-site-software/" target="_blank">http://gihanperera.com/2014/08/best-membership-site-software/</a> <br>If you&rsquo;re planning to build a paid membership site to generate recurring income, you might feel confused or overwhelmed by the many choices available. Ning? Kajabi? WordPress? WishList Member? Before you jump in and make your choice, be clear about the key experience you&rsquo;re providing to members.<br>Broadly, your members are looking for one (or more) of three things:<br><br><ul type="text"> <li><strong>Community:</strong> A sense of belonging, participation and contribution. They want to show their profile, ask and answer questions, take part in group discussions, and perhaps even take on specific roles inside the community. </li><li><strong>Resources:</strong> Unique information, insight and other &ldquo;stuff&rdquo; that helps them solve their problems, achieve their goals and overcome their fears and concerns. In this sort of community, you provide things training videos, webinars, e-books and special reports, audio downloads, online courses, an online support forum, and so on. </li><li><strong>Access:</strong> Special access to you. They want things like priority telephone and e-mail support, consulting time with you, and so on. </li></ul><br>Of course, your members might want a combination of these three things. But be sure you understand the right mix.<br>Also be sure you really do know what they want! I&rsquo;ve seen too many people who think their members want a community, and then spend all their time desperately trying to convince people to speak up, participate, share, and engage in other ways. But all along, the members really just wanted access and resources.<br><strong>How does this affect your choice of platform?</strong><br>Different membership site software provides Community, Resources and Access in different ways. So knowing the right mix of these services will guide you in choosing the correct platform.<br>For example, <strong>Ning</strong> is a great tool for creating a membership site that values community. It&rsquo;s like having your own private version of Facebook. Members can create profiles, connect with each other, write on each other&rsquo;s &ldquo;wall&rdquo;, engage in forums and groups, and so on. So if Community is important to you, Ning could be the ideal choice.<br><strong>It&rsquo;s important to get this right.</strong><br>If you pick the wrong platform for your strategy, you will struggle &ndash; and your membership site will fail. So choose carefully!', 'Factors to consider when choosing a membership site ', 'Community. Resources. Access.', 'Gihan Perera', 192, 22, '2014-11-26 18:24:37', '2014-11-26 18:24:37', 0),
(145, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 31, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/managing-and-engaging-with-your-community.html', '2014-10-20 00:00:00', 'Managing and engaging with your community', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Managing and engaging with your community</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/managing-and-engaging-with-your-community.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/managing-and-engaging-with-your-community.html</a> <br>The importance of community engagement is a foregone conclusion. It is a crucial growth component for businesses of all sizes. In an increasingly experience driven and co-creation led economy, excellent community engagement is a brand&rsquo;s utopia. As customers converse online through social media platforms, companies have realised they cannot be absent from conversations taking place around (and about) them.<br>Everyone from big brands to start-ups and not-for-profit organisations are recruiting community managers and outsourcing to community architects to help shape their online narrative.<br>Although community management is one of the most rapidly growing jobs, the core role expectation isn&rsquo;t new. People have been managing communities for as long as businesses have existed. However, the nuances of managing conversations online in an always-connected world where customers are more empowered than ever is a more recent development. Humanising the brand to make it fit into said customers lives is new.<br>For start-ups and young companies, here are a few simple tips on community management:<br><br><ul type="disc"> <li>Align the community you want to build around your core values.</li><li>Don&rsquo;t confuse community management with online advertising. It is NOT about getting 500 likes leading to quick sales by end of month.</li><li>Start small and don&rsquo;t be in a rush to grow. Meaningful communities hold more value in the longer run.</li><li>Remember every member counts and make each of them feel privileged.</li><li>Create a platform where members can talk to each other.</li><li>Provide value to the member. The community is about them and not you. Value could be in form of relevant content, inspiration, connections, and helping make lives easier for them.</li></ul><br>How we do business is changing on a fundamental level. Our customers are more inclusive than ever in our research, strategy and rollouts. Businesses that engage with their communities early on will stand to gain in future when these changes get cemented into the very fibre of our beings.', 'Tips on community management', 'Align the community around your core values. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t confuse community management with online advertising. Start small and donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t be in a rush to grow. Every member counts and make each of them feel privileged. Create a platform where members can talk to each other. Provide value to the member.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 13, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(146, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 24, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/visionary-thinking-should-be-a-daily-mantra-18082014.html', '2014-08-18 00:00:00', 'Visionary thinking should be a daily mantra', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Visionary thinking should be a daily mantra</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/visionary-thinking-should-be-a-daily-mantra-18082014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/visionary-thinking-should-be-a-daily-mantra-18082014.html</a> <br>Richard Branson said, &ldquo;Starting up a business is always an adventure, and not everything comes together for every entrepreneur in the same way. As you face the challenges of keeping your business going, you may find that your vision for the company needs to be adjusted as you go.&rdquo;<br>Here are a few simple suggestions on how you can stay true to what you set out to achieve, adjust the vision as you grow and prosper.<br><strong>Share with your team</strong> <br>Business owners need to make three fundamental changes in thinking to harness team vision:<br>Don&rsquo;t hold the reins too close to you &ndash; involve the team in the journey and watch the business fly. Let team members tell you the vision of the company in their words and see if it matches yours. <br>Treat team building as a more than an activity to diminish risk if founders leave. Having employees who understand and share your vision will make or break the business. <br>Bring on board people who understand and share your vision. Listen and give them a voice within the business and outside. <br><strong>Minimising quick-fix solutions</strong> <br>Key decisions need to be evaluated against the impact they have on realising the vision. Ignoring this will not only result in quick-fix solutions that don&rsquo;t deliver best results, but also increased costs and decreased efficiencies in the longer run.<br>Focus on the long term and you&rsquo;ll have better results. Short term is a poor predictor for long term. If we think long term, we can accomplish things that we couldn&rsquo;t otherwise accomplish.&rdquo;<br><strong>Don&rsquo;t build a business, build a foundation for success</strong> <br>To design a business that stands the test of time, endures change and prospers, it has to be built on a solid foundation. One that will help realise your vision of an ideal structure. Foundations aren&rsquo;t as glamorous as designing the structure, but will withstand change when it happens and help deliver on core values that shape your vision.<br>As with any good foundation, you want your business to be able to adapt to change through innovation and be ready for what matters 10 years from now. You can&rsquo;t control change, but you can control the strength and relevance of your business. Big ideas require deep foundations to take off.', 'How you can stay true to what you set out to achieve', 'Share with your team. Minimising quick-fix solutions. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t build a business, build a foundation for success.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 9, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(147, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/start-up-entrepreneur/are-you-ready-to-be-an-angel-21072014.html', '2014-07-21 00:00:00', 'Are you ready to be an angel?', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Are you ready to be an angel?</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/start-up-entrepreneur/are-you-ready-to-be-an-angel-21072014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/start-up-entrepreneur/are-you-ready-to-be-an-angel-21072014.html</a> <br>My personal journey into angel investment started from a background in trading equities. I used social media to grow my networks by offering small social and ethical investment grants to other startups &ndash; focusing on issues such as literacy, women-led initiatives and youth empowerment activities. This gave me a foundation to start my angel investment portfolio. One of my investments includes events software company iVvy, which recently launched a world-first platform for the <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/news/hot-trends-in-business-events.html" target="_blank">business events</a> industry.<br>If you have extra funds and want to give angel investment a go, here are some points to consider.<br><strong>Why are you getting into the game? </strong> <br>The first step with angel investment is to figure out what you want. Although financial returns might seem like the obvious answer, there are a growing number of people who do it for the lifestyle &ndash; to be part of the Silicon Valley buzz or receive awards for artistic projects. There are others who do it for positive <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/social-media-blogs/social-media-and-its-impact-on-the-sales-process-29062012.html" target="_blank">social impact</a> or to support a cause / passion.<br><strong>It is not like the stock market </strong> <br>Angel investment is different to trading in equities or investing in public markets. Investors are typically more hands on and involved in the company and its direction. There is no easy cash-in/ cash-out strategy and you can&rsquo;t predict risks as you would with stocks and mutual funds.<br>When you invest in a company, you usually buy into equity and not just a percentage of profits or revenue. The share of investment can&rsquo;t be easily divested, taken to the bank or cashed when you need money.<br><strong>Personal investment and history of entrepreneur</strong> <br>Know whether you want to invest in someone who has a history in managing startups or a young graduate with the next killer idea. Neither of these options are failsafe. You invest in ideas and people, so be sure you believe in the product and also look around at what is being said about the company and / or industry in social media and news.<br><strong>You don&rsquo;t have to do it alone</strong> <br>There are many active angel groups/ communities that you could join in Australia. These groups will put you in touch with businesses looking for funding. Joining group&rsquo;s gives you combined opinions, advice and more networks to tap into. More seasoned members may also be willing to teach you the ropes.<br><strong>Think about your timing </strong> <br>Know at what stage of the business you want to invest in. While early investment into a business has the potential of getting more equity for your money, the risk is higher due to teething concerns of the new venture and not knowing market acceptance for the product.<br>Investing after the business has been operational for a few years will increase the valuation and often result in less equity; but is less risky and offers <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/news/how-to-land-the-investor-big-bucks-02042014.html" target="_blank">quicker exits</a>.', 'Points to consider when entering into angel investment', 'Why are you getting into the game? It is not like the stock market. Personal investment and history of entrepreneur. You donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t have to do it alone. Think about your timing. ', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 8, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0);
INSERT INTO `advices` (`id`, `co_author_first`, `co_author_last`, `challenge_id`, `decision_type_id`, `category_id`, `source_url`, `advice_decision_date`, `advice_title`, `advice_image`, `executive_summary`, `challenge_addressing`, `key_advice_points`, `publication_name`, `context_role_user_id`, `advice_views`, `advice_posted_date`, `advice_update_date`, `status_id`) VALUES
(148, NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 135, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/opinion/do-you-have-an-exit-strategy-20062014.html', '2014-06-20 00:00:00', 'Do you have an exit strategy?', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Do you have an exit strategy? </strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/opinion/do-you-have-an-exit-strategy-20062014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/opinion/do-you-have-an-exit-strategy-20062014.html</a> <br>Successful entrepreneurs (especially serial entrepreneurs) consider exit strategies as the foundation of the vision and planning for their new venture &ndash; a question to be addressed at the start. <br>Aside from giving the business a sense of purpose, a clear exit strategy also helps in generating financial support. <br>Here are a few considerations to think about while planning to sell your business for a profit in a few years:<br><strong>Start early</strong> <br>The oft-heard mantra when talking exit strategies is: &ldquo;the sooner, the better&rdquo;. Exit planning should ideally start when your business does. <br>Thinking about exit from the business early on also gives you the acceptance and understanding of how much growth you can achieve within a given timeframe.<br><strong>Seek professional advice early</strong> <br>Start speaking to accountants, advisors and other planning experts prior to developing your exit strategy, so you know what factors to consider and are structuring it into feasible timeframes. Their help in building the valuation of your business is important to increasing the chances of selling at maximum price. Their due diligence and marketing advice will frame your strategies over the years leading up to the sale.<br><strong>Build your value </strong> <br>Managing price and valuation expectation at the start is essential to exit planning. As most small businesses often sell to people within their networks, it is also important to think about how they perceive the values of your company.<br><strong>Ensure the business can run without you</strong> <br>Owners/managers play a significant role in business &ndash; from product development, business generation to leadership and team management. However, buyers are interested in the business and not your job. <br>Investing in your employees and helping them grow is integral to building the value of the business and, getting the best price for it.<br><strong>Set a plan for yourself</strong> <br>Knowing what you want to do after you exit the business is as important as your exit strategy. <br>That&rsquo;s why, it is important to gradually make yourself redundant from the business by grooming your team, so you have time to cope with the change. Don&rsquo;t think of exit strategies as retirement.', 'Considerations to think about while planning to sell your business ', 'Start early. Seek professional advice early. Build your value. Ensure the business can run without you. Set a plan for yourself.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 6, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(149, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/the-key-challenges-facing-every-entrepreneur-16052014.html', '2014-05-16 00:00:00', 'The key challenges facing every entrepreneur', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - The key challenges facing every entrepreneur</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/the-key-challenges-facing-every-entrepreneur-16052014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/the-key-challenges-facing-every-entrepreneur-16052014.html</a> <br>If you are in a 9 to 5 job and are thinking of starting your own business, or are a sole operator or small business aiming to grow, now is the best time. You will face challenges as an entrepreneur. But the good thing is that most challenges are the same that others in your situation have confronted before and overcome. As with leading a positive life, you learn from others and apply to your business.<br>Here are a few common challenges and easy suggestions to manage them:<br><strong>1. Pick the right idea: </strong>Talk to many, many people about your idea and research it fully. Belief in a product or service is great. But it&rsquo;ll only get you that far if people aren&rsquo;t willing to spend money. If you don&rsquo;t have an audience as yet, it is you and your vision that people are buying into &ndash; not just what you sell. Failure is often a result of lack of preparation and acceptance of what is achievable by you.<br><strong>2.</strong> <strong>Quality above all else:</strong> As an entrepreneur, you are constantly juggling payroll, bookkeeping, operational, manufacturing, customer service, issues management and many other tasks. More so when business is growing marginally but not enough to employ a support team. This is when most businesses drop their game. <br>Every customer is your indirect salesperson or brand advocate. Ensure their loyalty by giving them your best. If quality is being compromised, don&rsquo;t take on more customers.<br><strong>3.</strong> <strong>Finding the right customers: </strong>Understand who your customer is and build that community. Don&rsquo;t waste time on people who do not reciprocate interest in your product. Empower your customers to decide what they want by engaging with them. Pushiness often results in wasted effort and negative brand perception.<br><strong>4.</strong> <strong>Initial investment: </strong>If you don&rsquo;t have funding, start small and earn top dollar before you invest more. Make success your only option for more funding. Aim for higher profit margins than just increased revenue. Get a <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/sustainable-cash-flow-strategies-for-service-businesses-28012014.html" target="_blank">sustainable cash flow</a> process going before investing more.<br><strong>5.</strong> <strong>Preparing for uncertainties: </strong>The only way you can put your fears to ease is by confronting them and having a plan to tackle uncertainty. Plan for the months when cash flow could be low and for a contingency if your product or service is replaced due to market innovation, or if you are hit with a recession. <br><strong>6.</strong> <strong>Finding the right employees: </strong>In your role as an employer, you are the mentor, leader and paycheck provider to the people you bring on board. Be prepared to do all three well. Beware of becoming a sounding board for someone else&rsquo;s issues and handholding them too much. Remember that leadership is defined by creating more leaders, not just by leading. Give your employees a voice and help them grow with you, so they stick around when the going gets tough.', 'How to manage the challenges entrepreneurs face', 'Pick the right idea. Quality above all else. Finding the right customers. Initial investment. Preparing for uncertainties. Finding the right employees. ', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 9, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(150, NULL, NULL, NULL, 11, 134, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/its-time-to-future-proof-australian-entrepreneurship-17042014.html', '2014-04-17 00:00:00', 'ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s time to future-proof Australian entrepreneurship', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - It&rsquo;s time to future-proof Australian entrepreneurship</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/its-time-to-future-proof-australian-entrepreneurship-17042014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/its-time-to-future-proof-australian-entrepreneurship-17042014.html</a> <br>Economists believe that entrepreneurship and diversified spread of sectors will be key to shaping our financial future. If this is to be, the fact that&nbsp; and only 50% nascent firms even reach operational stage needs to change. With the SME sector in Australia employing 70% of the workforce, it is crucial for the country to sustain and grow the entrepreneurial community.<br>While the spirit of entrepreneurship and innovation is alive and well in Australia, some fundamental changes are needed to the system to ensure ideas fuel future growth.<br><strong>Innovation vs success:</strong> Mentorship, increased government involvement, more support from banks and other financial institutions will all help the long-term commercialisation of ideas. While start-ups need help in navigating the initial tough years, small businesses need support that gives them confidence to grow and maintain operations locally.<br><strong>Perception of failure:</strong> Majority of entrepreneurs who cannot make their first idea stick, give up and get back into the workforce as an employee assuming business isn&rsquo;t for them. Entrepreneurs tend to fail because of lack of proper preparation. Failure needs to be reflected upon so you can get it right the next time. Was the product right for the market? Could it have been priced differently? Were you priced competitively? How much research did you do? Were your expenses and investment significantly higher than your returns?<br>Not every idea is a brilliant and failure can teach us a lot. Reflection on the mistakes of the past gives us the opportunity to learn and get it right the next time<br><strong>Funding:</strong> Funding models in Australia need to change on two intrinsic levels: 1) increased awareness of and requests for funding by entrepreneurs at nascent stage and, 2) more funding available at VC stage.<br><strong>Education:</strong> A fundamental change is needed in the education system to teach all students about entrepreneurship. Beyond business schools, entrepreneurship has not been promoted well in academic curriculum across all levels from high school to universities. This has to change if we want more innovators to create successful businesses that stay on Australian shores.<br>Entrepreneurship needs to transcend from innovation and starting a business to creating a change in the society and be relevant not just in 2050, but beyond.', 'Fundamental changes needed to fuel future growth', 'Innovation vs success. Perception of failure. Funding. Education.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 9, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(151, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/funding-101-where-does-the-money-come-from-24032014.html', '2014-03-24 00:00:00', 'Funding 101: Where does the money come from?', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Funding 101: Where does the money come from?</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/funding-101-where-does-the-money-come-from-24032014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/funding-101-where-does-the-money-come-from-24032014.html</a> <br>Businesses go through different stages of funding depending on their lifecycle. Even if you are still in your day job and thinking about starting your business, it is worthwhile understanding the different types and stage so you can:<br><br><ul type="disc"> <li>be aware of available options</li><li>plan for <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/news/capitalise-on-asian-century-with-tourism-growth-27082013.html" target="_blank">growth</a> and know at what stages cash injections are required</li><li>figure out how much you want to grow by</li><li>know your limits / boundaries</li></ul><br>The different types of funding available are Seed or Concept, Startup, Venture Capital (Series A, B and C stages) and Harvest (IPO).<br><strong>Seed or concept stage</strong> is the passionate inventor stage where there isn&rsquo;t a management team or prototype. This is the first injection of capital into the idea or company. The most common funding at this stage comes from: personal savings, <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/finance-cash-flow/company-credit-cards-reap-rewards-06032014.html" target="_blank">credit cards</a>, family and friends, grants, bank borrowing and non-bank finance.<br>Most banks don&rsquo;t fund startups but lend against property. Depending on your product or service, you could also crowdfund your idea at this stage to raise capital. A good idea and a solid plan can raise anywhere between a few thousand to hundreds of thousands to get the business off the ground.<br><strong>Startup stage </strong>is classified as when the business in underway, working with clients or customers and yielding revenues.The most popular funding options in this stage are: self-funded from profits, angel investment and grants. Angels come in with money after you have started selling. They jump aboard because you now have tangible proof of concept.<br>Angel funding usually scales up to $2 million. Angel investors often play a big role in mentoring the business as well. They&rsquo;re likely to be after businesses with exceptional growth prospects, so you&rsquo;ll need to demonstrate your <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/is-social-media-affecting-your-bottom-line-19032014.html" target="_blank">potential</a>.<br><strong>Venture capital (Series A, B and C) stage </strong>has been combined as the different series are typically funded by Venture capitalists (VC&rsquo;s). According to Commonwealth Bank, venture capitalists are professional investors who invest in promising businesses and help them grow, often to the point where they&rsquo;re ready to be listed on the share market.<br>They make money by selling their share in your business, either on the share market or to someone else. A venture capitalist will typically seek to exit your business in three to five years with a return of 35 per cent p.a. or more. They&rsquo;ll generally look to invest between $2m and $10m, depending on your business.<br><strong>Harvest or IPO stage </strong>is the big pay off after years of hard work when the company gets listed on the stock exchange or acquired by a bigger entity. What started out as a dream has become an entrepreneurial reality. The next challenge is to start all over again, but this time with a little more money.<br>Although it could seem overwhelming, think about your funding strategy as soon as you have your business idea. Even if you don&rsquo;t plan on seeking <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/crowdfunding-the-new-normal-in-brand-marketing-21022014.html" target="_blank">funding</a>, it&rsquo;ll give you a picture of where you will be ten years down the track.', 'The different types of funding', 'Seed or concept stage. Startup stage. Venture capital (Series A, B and C) stage. Harvest or IPO stage.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 10, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(152, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.womensagenda.com.au/talking-about/top-stories/how-to-ask-for-money-to-grow-a-killer-idea/201403033673#.VF_2MRbEnIU', '2014-03-04 00:00:00', 'How to ask for money to grow a killer idea', '', '<strong>Women&rsquo;s Agenda - How to ask for money to grow a killer idea</strong><br><a href="http://www.womensagenda.com.au/talking-about/top-stories/how-to-ask-for-money-to-grow-a-killer-idea/201403033673#.VF_2MRbEnIU" target="_blank">http://www.womensagenda.com.au/talking-about/top-stories/how-to-ask-for-money-to-grow-a-killer-idea/201403033673#.VF_2MRbEnIU</a> <br>Women need to overcome what could be an inherent hesitancy in seeking funding for their killer ideas. Given women angel investors and VC''s are a minority, there is no choice but to be brave and ask for more money. One of the best ways to break down gender stereotypes in the male dominated VC space will be to see more women entrepreneurs pitching confidently for funding.<br>The below pointers could help:<br><strong>Illustrate the opportunity and talk about the vision</strong>: It is important to pitch passionately and discuss current growth; but more so to illustrate future potential and the vision. Especially when women start a business that reflects their personal interests and have to pitch to men who lack those interests.<br><strong>Be confident</strong>: This goes beyond taking a few deep breaths and connecting with everyone in the room. Confidence in pitching for funding also stems from visualising why women entrepreneurs are successful. A <a href="http://www.dowjones.com/collateral/files/WomenPE_report_final.pdf" target="_blank">2012 study by Dow Jones</a> reported that 61% of start-ups with five or more females were successful and only 39% failed. Research success stories to take pointers and be inspired. <br><strong>Failure is good</strong>: Most women tend to take failure personally and get disheartened &ndash; which could affect their next pitch. Women should instead view failures as the opportunity to get feedback on their process and use it to nail their next pitch. Women are more risk averse then men and only when we cross this barrier and accept failure as part of constant growth will we succeed.<br><strong>Know your negotiation boundaries</strong>: Before you go into a pitch, know your negotiation baselines and don''t compromise beyond what you can''t or don''t want to. Investors will push to gauge commitment and determination and the pitch process is their first exposure to how you manage under that pressure. Don''t undersell the value of your business, its current success and the IP the team brings to the table.<br><strong>Use numbers wisely</strong>: I''ve seen women overuse statistics and metrics to support every point they make and from a belief that that''s the language male VC''s and investors understand. Numbers are only your proof point that supports the vision and not the pitch in itself. The pitch can be peppered with stats on customer in itself. The core story of how you generate more money can only evolve from selling acquisition, costs, unit economics, etc., but they need to flow into the strategy rather than becoming the strategy the vision.<br><strong>Showcase a clear ability to exit:</strong> Your exit strategy shows the strength of your financial plan and how soon investors can realise returns-on-investment (ROI). It''s fine to have the business as a hobby and something you will continue working on for a lifetime. If not, be sure to include your exit strategy highlighting how you''ll make $5 million in five years if that''s your vision. Investors will then be confident in your ability to deliver ROI as you are bound by a timeline.', 'Pointers for women entrepreneurs seeking for funding', 'Illustrate the opportunity and talk about the vision. Be confident. Failure is good. Know your negotiation boundaries. Use numbers wisely. Showcase a clear ability to exit.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 8, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(153, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/crowdfunding-the-new-normal-in-brand-marketing-21022014.html', '2014-02-21 00:00:00', 'Crowdfunding the new normal in brand marketing', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Crowdfunding the new normal in brand marketing</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/crowdfunding-the-new-normal-in-brand-marketing-21022014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/crowdfunding-the-new-normal-in-brand-marketing-21022014.html</a> <br>Much has been written on how to crowdfund a <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/sales-and-marketing/create-an-effective-integrated-marketing-campaign-step-by-step-24092013.html" target="_blank">campaign</a>, but I&rsquo;d like to focus on the marketing benefits of a crowdfunding campaign to entrepreneurs, businesses and brands at large.<br>Traditionally, businesses have engaged with customers after the product or service is ready to market. Crowdfunding has turned this theory on its head by giving businesses, artists, entrepreneurs and brands the ability to market directly to customers well before it launches. And, as crowdfunding is a pull strategy rather than push, it ensures an avid interest and engagement from customers &ndash; giving entrepreneurs <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/small-business-resources/managing/improve-sales-by-taking-a-coaching-approach-15082012.html" target="_blank">sales confidence</a> in their product or service.<br><strong>Pre-plan your strategy</strong> <br>Businesses and entrepreneurs considering crowdfunding should be prepared to tackle marketing, customer loyalty and engagement strategies well in advance of product or service launch. If you have 91,585 people engaging with your brand, how will you communicate with them? What data capture and management systems do you have in place to consistently communicate with people engaging with your brand and how are you rewarding their loyalty?<br>While large companies will continue to spend on traditional market research and product development, crowdfunding is a good alternative for small to medium sized businesses with budget constraints. Social media platforms are also pivotal in creating brand advocates who can assist in ongoing product/service development.<br>The other marketing benefit of crowdfunding is campaign flexibility. <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/crowdfunding-platform-indiegogo-launches-in-aud-31102013.html" target="_blank">Crowdfunded</a> campaigns can be adapted, scaled and changed almost real time depending on the feedback from funding public. For example, if people engage more on Twitter than Facebook, you know that&rsquo;s where your core target audience lies. Accordingly, you can allocate time and budgets into building a relevant content calendar.<br><a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/new-crowdfunding-campaign-to-support-young-entrepreneurs-in-the-g20-yea-25042013.html" target="_blank">Crowdfunding</a> also acts as a strong market research tool by giving entrepreneurs the ability to accurately assess demand. If people are not interested in paying even $1 towards funding, entrepreneurs need to question the validity of the product or service and its ability to sell. Alternatively, if the product or service has strong demand, it creates conversation starters for strategy partnerships and acquisition opportunities. <br>Quick tips for anyone considering crowdfunding:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Research and prepare for your campaign.</li><li>Have engaging content that shows your brand or product&rsquo;s personality.</li><li>Engage participants and supporters throughout the campaign with updates to keep the momentum going.</li><li>Create perks that corporate brands can invest in and/or become sponsors of.</li><li>When it comes to corporate sponsorship, think of it more as you giving the brand an opportunity to connect with thousands of people instead of you seeking funding alone.</li></ul>', 'The marketing benefits of a crowdfunding campaign', 'Crowdfunding is a good alternative for small to medium sized businesses with budget constraints. Social media platforms are also pivotal in creating brand advocates who can assist in ongoing product/service development. Crowdfunded campaigns can be adapted, scaled and changed almost real time depending on the feedback from funding public. Crowdfunding also acts as a strong market research tool by giving entrepreneurs the ability to accurately assess demand.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 9, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(154, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 93, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/sustainable-cash-flow-strategies-for-service-businesses-28012014.html', '2014-01-28 00:00:00', 'Sustainable cash flow strategies for service businesses', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Sustainable cash flow strategies for service businesses</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/sustainable-cash-flow-strategies-for-service-businesses-28012014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/sustainable-cash-flow-strategies-for-service-businesses-28012014.html</a> <br>For entrepreneurs and small business, now is the time to assess priorities for the year and strategise how to take your business to the next level. In <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/aussies-planning-to-work-through-the-holidays-16122013.html" target="_blank">planning</a> for growth and expansion, cash flow strategies are often relegated to an &lsquo;ongoing process&rsquo; rather than a focused discussion and strategy.<br>To ensure healthy business growth, implement a sustainable cash flow strategy now and plan ahead.<br><strong>Aim for long-term financial stability</strong> <br>To build a financially stable business set finance and cash flow goals for the business.<br>Realistically assessing how and when you want to reach your long-term financial goal helps in a few ways, namely:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Avoids the pitfalls of reviewing cash flow from a short-term perspective.</li><li>Plans for cash flow around growth and expansion strategies.</li><li>Makes you think of your ability to earn money in the future.</li></ul><br>Also, for people who allow purchases on credit, it helps in forecasting how much cash is coming into the business and, if it is sufficient to cover expenses and make a tidy profit.<br><strong>Profit first and growth later</strong> <br>A financially sustainable business is one that can pay for itself without having to borrow a great deal (or not at all). Rather than borrowing, aim for increased profit and use retained profits to grow your business. <br><strong>Timing is everything </strong> <br>You have to know when money is coming in and when it goes out. You should know your two to three month cash flow projections without having to look at sheets.<br>When creating your cash flow forecast estimate how much you will make and when you can expect to receive payment &ndash; expected and actual payment details.<br>Here&rsquo;s a quick cash flow checklist for service businesses:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>Have clearly defined terms of trade on your quote that clients have signed and agreed to.</li></ul><ul type="disc"> <li>Invoice regularly to assure a steady cash flow and follow up payments per agreed terms.&nbsp; </li></ul><ul type="disc"> <li>Prepare 12-month cash flow projections that you update <strong>regularly. </strong> Listing all your overheads will give you a minimum income <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/linkedin-scam-targets-bilinguals-with-pretty-face-25112013.html" target="_blank">target</a> required to sustain your business.</li></ul><ul type="disc"> <li>Most businesses live off the philosophy that &ldquo;deposits from the new job will pay for expenses from the previous job&rdquo;. This is OK when the business is young and growing but is detrimental in the longer term &ndash; especially in a tough economic climate.</li></ul><ul type="disc"> <li>Don&rsquo;t put all your eggs in one basket. Make sure your income comes from a number of sources. </li></ul><ul type="disc"> <li>Know your profitability. Reconcile each job for profit or loss. This empowers you to know the profitability of each job and recognise what category jobs are most profitable for your business and which ones to avoid. This will also help avoid over-servicing.</li></ul><br>Cash flow issues hit most businesses at some point in time. Preparation and forewarning will enable you to tackle the situation to shape your financial stability and sustainability.', 'How to implement a sustainable cash flow strategy', 'Aim for long-term financial stability. Profit first and growth later. Timing is everything.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 9, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(155, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.womensagenda.com.au/personal-freedom/investment/want-to-invest-in-another-womans-business-this-is-what-you-need-to-know/201311133197#.VF_2bhbEnIU', '2013-11-14 00:00:00', 'Want to invest in another womanÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s business? This is what you need to know', '', '<strong>Womens Agenda - Want to invest in another woman&rsquo;s business? This is what you need to know</strong><br><a href="http://www.womensagenda.com.au/personal-freedom/investment/want-to-invest-in-another-womans-business-this-is-what-you-need-to-know/201311133197#.VF_2bhbEnIU" target="_blank">http://www.womensagenda.com.au/personal-freedom/investment/want-to-invest-in-another-womans-business-this-is-what-you-need-to-know/201311133197#.VF_2bhbEnIU</a> <br>The concept of investing in another business or going down the path of becoming an angel investor has traditionally been associated with men. This is slowly changing. Women are capitalising on open markets, innovation and progress to investing their wealth and resources into other businesses. Women angel investors are the new breed mapping the entrepreneurial landscape.<br><strong>For women who are interested in investing in a business, here a few pointers to consider:</strong><br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Blend your passion with the business idea</strong>: When you start talking money, you will have people coming out of the woodworks trying to convince you to invest in their venture. While most ideas will be good, you will only be able to navigate the rush by identifying what you are passionate about at the outset. Match your passion to the business idea and not the other way around. </li><li><strong>Take risks and disrupt the landscape</strong>: The markets and industries are evolving at a phenomenal pace. To stay ahead of the game, businesses will have to adopt disruptive innovation methodologies. It is easy to trial a better concept of an existing product but nerve racking to do something that has no case study. Unfortunately, there is no magic formula to this approach &ndash; only trial and error. </li><li><strong>Crowdsourced funding</strong>: If you are donating only a portion of the funds to support the business, encourage the entrepreneur to consider crowdsourced funding opportunities. Websites such as Pozible and Kickstarter are great for this. </li></ul><br>The crowd-funding premise is based on the fact that people who fund the project connect with it more meaningfully and like something back in return. If it is a film then invite them to the opening or get them to contribute to the script, if products then give people free samples, if a service then discounts or acknowledgments on websites and social media &ndash; the opportunities are endless and not necessarily expensive.<br><ul type="disc"> <li><strong>Work the digital media</strong>: Social media is the new word-of-mouth and social footprint is the new brand equity. For start-ups that are cash tight, social media provides the best platform to communicate with stakeholders, communities and consumers with the most up-to-date information. Explore the possibilities and get the business to construct a cohesive social media strategy from start. </li></ul>', 'Points to consider when investing in a business', 'Blend your passion with the business idea. Take risks and disrupt the landscape. Crowdsourced funding. Work the digital media.', 'Renata Cooper', 195, 29, '2014-11-27 09:58:18', '2014-11-27 09:58:18', 0),
(156, 'Ido', 'Leffler', NULL, 2, 4, 'http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/how-start-a-business', '2014-03-20 00:00:00', '4 Steps to Making Any Big Idea Take Off', '', '<strong>Women&rsquo;s Health &ndash; 4 Steps to Making Any Big Idea Take Off</strong><br><a href="http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/how-start-a-business" target="_blank">http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/how-start-a-business</a><br>To launch your own big idea, look for opportunities in unexpected places and realize that you don''t have to go to the best business school to learn the entrepreneurial skills that will allow you to succeed. Here are four tips to get you started.<br><strong>Bond with like minds.</strong><br>Work with people you trust and can build a long-term partnership with. The more their progress is aligned with yours, the more committed they will be to making sure you succeed. Also&ndash;and we can''t overemphasize this&ndash;being an entrepreneur can be the loneliest, most isolating job in the world, so get very good, very quickly, at finding people who can act as a support system.<br><strong>Recognize momentum.</strong><br>You can have the best idea in the world, but if the timing isn''t right, you''re up a creek. We sensed a growing interest in natural beauty. In general, natural and organic products were clearly more than a fad, but the natural-beauty market was still emerging at the time, meaning the big companies didn''t even bother taking notice of it. We knew we were doing something special.<br><strong>Be authentic.</strong><br>Don''t put on a business persona&ndash;if it''s not you, it will just come across as awkward. When we were meeting with a Walgreens executive&ndash;she stood up to shake our hands. Ido realized the only way we were going to do business was if she met the real and authentic Ido. So he ignored her hand, stepped forward, and wrapped his arms around her. The hug was a hugely risky move, and we don''t recommend indiscriminate hugging as an everyday practice&ndash;but it worked!<br><strong>Catch your wave.</strong><br>Be confident, even if you face setbacks. If you want to build something fast, you have to be prepared to jump into the water and swim. We got the basics right. We created a product that people loved, that worked, and that we were passionate about. And then we gave it everything we had!', '4 Tips to help you launch your own big idea', 'Bond with like minds. Recognize momentum. Be authentic. Catch your wave.', 'Lance Kalish', 193, 34, '2014-11-27 10:16:47', '2014-11-27 10:16:47', 0),
(157, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 81, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/07/10/a-framework-for-making-creative-decisions/', '2012-07-10 00:00:00', 'A framework for making creative decisions', '', '<strong>Posse - A framework for making creative decisions</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/07/10/a-framework-for-making-creative-decisions/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/07/10/a-framework-for-making-creative-decisions/</a> <br>If you&rsquo;ve produced anything, you know that creative decision making is challenging.&nbsp; If a project is big, (like for example a website or a record release) then the number of people involved increases and stakes of making good decisions increase.&nbsp; But the world&rsquo;s best creative works very rarely come from teams.&nbsp; They&rsquo;re the product of a single artist, musician, author or inventor. &nbsp;In my experience, the bigger the team the harder it is to make the right decisions.<br>I can take what I&rsquo;ve learned in music and create a framework for making functional, creative decisions at Posse. &nbsp;Here are my views on the process.<br><strong>1. Define your values</strong> <br>Early on, James Scollay, ran a session with me to define Posse&rsquo;s brand values. He suggested that I come up with up to five core values that, when combined, could govern the brand and company.&nbsp; My answers back then haven&rsquo;t changed.&nbsp; They are: <strong>&lsquo;Everyone Wins&rsquo;</strong>, &lsquo;<strong>Delightful&rsquo;</strong>, <strong>&lsquo;Greatness&rsquo;,</strong> <strong>&lsquo;Revolutionary&rsquo;</strong> and &lsquo;<strong>Integrity&rsquo;</strong>.&nbsp; Even through all of our iterations, the bases for making decisions about our brand, user experience and company culture have remained constant.&nbsp; Values are often a reflection of the entrepreneur and their dreams, but when there&rsquo;s a team, they become the team&rsquo;s&nbsp;values as well.<br><strong>2. Trust the instincts of one talented person over a committee.</strong> <br>Great creativity is the vision of one exceptionally talented person, so it&rsquo;s vital to choose this person carefully and then trust them.&nbsp; Don&rsquo;t try to second-guess their decisions or you&rsquo;ll encourage them to play safe, then they&rsquo;ll make boring and wrong decisions.&nbsp; Note that safe creative decisions and disastrous creative decisions tend to be the same thing! &nbsp; <br>Don&rsquo;t think that by involving a committee you&rsquo;ll get more buy-in, that people will feel more empowered to promote the result.&nbsp; If the creative result is brilliant, everyone will want to be associated with it no matter whose vision it was.<br><strong>3. Know and test your target market</strong> <br>In music, we had only the vaguest ideas of our target market.&nbsp; There was no science behind how we defined the audience for an artist.&nbsp; Music is somewhat easier than launching a new product, as you can piggyback onto the market of other artists.<br>But if you&rsquo;re launching a new product like Posse, you have to think through your approach in much more detail.&nbsp; Recently, we had to choose how to design our stores and town, and had five artists submit concepts.&nbsp; They were all good but very different.&nbsp; My first thought was to share the designs with as many people as I could to get feedback.&nbsp; I sent them to about fifty friends and our whole team.&nbsp; Everyone had a strong and different opinion &ndash; all five had about the same number of lovers and haters.&nbsp; It was very confusing!<br>To help make a decision, we decided to define our target market and test people only in that market.&nbsp; But would that give us a result that was too niche?&nbsp; I decided to define and test our target market, which wouldn&rsquo;t be everyone but would be big.<br>One thing I am good at is spotting great creative talent when I see it, and by following a framework of defining our values, trusting the talent, knowing and testing our target market I feel like I&rsquo;m in a much better position to make critical creative decisions that will define our product.', 'Tips on making creative decisions', 'Define your values. Trust the instincts of one talented person over a committee. Know and test your target market.', 'Rebekah Campbell', 178, 9, '2014-11-27 14:51:09', '2014-11-27 14:51:09', 0),
(158, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 24, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/06/12/redesigning-our-strategy/', '2012-06-12 00:00:00', 'Redesigning our strategy', '', '<strong>Posse - Redesigning our strategy</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/06/12/redesigning-our-strategy/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/06/12/redesigning-our-strategy/</a><br>In February when we launched Retail Posse with forty stores, only a handful of people ever successfully made recommendations and earned points.  With more than $3 million in investment behind me, this was a frightening, stressful discovery! &nbsp;What next?<br>First, we had to look at our site from the perspective of a customer / user. &nbsp;What would they want Posse to do? &nbsp;What real world problems do they have that we can solve? &nbsp;Then, how can we make the site so original, so fun and so magical that when they use it they can&rsquo;t wait to run out and tell their friends. &nbsp;Only if we could figure out how to design a product that people loved would we have a shot at creating something successful.<br>We approached the process of finding our new strategy in three phases.<br><strong>1. What do users want?</strong> <br>If users are going to engage with our platform then we&rsquo;d have to solve real and significant problems they face in the real world. &nbsp;To find this I ran a series of fourteen focus groups and over thirty one-on-one user interviews. I can only say I found the process incredibly helpful. &nbsp;True, people won&rsquo;t tell you what they want &ndash; that&rsquo;s for the entrepreneur to dream up. &nbsp;But by asking questions you can learn about their sore spots, where they are frustrated in their lives. &nbsp;The questions I asked at these focus groups led to answers that helped me understand the customer problems we could solve.<br><strong>2. How can we make it fun?</strong> <br>There&rsquo;s so much competition that if I&rsquo;m to get excited about something it must be fun, so original it feels like magic.  I started to research gamification and I found a <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6O1gNVeaE4g" target="_blank" title="clip of a guy called Gabe Zichermann on YouTube.">clip of a guy called Gabe Zichermann on YouTube</a>.&nbsp;&nbsp;I played this clip to the whole team at lunchtime and we all concluded we needed to design Posse as a game.<br>Next, I ran a two-hour strategy session every day for a month (including weekends). &nbsp;Each day, the sessions involved different people. &nbsp;Sometimes it was small groups of members of the Posse team.&nbsp; Some days we&rsquo;d hammer away and only make a little progress. &nbsp;But generally, something, perhaps a comment or observation, would emerge from each session to spark an idea that bore fruit in the next. &nbsp;<br><strong>3. How will it work?</strong> <br>The next issue was, how would the whole thing fit together? What are the rules of the game?&nbsp; How will the pages look?&nbsp; How will we engage users?&nbsp; How long will it take to build? &nbsp;We split up into small groups, tackled different parts of the problem, and then came together as a whole team to find consensus. &nbsp;Everyone had&nbsp;different opinions about things and we argued these out. <br>Instead of banging away, knowing that the fundamentals were wrong, we weren&rsquo;t afraid to go back to the drawing board and start again from scratch.<br>I also think that the intense four-month strategy process helped us discover any potential land-mines that would kill the product, and to design something that (hopefully) people will love.', 'The process of finding new strategy ', 'What do users want? How can we make it fun? How will it work?', 'Rebekah Campbell', 178, 15, '2014-11-27 14:51:09', '2014-11-27 14:51:09', 0),
(159, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 123, 'http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/05/15/my-pitching-techniques/', '2012-05-15 00:00:00', 'My pitching techniques', '', '<strong>Posse &ndash; My Pitching Techniques</strong><br><a href="http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/05/15/my-pitching-techniques/" target="_blank">http://www.rebekahcampbell.com/2012/05/15/my-pitching-techniques/</a><br>I guess that anyone reading this blog is interested in hearing how I built and delivered a powerful pitch, and how you could improve your one. Let&rsquo;s get started.<br><strong>1. &nbsp;Learn how to speak in public</strong>. &nbsp;I raised most of my first big funding round by speaking at three separate Sydney pitch events. &nbsp;As I&rsquo;ve described, I had zero public speaking experience and was terrified of addressing a group of people in a room. &nbsp;So I signed up for a ten week course. I learned how to connect with an audience, project my voice, use body language, and speak to time. &nbsp;Most importantly, I overcame my dread of public speaking so I could concentrate on getting my message across. <br><strong>2. Build a narrative that will captivate and inspire.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;You have one minute to win people&rsquo;s attention. &nbsp;Always start your pitch with a story that clearly articulates the problem your product will solve in a way they can relate to. &nbsp;The listener must understand who has the problem and what it is before they can start to engage in your solution. &nbsp;<br>Next, you explain how your product will solve the problem: inspire your listener at the size of the opportunity. &nbsp;But if your product is for a more niche market then you need to show how big the market is.<br><strong>3. Show why you are the person to do this:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;Investors look for an entrepreneur who&rsquo;s had previous success and understands the market they are entering. &nbsp;Try to find a clever way to establish this as early as possible, as your credibility will change the way they listen to the rest of the pitch. &nbsp;<br><strong>4. Use exciting visuals:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;Every book you read on presenting will tell you: don&rsquo;t use boring visuals with lots of words or graphs that people can&rsquo;t read! &nbsp;But, almost every entrepreneur does this. &nbsp;PowerPoint or other visual presentations work by helping to give your presentation structure and driving home points. &nbsp;<br><strong>5. Know your stuff</strong>: Two things you must know back to front before you start pitching: a) Your competitors, and b) Your numbers. &nbsp;Build an overview of both of these into your pitch so you can show you&rsquo;ve thought things through. You should have scoped out the market for other companies doing similar things to you.&nbsp;<br>You need to have a financial model. You must demonstrate a clear plan to investors; they&rsquo;re entitled to know how you&rsquo;ll spend their money and how you intend to make money in the long run. &nbsp;Investors love asking about your projected profit in two years&rsquo; time, how many sales people or how much marketing you&rsquo;ll require to reach that many customers, what it will cost, the potential for this in five years&rsquo; time, what percentage of the total market you anticipate, and is that realistic? &nbsp;<br><strong>6. Practise. </strong>&nbsp;Once you&rsquo;ve built your pitch, go out and deliver it to as many people as you possibly can. &nbsp;Each person you pitch to will probably recommend that you see someone else (even if they don&rsquo;t want to invest).&nbsp;It takes a long time, but after each meeting you work out how to improve your pitch. &nbsp;You&rsquo;ll find yourself rearranging the PowerPoint slides, adding extra information they found exciting, deleting slides that seem irrelevant. &nbsp;Each potential investor will ask you different questions, which prepares you for when you meet the ones that really count.', 'How to deliver a powerful pitch', 'Learn how to speak in public. Build a narrative that will captivate and inspire. Show why you are the person to do this. Use exciting visuals. Know your stuff. Practise.', 'Rebekah Campbell', 178, 37, '2014-11-27 14:51:09', '2014-11-27 14:51:09', 0);
