(160, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 94, 'http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/managing/protect-your-business-when-staff-leave-20141029-3j31m.html', '2014-10-29 00:00:00', 'Protect your business when staff leave', '', '<strong>Startup Smart - Protect your business when staff leave</strong><br><a href="http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/managing/protect-your-business-when-staff-leave-20141029-3j31m.html" target="_blank">http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/managing/protect-your-business-when-staff-leave-20141029-3j31m.html</a> <br>If your best and brightest employees leave your business, they could they take valuable confidential information, know-how and intellectual property. So how can employers protect these assets?<br><strong>Employment agreement - intellectual property rights</strong> <br>Employees often create or access intellectual property. Some intellectual property rights are clear and automatic under general law or legislation. Other areas are unclear and should be addressed in an employment agreement.<br><em>Copyright</em>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<em>Copyright Act 1968&nbsp;</em>(Cth)<br>If a &lsquo;work&rsquo; (artistic, literary, musical or dramatic) is created by someone in pursuance of his or her employment, or under a contract of service, it is generally the employer&rsquo;s property.<br><em>Designs -&nbsp;</em>Designs Act 2003 (Cth)<br>Designs created in the course of employment or under a contract will belong to the employer and will be registered on the designs register in the employer&rsquo;s name. <br><em>Patents</em> <br>A range of inventions can be patented, including appliances, devices and computer-related inventions. The employment agreement can include that the employer is entitled to apply for patent protection for an invention by an employee, if invented in the course of employment.<br><em>Know how</em> <br>Other intellectual property, including trade secrets and confidential information, has some protection under common law and equity. It is not possible, however, to prevent an ex-employee from making use of his or her general know-how after leaving the business.<br><strong>Employment contract &ndash;&nbsp;confidential information</strong> <br>An employee has general law duties not to use or disclose confidential information obtained by virtue of the employment relationship in any way which benefits the employee or a third party. <br><strong>Employment contract &ndash;&nbsp;non-compete clause</strong> <br>Non-compete clauses are designed to prevent employees from engaging in certain conduct that may damage the employer&rsquo;s business. A well-drafted non-compete clause includes prohibitions on soliciting past or current clients, poaching past or current employees, and interfering with contractual relationships including supply relationships.<br><strong>Limiting access</strong> <br>You can take practical steps to protect your business including limiting employees&rsquo; access to intellectual property and confidential information. For example, only senior staff and employees in development roles can access confidential business planning. <br><strong>Exit letter &ndash; specific and implied obligations</strong> <br>It is wise to provide departing employees with an exit letter that sets out their obligations under the employment agreement and their general law obligations.&nbsp;<br><ul> <li>a duty of good faith, including a duty not to solicit customers of the business.</li><li>a duty not to use or disclose confidential information obtained by virtue of the working relationship, in any way which benefits the ex-employee or a third party.</li></ul>', 'How to safeguard your business when an employee leaves', 'Employment agreement - intellectual property rights. Employment contract -  confidential information. Employment contract - non-compete clause.', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 27, '2014-12-01 09:52:14', '2014-12-01 09:52:14', 0),
(161, NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 135, 'http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/insurance/surviving-death-in-a-small-business-20140822-3e5mh.html', '2014-08-22 00:00:00', 'Surviving death in a small business', '', '<strong>Startup Smart - Surviving death in a small business</strong><br><a href="http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/insurance/surviving-death-in-a-small-business-20140822-3e5mh.html" target="_blank">http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/insurance/surviving-death-in-a-small-business-20140822-3e5mh.html</a> <br>What will you do if your business partner passes away or is unable to work in the business? It&rsquo;s in the interests of all shareholders that you plan for these scenarios, to minimise conflicting claims and to ensure you can fund the share purchase.&nbsp;<br>If your partner passed away today, you and the surviving shareholders may have to deal with one of several scenarios: &nbsp;<br><ul> <li><strong>Deal with a new shareholder&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; The deceased person should have dealt with their shares in their will.&nbsp; If the business has not planned for a shareholder death, then the shares may pass to the deceased&rsquo;s spouse or another heir.&nbsp; This means that your company will have a new shareholder.&nbsp; </li><li><strong>Buy out the shareholding&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; If the will is silent on the disposal of the shareholding of the deceased person, then you or the company may be able to negotiate to purchase the shareholding.&nbsp; How will you fund this?</li><li><strong>Sell your shares&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; If you do not want to continue the business without your business partner, and you or the company cannot afford to buy their shares, then you could seek to sell your shares.&nbsp; </li><li><strong>Liquidate the business&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; This is generally undesirable from a business perspective.&nbsp; It forgoes the opportunity for succession of the company including the opportunity to sell the company as a going concern.</li></ul><br>Your business can survive death of a partner with good planning and documents. 3 key documents that may assist are:<ul> <li>A buy-sell agreement between the shareholders;</li><li>A shareholders agreement between the shareholders; and</li><li>A binding financial agreement between each shareholder and their spouse.</li></ul><br><strong>Legal documents and insurance</strong> <br>A shareholders agreement is the agreement between shareholders on how the company will be run, including director and shareholder meetings, issuing new shares, and selling shares.&nbsp;<br>A buy-sell agreement is a document that provides for shareholder survivors to buy the shares of the deceased or disabled person<em>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</em>A buy-sell agreement is important for any business with more than one founder and shareholder. &nbsp;How will you fund the purchase?&nbsp; The buy-sell agreement is generally created hand-in-hand with an insurer and insurance to fund the share purchase.<br>A key issue is whether arrangements between shareholders will be enforceable against the person who inherits the shares.&nbsp;&nbsp; What can be done?&nbsp;<br>A binding financial agreement between a shareholder and their spouse may be useful.&nbsp; A binding financial agreement addresses the division of a couple''s assets<em>.</em>&nbsp;&nbsp;A binding financial agreement may define the company shares as separate property and not part of the joint matrimonial pool.&nbsp;<br><strong>Planning, documentation and insurance are key</strong> <br>It may be uncomfortable to consider the death of your business partner but it is better to have some arrangements in place, rather than none. It&rsquo;s impossible to know which of you or your co- shareholders may die first. The right legal agreements and insurance can benefit any shareholder so it is in all parties&rsquo; interests to agree these documents with your fellow shareholders.', 'Survive death of a partner with good planning and documents', 'A buy-sell agreement between the shareholders. A shareholders agreement between the shareholders. A binding financial agreement between each shareholder and their spouse.', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 6, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(162, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 94, 'http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/startup/how-to-protect-your-business-online-20140620-3aina.html', '2014-06-20 00:00:00', 'How to protect your business online', '', '<strong>Startup Smart - How to protect your business online</strong><br><a href="http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/startup/how-to-protect-your-business-online-20140620-3aina.html" target="_blank">http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/startup/how-to-protect-your-business-online-20140620-3aina.html</a> <br>What rights does registering a domain name give me? Can someone register similar domain names? Is this illegal? What can I do to protect my brand and help me get found online? <br><strong>What rights does registering a domain name give you?&nbsp;</strong> <br>A domain name is your business&rsquo; online address. Each website has its own domain name, so it is distinguishable from other sites.<br>When you register a domain name you get a license giving you the exclusive right to use that domain name for a specific period. For .au domains this is two years.<br><strong>Can someone register domain names that are similar to my business?&nbsp; Is this illegal?</strong> <br>Yes they can. For example, you may register <a href="http://www.legalvision.com.au/" target="_blank">www.legalvision.com.au</a>&nbsp;but another party could register&nbsp;<a href="http://www.legalvision.com/" target="_blank">www.legalvision.com</a>&nbsp; Is this illegal? No, simply registering domain names that are similar to another business&rsquo;s domain name, does not breach current Australian law. However, there are other serious considerations.<br><strong>How can I protect my brand online?</strong> <br><em>Legal solutions</em> <br>First, choose a brand that is clearly distinguishable from your competitors can be easier to protect and defend.<br>Second, include a copyright notice in your website terms that sets out your intellectual property rights. Your website terms can include permissible and prohibited use of your website.<br>Third, consider registering variations of your main domain name. There is no restriction on the number of domain names that a registrant can license, but bear in mind auDA policy for .au domain names.<br>Register your business trade mark to give you the exclusive right to use this trade mark as a brand name for the products or services specific in your registration. This is Australia wide protection.<br>Check for infringement. You can regularly check variations of your branding and trade marks, to see if a competitor is using your branding or trade marks.<br><em>Practical solutions</em> <br>Andre Weyher, marketing director, has two key strategies to help you get found online:<br><ul> <li>Site building:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>A correctly constructed website<strong>&nbsp;</strong>is a huge element of good organic rankings. Make sure that you choose your meta titles, descriptions and headers carefully. Include your brand name as often as you can, invest time on social media. If you run your site properly, the only traffic you should lose are the users that type in the wrong domain by accident. </li><li>Link outreach:<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Good organic rankings includes other sites linking in to yours. The more websites that link to yours, the more trust Google gives your site and helps it rank higher. </li></ul>', 'Several methods which can help protect your brand online', 'Legal - choose a clearly distinguishable brand, include a copyright notice in your website terms, consider registering variations of your main domain name. Practical - site building, link outreach.', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 5, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(164, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 94, 'http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/the-legalities-of-opening-an-online-shop-20140515-38bgy.html', '2014-05-15 00:00:00', 'The legalities of opening an online shop', '', '<strong>They Sydney Morning Herald - The legalities of opening an online shop</strong><br><a href="http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/the-legalities-of-opening-an-online-shop-20140515-38bgy.html" target="_blank">http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/the-legalities-of-opening-an-online-shop-20140515-38bgy.html</a> <br>Do you love boutique products and want to be your own boss? Many Australian sole traders and small companies set up online shops. <br>Founders bring a passion for their products and a commitment to great service. But are your legals covered? Lack of legal advice and documents means that you may inadvertently breach the law, including copyright law, the consumer law and the amended privacy laws. The risks include having to cease business, pay damages and pay fines.<br><strong>What content can I use on my website?</strong> <br>You need to either own, or be licensed to use, content on your website. You own content that you create, including copy you write, photos you take, and blogs you write for your website.<br>If you use third party material, you need the right to use it. If content has been created for you, you should get an assignment in writing. Alternatively, you can license content, for example purchasing a license to use stock photos.  &nbsp;<br><strong>What legal documents does my online shop need?</strong><br><ul> <li>Website Terms of Use: These apply to every visitor to your website. These set out how users can use your website, prohibited conduct, republishing rules, and a disclaimer to limit your liability for your website.</li><li>Privacy Policy: Your privacy policy states how your business will deal with personal information collected on the website. This includes what personal information you collect, disclose, store and use, including for direct marketing. It also sets out the information owner&rsquo;s rights, including to complain about a breach of privacy law and to unsubscribe from your direct marketing.</li><li>Sales Terms and Conditions: These apply to every customer. These need to cover practical information, including purchase, ordering and delivery. Well-drafted terms also protect your business interests, with a disclaimer and limitation of liability, setting out your maximum liability and what you are not liable for. </li></ul><strong>How do I protect my website intellectual property? </strong> <br>Your website contains valuable intellectual property, including descriptions of products, images and any blog content.&nbsp; Your Website Terms of Use should protect your intellectual property and set out permissible and prohibited conduct. <br><strong>How do I comply with Australian Consumer Law?</strong> <br>If you sell good to consumers you must comply with mandatory legal obligations. These include to sell goods of an acceptable quality, make sure that the goods are as described on your website, make sure the goods are fit for the purpose they are being sold for.<br>You need to handle customer complaints as required by the consumer guarantees in the Australian Consumer Law.&nbsp; Purchasers are entitled to a replacement or a refund for a major failure and for compensation for other reasonably foreseeable loss or damage. <br>To conclude, developing your boutique business baby is a labour of love. Addressing the legal side will protect your interests. This helps safeguard the time and money you have invested, and gives your business a strong foundation for growth.', 'The legal side you need to address when opening an online store', 'What content can I use on my website? What legal documents does my online shop need? How do I protect my website intellectual property? How do I comply with Australian Consumer Law?', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 6, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(165, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 94, 'http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/three-questions-to-ask-before-you-launch-an-online-marketplace-or-community-14052014.html', '2014-05-14 00:00:00', 'Three questions to ask before you launch an online marketplace or community', '', '<strong>Dynamic Business - Three questions to ask before you launch an online marketplace or community</strong><br><a href="http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/three-questions-to-ask-before-you-launch-an-online-marketplace-or-community-14052014.html" target="_blank">http://dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/three-questions-to-ask-before-you-launch-an-online-marketplace-or-community-14052014.html</a> <br>Marketplaces are bringing unique ideas to market. Do you have an innovative idea for a marketplace? Before you launch an own online marketplace or community, ask yourself these three key questions:<br><strong>1.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>What are the legal relationships?</strong> <br>To set up a marketplace, you need to be clear on what the marketplace will offer, who will participate and why.<br>Who is the buyer? Who is the&nbsp;<a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/news/etsy-launches-new-sellers-only-app-29042014.html" target="_blank">seller</a>? What are the legal relationships between you, the buyer and the seller?<br>You need to be clear on the rights and obligations of each party in each relationship. &nbsp;Your sellers must have the right to sell their product or service, must provide accurate descriptions, and must fulfill the obligation to sell the product or service. <br>You need well-drafted business terms and conditions to clarify the relationships, to minimise and deal with <a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/featured/small-business-welcomes-creation-of-new-ombudsman-02052014.html" target="_blank">disputes</a>, and to limit your liability.<br><strong>2.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>How does the money flow?</strong> <br>You need to decide how money will move between the parties. How will you get paid? How will buyers pay? How will sellers receive funds? <br>Questions to ask are:<br><ul> <li>Will users pay a fee to use your marketplace?</li><li>Will you receive commission from buyers when they purchase a product or service through your website?</li><li>Will you receive the total payment, then pay a portion to the seller?</li><li>Alternatively, will you receive a fee, then the buyer and seller interact and pay directly?</li><li>How will payments be made?</li></ul><strong>3.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>What are the intellectual property rights and issues?</strong> <br>First, you need to ensure that your business&nbsp;<a href="http://www.dynamicbusiness.com.au/entrepreneur-profile/the-prenup-for-co-founders-26112013.html" target="_blank">intellectual property</a> is protected. You need to own or have the right to use your business name, logo, and any other branding. <br>Your marketplace terms and conditions need to state that the material on your marketplace is owned or licensed by you. &nbsp;The market standard approach is that users have a right to use the marketplace, but no rights to reproduce, use or modify your material, unless expressly agreed.<br>The terms should address user content. Your sellers must warrant that the descriptions they provide of goods or services for sale, are accurate and complete. Your buyers must warrant that they will uphold their end of the bargain, e.g. pay the price bid.', 'Understand your online marketplace by asking these 3 questions', 'What are the legal relationships? How does the money flow? What are the intellectual property rights and issues?', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 6, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(166, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 98, 'http://www.theage.com.au/small-business/finance/creating-a-business-prenup-20140414-36mxg.html', '2014-04-14 00:00:00', 'Creating a business pre-nup', '', '<strong>The Age - Creating a business pre-nup</strong><br><a href="http://www.theage.com.au/small-business/finance/creating-a-business-prenup-20140414-36mxg.html" target="_blank">http://www.theage.com.au/small-business/finance/creating-a-business-prenup-20140414-36mxg.html</a> <br>Businesses with two or more co-founders bring twice the skills, time and passion to launch and grow an enterprise. But co-founder disputes occur relatively frequently. Which is why it&rsquo;s essential to structure shareholders agreement that clarify roles, how much time each party will dedicate to the business, how disputes are resolved and what happens when one partner wishes to leave.<br><strong>What does a shareholders agreement cover? </strong> <br>A shareholders agreement is the roadmap between the shareholders.&nbsp; The particular issues relevant to employee-shareholders include what are your roles and responsibilities, who can appoint directors, new issues of shares, what to do if a shareholder-employee leaves and how to restrict competition with the business.<br><strong>When should we create one?</strong> <br>A shareholders agreement is usually created at the start of a new business venture. It is wise to sit down at an early stage to discuss how things will work between the co-founders. <br><strong>Shares are remuneration, what if my co-founder stops working? </strong> <br>New businesses are often not able to pay market salaries. Founders often receive shares in lieu of salary.&nbsp; <br>How do you ensure your co-founder does the work they were brought on to do?&nbsp; You can agree duties up front, but you may not want to be too precise, as new businesses need flexible staff. A better approach is to agree goals, broad areas and time commitments. <br><strong>I&rsquo;m working for shares, can I be diluted?</strong> <br>Employee shareholders may give up considerable salaries to work in the new business. Shares are an important part of their decision. The shareholders&rsquo; agreement should set out how new shares can be issued. <br><strong>We&rsquo;ve had a falling out, what happens to the shares? &nbsp;</strong> <br>It is wise to agree in advance what you will do if you cannot work together.&nbsp; A well-advised company will agree how shares will be sold and the valuation. You can agree a valuation formula, or say that an accountant will decide the value at the time.<br><strong>How do I protect our business when a key employee leaves?</strong> <br>A well-drafted shareholders agreement can address this. It should include clauses relating to not competing with the company, not soliciting clients, not poaching employees and not interfering with supplier relationships.&nbsp;<br>Starting a business with co-founders can be the difference between one person having an idea and a team celebrating a successful business launch. Your co-founders can be the difference between failure and success. Agree the ground rules and the road-map early, in a comprehensive shareholders agreement. With the comfort of a strong foundation, you and your co-founders can focus on your business growth and success.', 'The structure of a shareholder agreement', 'What does a shareholders agreement cover? When should we create one? Shares are remuneration, what if my co-founder stops working? IÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢m working for shares, can I be diluted? WeÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ve had a falling out, what happens to the shares? How do I protect our business when a key employee leaves?', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 5, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(167, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 94, 'http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/new-privacy-laws-are-you-ready-20140307-34bbq.html', '2014-03-17 00:00:00', 'New privacy laws: are you ready?', '', '<strong>The Sydney Morning Herald - New privacy laws: are you ready?</strong><br><a href="http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/new-privacy-laws-are-you-ready-20140307-34bbq.html" target="_blank">http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/trends/new-privacy-laws-are-you-ready-20140307-34bbq.html</a> <br>From 12 March a new set of privacy principles regarding the handling of personal information came into effect. These are the Australian Privacy Principles. The big changes relate to how businesses handle, use, and store personal information and engage in direct marketing. <br><strong>Do privacy laws apply to my business?</strong> <br>Your business will be affected by the changes to the privacy laws if you handle personal information and you generate more than $3 million in annual turnover or generate less than $3 million but you fit under a second set of criteria. <br><strong>Does your business trade in personal information?</strong> <br>Many small businesses trade in personal information. This is information that identifies, or could reasonably identify, an individual. This includes names, addresses, dates of birth and bank account details.<br><strong>What are the key reforms?</strong> <br>The key reforms relevant to small businesses, particularly in the online space, require:<br><ul type="disc"> <li>that your privacy policy addresses specific topics. </li><li>that you have procedures and systems in place to ensure you comply with the new law.</li></ul>The other big change is that there are fines for breaching the news laws for serious or repeated breaches of the Privacy Act. <br><strong>How do I comply?</strong><br><ul type="disc"> <li>Do a quick audit: review your business to identify where and how you deal with personal information.</li><li>Get a system in place: establish or revise procedures and systems so your staff that handle personal information comply with the privacy law changes. </li><li>Provide a&nbsp;privacy notice: when you collect personal information, inform individuals of details including your organisation''s name, contact details, the purpose of collection and to whom it will be disclosed. </li><li>Sort out your privacy policy: make sure your privacy policy addresses the required topics. These includes what personal information you collect, how you collect it and the purposes for which you use and disclose it. Finally, you need to set out how you secure and store personal information.</li></ul><strong>How do the changes affect direct marketing?</strong> <br>You can use personal information for direct marketing if your business collected it, you disclose that you may use it for direct marketing and you provide a way for people to unsubscribe.<br><strong>What rights does an individual have?</strong> <br>You need to give individuals the right to access their personal information and correct out of date or incorrect information. You need a process to deal with complaints about your compliance with the Australian Privacy Principles. If you send direct marketing material, you need to give each individual a way to opt-out.&nbsp;<br><strong>To wrap up</strong> <br>The Privacy Act has been around for many years - it''s just had a revamp. Complying is not difficult. Follow these tips to get your privacy policy in order and have procedures and systems to comply with the new law.', 'Key tips for small businesses to comply with the new privacy law', 'Do a quick audit. Get a system in place. Provide a privacy notice. Sort out your privacy policy.', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 8, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0),
(168, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 98, 'http://www.startupdaily.com.au/2013/07/losing-control-5-issues-to-consider-when-bringing-an-investor-into-your-startup/', '2013-07-24 00:00:00', 'Losing Control - 5 Issues to Consider When Bringing an Investor into your Startup', '', '<strong>Startup Daily &ndash; Losing Control &ndash; 5 Issues to Consider When Bringing an Investor into your Startup</strong><br><a href="http://www.startupdaily.com.au/2013/07/losing-control-5-issues-to-consider-when-bringing-an-investor-into-your-startup/" target="_blank">http://www.startupdaily.com.au/2013/07/losing-control-5-issues-to-consider-when-bringing-an-investor-into-your-startup/</a><br>This article sets out the five key questions you should ask yourself when negotiating a Shareholders Agreement. In particular, it discusses:<br>What rights, power and obligations will you and the investor have?<br>How will you break a deadlock?<br>What to do if a Shareholder wants to sell?<br>Who has rights to appoint and remove a Director?<br>Will the investor have the right to appoint a Director? This is likely to be a threshold requirement for the investor.<br>Who can remove a Director? The investor&rsquo;s right to appoint a Director is compromised if the founder can remove the investor&rsquo;s Director.<br>What voting power and rights will each Director have?<br>The Company is managed by or under the direction of the Board of Directors. Generally, the Board makes decisions, unless the <a href="https://legalvision.com.au/documents/shareholders-agreement/" target="_blank">Shareholders Agreement</a>, Constitution or Rules says a decision must be made by the Shareholders at a General Meeting.<br>It is crucial to determine what power each Director has, including:<br><br>Will each Director have 1 vote, or will their voting power reflect their percentage shareholding?<br>If each Director has 1 vote, in a 2 Director company, how will you break a dead-lock? See point 3 below.<br>If Director&rsquo;s votes reflect their shareholding, what can the majority Director decide alone? What requires a unanimous vote, i.e. both Directors?<br><br>How to break a dead-lock between Directors?<br>What to do if you cannot resolve a dispute? This can be addressed in the Shareholders&rsquo; Agreement. Some solutions are:<br>(a)Require the parties to meet to resolve the issue, i.e. first the Directors meet, then (if different people) the Shareholders meet. What if the dispute is still not resolved?<br>(b)Agree in advance that you will be bound by the decision made at alternative dispute resolution. What if you do not want to go to a third party?<br>(c)The majority Shareholder can buy out the minority Shareholder at an agreed price, e.g. fair market value as determined by an independent valuer. The risk is that the majority Shareholder will refuse to agree a solution, to trigger this clause. The benefit is that it gives a way forward if there is a severe relationship breakdown. <br>Please note: A&nbsp;<a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/cth/consol_act/ca2001172/s9.html" target="_blank">Director</a>&nbsp;must exercise their powers and discharge their duties with a reasonable degree of care and diligence, in good faith in the best&nbsp;<a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/cth/consol_act/ca2001172/s601waa.html" target="_blank">interests</a>&nbsp;of the Company and for a proper purpose.<br>What decisions will the Board make, as compared to Management?<br>The Shareholders Agreement sets out how often the Board meets and what they decide. If you are an Executive Director you may prefer more decisions to be made by management. <br>What if the investor wants to sell?<br>The founder needs rights so they are not left with an unfamiliar and possibly adverse shareholder. Protections include:<br>(a)Right of first refusal, so the founder or the company has first option to purchase the investor&rsquo;s shares;<br>(bTag-along rights, so the founder &lsquo;tags-along&rsquo; with the purchase, at the same price that the buyer is paying for the investor&rsquo;s shares, which generally must be no less than market price.<br>In conclusion, the right investor can transform a start-up. Taking the time to agree a Shareholders Agreement, to negotiate key issues, settle key terms, and set out a road map, builds a strong foundation for a successful relationship.', '5 Key questions you should ask yourself when negotiating a Shareholders Agreement', 'What rights, power and obligations will you and the investor have? How will you break a deadlock? What to do if a Shareholder wants to sell? Who has rights to appoint and remove a Director? What voting power and rights will each Director have?', 'Ursula Hogben', 194, 26, '2014-12-01 09:52:15', '2014-12-01 09:52:15', 0);
